comment_Rating: After all these years, now I can say he is the best prof in my life I wish I had a chance to get other classes from him again. You value his teaching more after you have time to digest all you learn in his class.
He is awesome. One of the best ever if not the best.
awesome prof
i didnt know econ could be this much fun!
He is awesome, understood it while taking other classes and after start working. Extremely helpful and good looking prof.
very useful course from an awesome professor
he has an accent but you get used to it, other than that he is terrific
Best professor ever
Very easy...don't take anyone else for Principles of Economics

Terrific teacher, who is not easy specifically because he challenges his students to think deeply and clearly.  In other words, everything one could want in a teacher.  I have carried for a lifetime the insights he catalyzed.
Excellent elucidation of original sources. A true scholar.

Chris was a very clever, thoughtful professor of Classical political science. Unlike many professors, he never disguised his opinions as 'facts' or pretended that he didn't have his opinions. Great guy to talk to.
Had him freshman year - Bruell and Landy - studying Plato all semester.  Both are brilliant.  Great stories.
Can be hard to follow at times, but always is perfectly clear when you look over your notes

Prof. Faulkner is a great professor. He has a dynamic lecturing style which makes what could be dry material exciting and enjoyable. He is brilliant, but never condescending. Really cares about students' thoughts on material and what they're doing outside of class. Definitely try to take Faulkner.

He is AWESOME! He's a great man and he's super friendly. He is obviously a genius, but never makes his students feel beneath him. He is open to new ideas and comments. He actually made political theory not suck. He is a fair grader and very approachable should you need help. His lectures can be a little boring, but go asyou like no attendencepolicy
Very helpful.
No Comments
No Comments
Prof. Doherty inspired me to pursue a career as a writer, which I've been doing now for 35 years. Great guy.
Prof. Doherty was one of the best teachers I had as an undergraduate, and now 20 years later, I'm *still* using things I learned in his class. Very inventive, and very personable.

Professor Doherty was one of the best teachers i ever had at BC as an undergraduate, friendly, willing to talk to you outside class, and inventive in the classroom. i was never bored as i was in so many other classes.
AWESOME TEACHER
Himes assigns a lot of reading, but he's wonderful so it's worth it.  Just a word of caution - he does not respond well to email.  So, if you need anything from him, be sure to ask in person.

Keepin' it real! It is rare to find someone who speaks as well as he does: passionate, insightful, and daring both in the classroom and on the pulpit. Had him as an undergrad at ND in the 90's. Wonderful to see that he's still got it.
I had Fr. Himes for class when he taught at Notre Dame. Great theologian and teacher. If you can't take his class, go to a mass he is celebrating.
by far the best professor and mentor i have ever had.  you should not leave BC w/o taking a course from him.  incredible.

The best two professors I had at BC were Fr. Himes for Theology and Fr. Flanagan for Philosophy - and there are barely any priests still teaching.  Himes is brilliant.  I'm not Catholic and I still went to Wednesday Mass at St. Mary's to hear his sermons.
Best teacher I ever had, and I had him in 1988.
I had this man 20 years ago.  He is still one of the best teacher i ever had

Pete is absolutely wonderful. Taking this class was like having my grandfather teach me accounting, and having him do it amazingly at that. Do NOT think twice about taking Pete and do NOT let his workload scare you away; you'll be a better person for it in the end. PETE IS THE BEST PROFESSOR IN CSOM!
If you can take a class with him, do it. You'll learn more in 1 day than you will in a semester with most profs.
GREAT.
Best accounting professor
Pete is the greatest professor I have ever had.  He has taught lessons regarding accounting and life in general and was very effective doing both.

Worst teacher at BC. Lectures are incredibly boring. He literally repeats everything from the previous class. Def passionate about Cuba which is cool, but I was bored about my mind every class. Highly recommend taking another teacher.

He was an interesting guy, and I enjoyed how he conducted class. I have a hard time accepting such enthusiasm for Cuba as a political and economic model that he seemed to convey. Doesn't mesh well either with the fact that 20% of that country emigrated, or with what I saw when I visited. Seems like a good guy though
possibly the worst prof i had at bc.  i knew more about this subject then he did.  ended up going to class **** just to make it more exciting
I had prof taylor for 3 classes.  He was a good teacher and very approachable.  I learned a lot and highly recommend him.
I had Frank for an independent study.  It was very informative and interesting.  He is a great lecturer and he speaks to you as an equal when you see him one on one.  He is an asset to BC.
A pleasant professor whose no-nonsense attitude towards her teaching and grading methods fosters excellence in students. If you work hard and come to class you should do well.
Can be a bit hard on Papers, but a truly nice professor who actually takes the time to listen and get to know her students. I really enjoyed her class.
Let's put it this way - for a full year, I was in a class of less than 20 students and she never learned my name.

Prof Wilson is an amazing professor. I took Narrative and Interpretation and Literature and Journalism in America. I graduated two years ago, but I was the student who was always looking for the hardest/most life-changing professor. His classes challenged the ways I think, read, and write in a fundamental way. Best prof I had at BC.

Super nice guy, but he graded way too hard, considering he was very vague about exactly what it was he wanted on each assignment. Class discussion was usually relatively boring. I would not recommend this class if you want to learn or get a good grade.
Professor Wilson is a pretty tough grader, but a great teacher.  He pushes you to improve as a student, thinker, and writer.  Great teacher, just don't expect an easy grade.
Great guy, great teacher.

I took as many classes with Profeccor Wilson as possible while I was at BC. He chose books that were not typical and made you think about things in entirely new ways. He was always willing to help in office hours and always had interesting class discussions.

I had Chris Wilsona few years back for a grad course.  He was very unhelpful and unclear about what he wanted.  He would say one thing and rade your work on another criteria.  I really got the impression he was looking for what he wanted you to write.  Many friends felt the same way.

I had him for a non-fiction writing class. The books he had us read really opened my eyes to the art of nonfiction and also inspired me to write my own essays. He was what I always wanted out of a college professor: Someone who is enthusiastic, super knowledgable, and generally good fun.

Brilliant, down to earth, and cares about students.  Thinks about things like not ordering huge anthologies no one want to read from or carry.  Welcoming in office hours.  Realisitic but firm about deadlines.  A real teacher.
Wow, horrible teacher. She made a painstakingly boring movie that was shown on PBS, is that supposed to make me excited?
Extremely professional.
No Comments
She rocks my world!!

She is the balm!! I was in the presence of greatness. She inspired me to come every week and participate. The coursework was intriguing--I couldn't concentrate on anything else!! She is amazing--god's gift to Academia!!
It's clear that she loves English, and she'll make you love it (or at least understand the lit), too
Professor Defusco is great!  She is very knowledgeable and extremely helpful.  I always enjoyed her interesting classes.

Had her for a summer course called Hopes and Promises of New England Writers. Class was easy and interesting. For the test she would read us 50 or so review questions that were the exact same as the test (and the multiple choice answers). She's an easy A, and not boring. Not the most reflective class, but you will learn some.

Not sure if previous poster took the same prof as I did? Excellent professor--lectures interjected with humor. Intelligent but not elitist. Readily available outside of class. Best lecture on Shakespeare i've had.
She is really awesome and she keeps the class motivated.  She is funny and makes you look foward to her classes.  She also helps you when you need it and is understanding.
Great Professor.  Brought current events into the class and really kept class interesting!
Andrea is by far the best professor at BC.  Friendly and down to earth.

Instead of giving the class over to a professor who is actually able to teach, he continues to waste everyone's time. Needlessly high amount of quizzes, pointlessly difficult exams. Would be better to take the course with someone else.

Hes is a tough Professor, but is highly respected in his field. He truly wants the best for his students and will help you in any way possible (so dont be afraid to talk to him). His tests a very unique and require lots of studying, but I promise its worth it. TAKE ADVANTAGE OF OFFICE HOURS (they are so helpful)! Overall fantastic Professor.

comment_Rating: Choose someone else

It's general chemistry. You should take anyone else. He takes pride in his classes undeserved reputation for toughness and tries to convince students that his class will prepare people for Organic Chemistry better than others. It won't. That's just Stockholm syndrome.

He cares so much for his students, it is not an easy class by any means but so worth it. He has such a sarcastic/blunt sense of humor that makes going to class tolerable. Going to his office hours is a life saver and he is someone you really want to get to know.

Professor Wolfman dedicates so much time and effort to his students. He is really here to teach and will do what he can to help you connect with the material. The course is not easy and requires lots of work and attention but Professor Wolfman is always looking to work with students to help them understand the course.

By far the most difficult class I've ever taken, but I would take it again 100 times if I could. I got a C- first semester, and an A- second. What made all the difference was going to Wolfman's office hours and getting to know him. He learned 105 names for a lecture class and I'm so glad mine was one of them.
He is extremely helpful. His humor makes it easier to pay attention. He really, truly cares for his students.

This class actually makes you think. You have to be able to apply chemistry principles, rather than just learn how to solve different problems. If you're willing to put the effort in, this class is worth it.

An amazing teacher but extremely difficult. I had had no background in chemistry and was failing the class so I had to withdraw. Does not give enough time on tests and the weekly quizzes can be very difficult. I learned a lot in his class. I am sorry to be leaving.

NO NO NO NO NO NO. He is a great man and i do truly believe that he wants his students to learn, but the class is extremely difficult. save ur gpa and get into ANY other chem. only take this class if u r serious about getting into chemistry. if u just want to get into med school, STEER CLEAR

Dr. Wolfman is the best professor I've ever had. He makes an effort to get to know all of his students (which is saying something for a class of up to 200!). I learned a TON in his class and was very well prepared for Organic Chem the next year.

If you attend class and keep up with the online homework you will understand everything. If you attend office hours, Professor Wolfman makes an effort to get to know you, and office hours are the way to get a good grade in his class. He is such a nice teacher!

It's a very hard class, but not because he makes it hard.  The content is simply difficult.  He plays music before class, does a pretty decent job of keeping over 150 students focused, and I have honestly never had a professor who genuinely cared and truly wants everyone to succeed.  He curves well too and he counts your lowest exam grade for half.
He is one of the greatest prof. ever. Funny and keeps class interesting.
Wolfman was a great professor but you definitely had to go to class and do lots of problems.
For the love of God, don't take him.

Very funny, but too fast in lectures, and review. he uses alot of examples, but he goes through them very quickly.  Somtimes does experaments in front of the class, which are always intresting and entertainging, brings science into the world by speaking about intresting scientific discoveries and events. overall a nice, funy, and entertaining prof.

Prof. Wolfman explains the material very clearly during lectures. His office hours are extremely helpful. His tests are the hardest among the gen. chem. professors, but you really are able to understand the concepts behind the questions you are being asked.
He's obviously brilliant, but tends to make things way more confusing than necessary. Don't even bother trying to listen to his lectures. Read the textbook and take notes from that.
Basically, I don't even listen to anything he says in class (read the book instead) and I think I do better that way cause his lectures are confusing beyond belief.

Extremely patient and helpful. If it were not for him, I wouldn't have graduated in '80.

Excellent teacher.  Very smart! I wish I could have gotten him when I register to do my bachelor. Prof. Carpenter you are a genious.

comment_Rating: He was one of the nicest professors Ive had. Immediately, you can tell how passionate he is about his job, which is great when it comes to discussions and asking questions. Hes also very understanding and helpful, so dont be afraid to introduce yourself. Would take again.

The entire time I was taking his class I thought he was incredibly unqualified to do his job. He was teaching Ovid without knowing anything about Greek or Latin language or myth. He basically just memorized a wiki page of facts and made assumptions. He forces you to change your writing entirely without reading your essays. Dont take his class.

Amazing, inspiring teacher. The work load was manageable but engaging, and I throughly enjoyed the readings. His class was totally discussion based, with four outside of class papers. He is one of the most engaging, intellectual, and compassionate professors at Boston College.  It is too bad that he does not teach more classes!

John Anderson has a passion for the literature and poetry he teaches, which becomes quite obvious after a few moments of talking to him. His discussions in class are intriguing and engaging. I only wish I could have taken more of his classes.

Excellent. He truly cares about you as a student.
mid, neither good nor bad, lectures could be boring but a really nice and caring professor

comment_Rating: Really engaging lectures, obviously very passionate about the subject. Easier grader when it comes to papers. A midterm and final test with questions for 70% of the test provided before hand. Kind of a lot of reading, but pretty interesting and lead to really interesting class discussions.

Honestly, among my favorite classes at this school thus far. She presented a hearty and appropriate course with all of the historical goodies and contemporary issues intact, discussions never failed to be entertaining. It can be abstruse if you're only beginning however- the Schelling readings notably.
I had her in 2001 for Romanticism and Idealism- she is a great professor, very open to feedback and discussion. A fantastic teacher and a wonderful person!
I had her back in 95/95 for a class on Romanticism. Smart, fun to listen to, encouraging, and a unique class that explored the philosophy of the romanticism. Some strange readings, but a fun class.

Pro. Ames is a really good teacher, he explains things very well. There is a fair amount of work, but he is a pretty easier grader.

Professor Bodenheimer knows a lot about her subject and just has a wonderful passion for literature. She makes class interesting and relate-able by making us look at maps to see where the characters in the novel live and work.
Excellent Professor! I had a concussion late in the semester and she was very considerate in making sure I didn't get behind!
Honestly, shes a hard teacher who is pretty condescending and always tries to assert that she is better than you. Her class was fun and I learned alot, but she is not the nicest person to deal with
professor Lydenberg made me realize that poetry is the highest form of self expression.

Retired a while back, but still occasionally teaches, I believe.  Wonderful teacher; took two grad courses w/ him.  Enthusiastic, knowledgeable and a truly decent human being.  If you get a chance to take a course w/ him, or even attend a talk by him, do so!

I took Professor Boesky for Introduction to Medical Humanities. I could not recommend her more. She is my favorite professor at BC. She is extremely knowledgable and inspirational. She makes me want to be a better person. Take her class!!!

I had Prof Boesky for Intro to Medical Humanities. She is one of the best professors whom I have had thus far at BC, thanks to her helpfulness, her passion, and her ability to engage a lecture that is intriguing, educational, and unique. I genuinely feel that I have grown in my understanding of Medical Humanities, thanks to Prof Boesky's teaching.
Professor Boesky was wonderful! She is engaged with the material and actually cares about teaching.

She tries hard, but lectures totally lack direction and clarity.  Not difficult but hard to get an A.  MAkes material that is potentially interesting fairly boring.  Definately teaches style over substance, which is ok if you like that.
I took an Irish Gothic english course with Professor Howes and truly enjoyed her class. She was engaging and related the content to relevant social and historical issues and concepts.

Not everyone is a brilliant or creative scholar.  There is something to be said for showing up, being kind, being organized, and having a firm grasp of information and concepts.  Yes, there is a kind of murmuring, and maybe to some degree a lack of confidence.  But she knows her stuff, she's solid, she's fair, & she's not a grandstanding Priapus.
Marjorie Howes is incredibly intelligent and personable.
She rambles through readings, not really teaching anything, letting everyone talk but not really clarifying one thing.  Waste of my time.
Incredibly disorganized.  Very knowledgeable and a good person.  If you can get over his lack of organization, you will enjoy his classes.

Prof. Kern is closed-minded in his discussion and will grade papers based on opinion, not necessarily on the writing itself.  He shoots down any thoughts that are "out of the box" which is absurd for a poetry class.  I find him to me a terrible teacher and a jerk, at that.  Do Not Recommend!
I graduated in 1998, but I remember Prof. Kern being, as the previous reviewer said, very enthusiastic, if a bit unstructured.  I enjoyed his classes and thought he graded fairly.

Ohhhh....why are these ratings so mean?? His interest in what he's teaching is wonderful.  I found him very nice, helpful, & enthusiastic about students' ideas. Certainly there was some lack of structure but, come on, it's an English class - lots of freeform discussion. I found his grading & comments on papers fair & thoughtful.

This class was painful: boring, BORING, BORING. He speaks in monotone, relies on students to structure the class with their comments (except never gives any critique of what they say), and grades the papers pretty harsh (it's fairly easy to get a B, but difficult to get an A). He just sucks. Take someone else.
Just rambles and never gets through all the material. He's very unclear about what he expects. Unapproachable and a tough marker. Not recommended.
Excellent professor: She is knowledgeable and helpful to her students.  She is quite useful to graduate students taking exams.
A great, high-energy professor who is always willing to try new ideas out and help you grow as a thinker. Fabulous!

Phil O'Leary is an excellent professor with encyclopedic knowledge of and passion for his subject matter. Interested and engaged students should not have a problem comprehending his lectures. It is particularly helpful if you have some understanding of Irish history and literature. He was one of my favorite professors while I was at Boston College.

Unprofessionally disorganized, distracted and unavailable. His communication skills are poor and it is uncertain as to what his expectations are. A VERY intelligent and erudite individual who clearly enjoys the material but lacks the ability to engage students because of his remote attitude. Unfortunate!

His notes are yellowed from years of use. His voice is tired, and soon you will find so are you. He is supremely boring and thinks he knows everything about everything. He's not a super tough grader (most people get Bs), but lecture is just so painful.

Great guy and fellow Mainer. Really approachable and easy to talk to. Gives amazing feedback and you can tell he really cares. I have learned so much from him this year. Once of my favorite teachers by far.
good professor who really cares about his students.  one of the better professors i've experienced at Boston College

Lad is the best! - Currenly am teaching high school and had for a couple of writing classes. Probably the only teacher at BC that cared about his students. I still keep in touch with him and he has helped me to bring life to my teaching at the high school level. He is my hero! Take his class - You will love him.

The best teacher I've ever had. Savvy -- asks students to talk to each other (he won't make eye contact so that students will be forced to converse with one another), challenges you to think about your pedagogy by "doing" your pedagogy, cares about the emotional energy of the writing class, encourages you to cultivate your own teaching philosophy

Lad is an excellent teacher. I had him in his Composition / Theory Writing Class at the Grad Level. He knows his stuff and he helped connect me back to the roots of writing with his books and seminars. Take his class! - One of the best!

Prof Mathieu was extremely caring and sympathetic towards students. She understood that students had a lot going on outside of class and did her best to minimize coursework. Any work that we did do she would always check in with us to make sure we felt it was meaningful. She does take attendance.

She's really nice and helpful. She let us grade our own work. Her feedback was very great and help me better improve as a write. She was really kind and gave the class extensions. She really listened to us as students and what we needed help with.
A bit disorganized.  I wasn't a huge fan of her class.  She didn't grab me as a teacher.  She wasn't very engaging.

Could have taken this as independent study and learned more about pedagogical theories. Lacked the structure of a graduate course. Time wasted on personal interests rather than the material. Define irony: a course without a structure attempting to teach how to structure college courses and syllabi.
great communicater, smart and very interesting, it doesnt hurt that shes beutiful

Paula is a very talented professor.  She is also helpfull when you are in the process of revising your papers....BUT...be aware that this class is NOT an easy A...you have to be a ver talented writer in order to get even an A-.  The class goes by quick...and she is always open for suggestions.
She is fabulous.  Rocks my world.  So smart.
Very fair and a great person
very fair if you can write well and articulate your thoughts.

knowledgeable but not great at teaching. exams are exceedingly hard but actual classwork is misleadingly simple. i memorized a lot and did well on the exams but feel like i didn't learn the actual subject

Professor Kelly is past his prime. He seems to knowledgable on the topic, but fails to communicate properly with the students. He has lots of "relevant" examples applicable to the "real" world, but even these tend to be extremely dated. The exams are getting increasingly difficult, even though he posts practice exams that are misleadingly easy.

Best professor I ever had at B.C. If you take organic chem, I HIGHLY recommend T. Ross.
Focused on memorization instead of teaching concepts, making this class dull and tedious.

Great guy, great teacher. Makes really complicated concepts easy to understand. You can tell he's really applied the stuff in the real world. Definitely take him.

Excellent!!

He wrote the book, so text and lecture are virtually identical.  Classes are 300 people, so just pure lecture, no questions allowed.  Funny anecdotes, good research, good speaker.  Optional discussion was worth very little, so not worth going.  Two assignments: midterm and final.

Tricky Dick Tresch was one of the greatest professors I ever had.  He wrote the book, so obviously lecture's gonna be similar.  There's a reason he won state teacher of the year...twice.

I took Tresch for macro.. probably the hardest class ever. You should either go to class or read the book, but not both. I found reading the book to be helpful, but I still suffered. The classes are rather large and you typically have a discussion group.

Prof. Babb is super sweet and cares about her students. She grades on a variety of things, so don't worry too much about a singular assignment (drops lowest grades in certain categories). She gives pop quizzes but they are only one/two written question(s) --- focus on the abstract/thesis and findings. Take her class!

Spread out grading: tests, quizzes, HW, papers, participation so if you drop one it doesn't completely ruin your grade. Super nice and lenient if you are respectful and participate. Follow HW directions closely
ratingTags_Rating: BEWARE OF POP QUIZZES--Clear grading criteria

comment_Rating: explains material very clearly. fyi- tests rely mostly on class notes not readings.

Incredible professor. Had him for models of politics and he was very engaging as a lecturer. The material is very interesting and he is always willing to answer questions if you are confused. One of my favorite polysci professors ever.

Prof. Hayao is friendly and the class is straightforward. As long as you come to class consistently, you'll get all the info you need for exams, he even tells you what questions to expect in advance. Readings are long and dense but you should be able to get by without doing all of them. Make sure to start on the term paper early in the semester

comment_Rating: Professor Hayao is really sweet, the material is easy to grasp and he goes over it a lot in the lectures. He gives some unclear direction on the papers so meeting with him is helpful. Overall really nice guy who is interested in what he teaches

While the 'Fundamental Concepts' classes range in difficulty and workload for each professor, Hayao was very fair in terms of grading and gave multiple opportunities to lift one's grade. It is a reliable class.

Politics of Japan and Korea is an easy A- but a really tough A. Professor Hayao is a great lecturer but has highly specific grading criteria. Also can repeat himself a bit, but the class is overall straightforward. There are a lot of readings but they really are necessary to do well on the tests.
Basically a straight lecture of the readings. Nice guy.

Kelly now teaches at University of San Diego, he gives no tests (except final) or homework, although in order to be prepared for class you have to read the readings, & you have to write 2 essays at the end of semester. Hes very contradictory & does know his material but makes offensive assumptions about students. Would not take unless Phil major.
Had him has a visting professor and he was fantastic. Really dug into material, great balance of lecture and discussion. Always super helpful and crystal clear about instructions. Highly recommended.
Good professor, keeps class engaged and is sincerely committed to making sure everyone understands material.
Very energic & personable.  Makes cass interesting.  Always available and concerned that everyone is getting the material.  Makes sometimes boring topics interesting.

Very insightful professor.  Brings probing questions to class.  I always feel challenged after leaving his class.   The best is that he is always available for extra help and review sessions.  Great professor!  Definitely take his class.

Great professor!

Sweetest man you will ever meet. Hard class but definitely worth it. Lots of group work but has good rules in place to make sure everyone pulls their weight.
Great teacher and very enthusiastic. He always emphasizes ethics issus which is rare for someone in the business school.

Professor Cohen was very helpful to me as I am from China and he was always available for help. Very intelligent although at times he was very critical of the ethics of corporations. He asks tough questions but he always works with the student to make sure they learn.
Great guy-amazingly passionate about the material. Only negative is that he is a fanatical Yankees fan.
Jeff is my father so I got to say nothing but good things about him! take his class he is the man and I love him to death!

Great Teacher. Hilarious guy, and really makes you think. I'd definately reccomend him. A break from the usual boring charecter of business professors.
Prof. Quigley is what a college professor should be: intelligent,very interesting,a great lecturer and enthused about his material. Fantastic.

Dr. Quigley is the most competent lecturer I've ever had. Each class covers a distinct period and he speaks easily and effectively without notes. Major points are identified and each follows seamlessly from the prior. Last 30-40 minutes are Q&A. Don't miss a class or you miss a lot of material.

Quigley is an absolutely incredible and brilliant man.  After taking Modern Hist w/him my first semester, he instilled a love of history I never new I had - convinced me to major in it!  I too took as many classes w/him as possible.  He is structured, clear, and gives papers instead of finals.  Take History of NYC with him if offered. Its his best

I took Prof. Quigley as many times as I could. By far the best teacher at BC. Gifted writer and organized and interesting lecturer. Your time at the Heights isn't complete unless you take a class with him
Funny and nice and smart
The Best History Prof Ever.
She's funny and interesting. You won't be bored and she cares about her students.

Disorganized genius. Uses her own life experiences in the classroom to make her points, and she's a gifted storyteller with a ton of hilarious stories to tell. Too much fun to have class with, you won't regret it.

Lara Birk is an amazing professor, woman, and lunch date. Take her class, you will not regret it. She will change your life.

Professor Birk taught at Wesleyan University this past year but I know she is returning to BC in the coming year.  She is amazing!!! Before each class we read several interesting readings and then in class she guided us in some of the most thought-provoking class discussions I've ever participated in, showing us relevant videos.  Fair grader.
Wow, what a great professor.

I would say his exam was pretty easy. You don't really have to go to class, and he won't mind, but some stuffs that he talked about in class were on the midterms. If you have never taken calculus before, this class might feel little hard because, instead of explaining basic concepts in details, he likes to prove interesting yet more complicatthings

I like Anand a lot he was very funny and clearly loves the subject. Took calculus in high school once with an awful teacher and am currently taking it my second time around. I struggled last year and am prospering so far this year. He re-inspired my love for math and I've come to appreciate the value of a good teacher.
He's a boss
My favorite professor at BC. She is super caring and nice. Always available outside of class.

Professor Nikolova is by far the best professor I've had at BC. She genuinely cares so much about her students, always makes herself available as a resource outside of class, and is highly inspirational. She felt like a second mom to me this semester. Everyone should have the opportunity to take her. Take Professor Nikolova, she is the best!!

Professor Brownell is very kind and approachable. His teaching style relies on long, slightly unorganized lectures which can be hard to follow. He is at times ambiguous in his way of explanation, so make sure to pair them with the textbook and article readings.

Prof Brownell is very caring and approachable. He is lecture heavy, and it can sometimes be boring, but he tried to add interest to a fairly boring topic. Exams are very fair and he gives a review sheet before then, and the readings are only needed for extra review

Such a kind professor who is passionate about his work however his lectures are very heavy. Always found myself having to rewatch the recorded lectures later on in 2x speed. Tests are mostly short answers (2 sentences max per question) which can be both good and bad. Haven't gotten an A in my two exams so far.
Kinda boring lectures. Slide presentation were disorganized and hard to follow. Overall good teacher. Very willing to help students.
Prof. Brownell clearly wants his students to succeed. I would recommend taking his class.
Amazing course on solid state physics--essential for all graduate students in the department.

Prof. Engelbrecht is THE best professor I ever have. He is a real gentleman and a scholar, which is really rare these days. I STRONGLY recommend everyone who wants to gain a clear understanding of physics to take at least one of his courses.

Nicest guy ever! Always willing to help. However, gives too many notes and I often zone out his lectures since I am rushing to write everything down. If you want an A, you have to work for it. Review the study guide and be able to identify random passages the Bible (hardest part of the tssst). MC are easy and open ended he gives you beforehand.
ratingTags_Rating: Skip class? You won't pass.--Clear grading criteria--EXTRA CREDIT

comment_Rating: Professor Kemp is a great guy and an awesome lecturer. I had him for Biblical Heritage Parts I and II. Very smart guy and makes every class a lot of fun.

I went into PULSE hating philosophy and theology. I did not know if I believed in God, but I definitely was willing to contemplate it. Traska has a way of taking students on a journey and teaching them the necessary material without stressing them out. He makes the class as easy as possible and makes lots of funny pop culture jokes. TAKE HIM!

Of all of the professors I've had at BC, Traska is definitely the best. He has a way of making his class completely stress-free while still making sure people leave the lecture learning something. Put effort in, and respectshow interest in the subject, and you can count on an A. Putting up with the daily quizzes was absolutely worth it.
Great Teacher, enthusiastic and helpful. Knows how to explain things. Knows his subject well. Makes you work - makes you learn. Good class, very useful.

Professor Johns managed to make mistakes every lecture, even with notes right in front of him, and didnt catch or correct mistakes until a student raised their hand. Spent way too much time teaching things that weren't required. Difficulty of last two exams escalated tremendously. He made simple concepts much more complicated than necessary.
Absolutely terrible. Unclear, gets sidetracked and makes no sense. Avoid her at all costs, her class is miserable

I had Professor Brinton for PULSE -- yeah, Phil & Theo. They're both tough subjects, but Professor Brinton is the philosopher king drawing me slowly out of the cave of ignorance and into the light of the higher good (poetry-creds to Plato -- those are his ideas, not mine). Prof Brinton is challenging, but a very good teacher of difficult material.

She is rude and not receptive to students which is funny because her focus is clinical psych. She will make attacking comments to students in front of the class. Her lectures are hard to sit through. You have to buy her textbook to pass this class. She wants you to struggle. Exams are 60% of your grade. Do not take this class unless necessary.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Test heavy--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: Karen Rosen does not care about her students. It is almost impossible to do well in the class and the final examination is cumulate and weighted 35% of the final grade. It is like she does not want students to succeed. Also can make very rude comments to students. Do not take if you do not have to, it will be an unnecessary amount of life stress.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Group projects--Test heavy

comment_Rating: She knows her stuff, but lectures are monotone and info heavy with barely any text on slides. Exams are too much work with four short essay questions, one essay, and 30+ MC questions. Impossible to finish one exam in time. Sadly, she is head of clinical psych concentration, so I will have to take more of her classes. Material is interesting.

Dr. Rosen just seems disinterested in her students which is ironic because she is a clinician. When asked questions her answers lack a genuine response. There is too much busy work and the midterm and final are weighted quite heavily (60% of overall grade). Exams involve writing 5 essays and 30+ mc in an 1hr15 which was impossible/ harshly graded
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Get ready to read--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: Super lecture heavy and she's not the most interesting lecturer either. There are a lot of arbitrary assignments and she's lenient with the discussion posts but such a tough grader for everything else. She's also not that accommodating or understanding of her students. Honestly, don't take this class unless you absolutely have to.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Get ready to read--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: Such an easy professor!  Definitely recommend to those in the Higher Education program.

Grimm makes class interesting, easily understood and fun. She speaks half English, half German in class. The vocabulary is very applicable to real life. She is very real--we've had class discussions in german about things like drinking and smoking. She turns learning German into something for life, not just class. Signed up for another class w/ her

One of my favorite professors at BC. This man is undoubtedly a genius and the extent of his passion is UNPARALLELED. He can get easily side-tracked with soccer or talking about how Bach is better than any other musician and his intellect can be intimidating but he's actually SUPER funny. Get ready to be amazed. He's super understanding as well.
Teresa makes this class fun and interesting; doesn't feel like a core hassle at all!
Professor Disanto is a genius!!
Dr. DiSanto is so caring. I love fish(es)! I wish she taught more courses at bc.. She's an inspiration!
taking Val's class has been a life transforming experience. thank you, professor!
It's obvious that Dr. DiSanto loves to teach.  She really cares about her students, and she's the best prof ever.  Hilarious!!! She makes you love fish.

She is a bit hard to understand at times, as she is a native of Italy. However, she cares a lot about everyone doing well and she gives two extra credit options to make sure everyone does well. Lecture's consist of a lot of note taking, but it is worth it if you want to do well on the tests. Interesting class overall.

I took Perspectives with Professor Burmeister my freshman year at BC. It ended up being my favorite course that year and one of the best I've taken at the university. Professor Burmeister is extremely articulate and gifted at explaining the complex topics we confronted in readings. It is not easy to get an A, but the course is extremely meaningful.

Take his class. I transfered to Boston College and he was my first professor! This man is amazing and will open your eyes to the world around you and make you contemplate whether to be a philosophy minor or not!

Lectures are a little long, but he does the best in a class that doesn't participate very much. There are some tricky quizzes though, guidelines aren't exactly laid out clearly, but overall not bad. Over a month since our first assignment, and still no grade; could be a result of learning a new system, though. Selfie game on Fleek

Course was graded through contract grading, which allows for you to meet with him and set goals for your grade in the class. (ex: if I want an A I'll show up for 90% of classes, if I want a B I'll show up for 80%, etc.) A tad disorganized with canvas and email communication, but laid back and a great lecturer. Really enjoyed the class!

Unwilling to help if you're struggling, even if there's a common problem shared by many students. Often ignores emails and is hard to access outside of class - once I showed up to office hours only to find she was out "looking for her husband." Exams almost entirely focus on obscure details never covered in lectures or readings.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Lecture heavy--Tough grader

comment_Rating: Professor Zhang is one of the most underrated history professors at BC. Definitely take her! She knows what she is talking about, cares about getting to the know the students, and facilitates interesting class discussions. Amount of homework is pretty normal, but the grade really depended on a final paper and participation only.
Very passionate about her work, and very open but don't fool around in her class if you want an A.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Skip class? You won't pass.--GRADED BY FEW THINGS

comment_Rating: Professor Zhang is incredibly motivated and cares about her students success. She can at times be a little too hyper specific however over the quality of student's work. She treats you like a graduate student, and some may enjoy that, but if you are looking for a confidence boost, not the class for you.

GREAT teacher. She really cares about her students and wants them to succeed. offers help in any way possible. I wish she could teach all my classes. I learned a lot and also enjoyed the class. stickler for attendance though, so you better show up. decent amount of homework, but you are learning a new language so what do you expect?
ratingTags_Rating: Skip class? You won't pass.--Clear grading criteria--Caring

comment_Rating: I did not enjoy being in her lectures, hard to understand, very difficult, unfriendly. and does not grade fairly.
ratingTags_Rating: Skip class? You won't pass.--LOTS OF HOMEWORK--SO MANY PAPERS

comment_Rating: Prof. Easton is so kind and supportive. Always available for office hours and if you put in the time in her class you'll see results. She really wants to see you succeed.
He gives homework that helps a lot for the midterms. You can pass the class without going to lectures, he usually steer off topic
ratingTags_Rating: Lots of homework--Graded by few things--Get ready to read

comment_Rating: He's your standard Gen Chem professor; would ABSOLUTELY recommend for a first semester freshman. I only didn't do great because I had a high school mentality from freshman year. He will teach you the basics well; exams ARE FAIR if you actually READ THE BOOK AND DO THE HOMEWORK. Actually study for quizzes. Understand material as much as you can.
ratingTags_Rating: Graded by few things--Clear grading criteria--EXTRA CREDIT

comment_Rating: Professor Davidovits is such a great human being! I had Fox originally last year and I dropped because he was too tough a grader and rather rude when we didn't do well. Prof. D teaches in a way that makes sense, doesn't waste our time with busy work such that we can study effectively, his exams are fair, and is easily accessible outside of class.

Professor Davidovits shows interest in the subject at hand by giving his students insight of chemistry beyond the classroom and labs. Even though the class is lecture heavy you will do fine on the exams as long as you do the designated homework problems and practice more problems that are shown in the book.

Took Freshman Topic Seminar (Nature of Inquiry) and loved it. Class consisted of posing questions we were curious about and discussing them in a group setting. Davidovits was Academic Advisor for his topic seminar class. Tried to push Chem as much as possible, regardless of major, but good advice and good-humored.

I loved Calc up until I took this class. Very monotone voice and does not do a good job explaining anything. If youre new to the subject, good luck, I had some experience and I still elected to drop. Tests are really hard, studying takes a lot of time work, basically the rigor of 2 classes if youre brand new. Nice guy in person but not helpful
ratingTags_Rating: Skip class? You won't pass.--Test heavy--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: great professor. Always available outside of class. Non like some arrogant math professors, he always listens to your questions patiently and thinks together with you. Some said he is a little tedious during the class. But I don't think it matters much. Also, homework and tests are lecture based. Grading is really fair and he gives partial credit

Complete shmuck. Has monotone lectures where he does not engage the class at all and frankly doesn't convey the material very well. He is never available to meet outside of class and shows a lack of regard and respect for his students. He is super unclear about test topics and other important information. Avoid his Calc II class at all costs.

Professor Reed is a solid Calculus professor. He focuses mainly on lectures which can be kind of tedious and boring, but actually teaches the material. He has tons of examples and definitely comes to class prepared to teach. He isn't exceedingly accessible outside of class, but there is a discussion once a week that helps. Overall a good course.

Her class is very discussion based in a way that I really liked. It's easy to get away without reading, but I definitely got a lot out of it when I did read. The reading was normally very manageable (a short poem or less than 10 pages) most nights, but towards the end of the semester we would sometimes have 80-90 pages to read, which was tough.

She is super nice and makes class interesting. Not great at responding to emails and sometimes hands out work right before it is due. She is a hard grader but does want to make you do better in the corse. Will have long meeting to help with your writing.

First year writing, Adair is a fantastic prof and person and made me a better writer. A lot of writing (about 3 pages a week) but in all honesty, these are rough drafts. She also has you write on a variety of topics and styles which makes it interesting. If you want an easy A, don't take, but if you want to become a better writer, this is it.
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--So many papers--Tough grader

comment_Rating: Best clinical experience I have had
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--GROUP PROJECTS

comment_Rating: Truly one of the nicest people I've ever met, she truly cares about her students' success in and out of her class. Not sure about her other classes, but I highly recommend her for the Enduring questions/natural science core, especially if you're not super into hard science.
A fabulous professor who cares SO MUCH about her students. A great person to converse with out of class as well. I would highly recommend any of her classes.

She is one of my favorite people at this school. She applies what she knows about neuroscience and learning to the class so you feel like you are learning but it is super easy. Such a relaxed grader and everyone in the class respected her a lot.

Professor Maxwell is an amazing professor. he really cares about his students and their understanding of the course content. His class is difficult but he has lots of office hours. The research paper/project is really tough and he does a lot of group work but he is overall just a great person. You would be lucky to take his class.
I wouldn't recommend taking him. He is confusing and moves at a very fast pace. Problems done in class do not reflect the problems on tests. He also makes the tests extremely long.

A ton of homework given every week (written and online), very fast paced class, doesn't spend much time on the hardest topics (related rates being one), and tests are very difficult. Very difficult to get a good grade, would recommend taking other professors
Boiiiiii. This mans cannot teach mathematics even a little bit.

Dianne is great! She was very understanding of the fact that it was our first semester of college, especially during Fall 2020. Readings were very manageable (she posted them all on Canvas), and she was very generous with paper extensions. The course was engaging, but she was a pretty tough grader.

I adore her. She's a very open-minded person who cares about every student's opinion and two cents. She opens the class to discussion and creates a very relaxed, open environment for students. She also recognizes that she too, is a human and doesn't put her self on a pedestal, its like having a caring parent as a professor.

Look, there is a ton of reading for this class. However, if you can stomach it, this is one of my favorite courses I've taken at BC. Dipasquale tries to seem mean in the very beginning of the semester, but he quickly became one of the most engaging and funniest professors I ever had. His lectures also explored very interesting ideas.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Amazing lectures --Beware of pop quizzes

comment_Rating: I really enjoyed having DiPasquale for learning, but not totally as a student. Class material and lectures were very interesting and he's very funny, but grading is tough. Mandatory attendance with a minor participation grade, so the midterm/final are huge. Readings are really dense and a lot of the time boring. Do not take if not a Poly Sci Major
ratingTags_Rating: Amazing lectures --Lots of homework--Beware of pop quizzes

comment_Rating: Professor DiPasquale is by far one of the best professors at BC and my favorite professor that I've taken in my 4 years here. His classes are difficult yet very rewarding. I have taken 3 of his classes and I have learned the most in these classes than any other political science classes offered. Highly recommend if you're willing to put in the work

There is a lot of reading (50-100+ pages per week) but he explains them really well. His lectures are very insightful and entertaining. Consists of two take home papers (20%) and two exams (25% and 35%). He will cold call and give pop quizzes but if you read and take notes they are not hard. Office hours are extremely helpful Grades HOLISTICALLY.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Gives good feedback

comment_Rating: This Professor is without a doubt my favorite one here at BC. Get ready to spend your entire printing budget on his class though. Lots of reading and big on information retention. Lectures are captivating and very inspiring without being dry and boring. You can not be a BC student without taking at least one of his classes.

Professor DiPasquale is one of the best teachers I've had. His class is tough but super fun, and you become a  better student. There is lots of reading, cold calling, and the occasional pop quiz, but it's all totally worth it because of how much you learn and how funny the class is. Defo go to office hours too! Such a fun guy to talk with.

DiPasquale is very interesting, one of the most interesting professors I've ever taken. That being said, his class was completely crazy reading/grading wise. He assigns a disgusting amount of reading that nobody has time to do, and you have to remember small details from it. I would take him again if I didn't get graded by him.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Get ready to read--Amazing lectures

comment_Rating: Prof. DiPasquale is brilliant. Every poli sci major should take at least one class with him. He assigns a ton of reading, cold calls, and gives pop quizzes, but it is so worth it. His lectures are phenomenal, he is absolutely hysterical, and you will learn to look at the world from an entirely new perspective. Take Islam and Liberal Democracy!!

Mixed opinion. Good guy, great lecturer, clearly brilliant. I'm not sure the class actually gets you to retain much though. Assigns so much reading that its almost impossible not to skim. Cold calls. Pop quizzes w fill in the blank sentence from 50 pages of reading. Tests are blue book essays that make you cram most of the info for just a few days.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Amazing lectures --Test heavy

comment_Rating: Cold calls every class but it forces you to get the most out of the material. Learned a lot in his class and was a great lecturer.

A ridiculous amount of reading, and you don't discuss more than half of it. Infrequent pop quizzes cover a wide range of details from the reading. Cold calls every class, but his lectures are good and have many good anecdotes The midterm was lengthy and graded meticulously. A lot of work, an interesting class, and hard to get a good grade.
ratingTags_Rating: Lots of homework--Get ready to read--Tough grader

comment_Rating: DiPasquale is an absolute beauty. he does cold call at times but he exceeds all other categories a teacher should. very clear and concise. gives good responses to your questions and is willing to explain anything if you are confused. also is very funny and gives inspirational monologues that make you really think about certain things. he's great

Prof. DiPasquale assigns a good amount of reading, but he genuinely cares about his students and is very open to hearing out all opinions and engaging others. You need to do the reading in order to follow along in the discussion the next day and pass his exams. He grades according to level of improvement, so it's a good idea to go to office hours.
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--Caring

comment_Rating: Best professor I've had at BC. Brilliant, respects his students, changes the way you think. Take any class you can with him.
Absolutely phenomenal professor who I cannot say enough good things about.
Professor Kineke means well but simply repeats the textbook in every class. There is much more complex and confusing material than you would think. The labs are also extremely difficult.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough Grader--GRADED BY FEW THINGS--LECTURE HEAVY

comment_Rating: There is a lot of reading and he can get off topic at times. The feedback he gives on papers is good but not very clear as to what EXACTLY he wants you to do or how to better it, even if you ask him for help again. Class participation matters as you are graded everyday on it. Also, there are only 2 papers, but the account for 25% of your grade.
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--Participation matters

comment_Rating: Bobby is a great teacher. He's excited about the stuff we read and tries to get us excited too. Some of the class discussions were really interesting. Beware if you hate talking in class because Bobby will try to get you out of your comfort zone. His feedback on writing was super useful, though he's not an easy grader. Recommend it!

Professor Robert Wengronowitz is overall a really awesome person and puts a lot of work into improving the class for the students. He really wants you to earn a good grade and values good discussions.
If you want an "easy" elective class with an amazing professor, take Music and Social Justice with her. She is so passionate, and the course load is light yet interesting. Highly recommend.
Take this class!
Seth is awesome. Really knows what he's doing. Class was easy if you put in any effort. His tests are not bad either.
Don't need to go to class to learn anything, but you won't get a good grade if you don't watch the lectures. Lab sections are unnecessarily hard and a lot of time.

Good guy but the class was hard, if you're not a geology major it will take too much time for an elective. Very hard testing, lot to read, if you get behind of the class forget it. It a LOT of material. But hey, great lectures!
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Get ready to read--Test heavy

comment_Rating: Kruckenberg is a great guy, no question about it. That, being said he was always too busy to attend office hours at the time he said he would be there, or even answer a simple email. Grades on the weekly check ins and quizzes were posed the day before the exams every time, and the exams were not easy. Definitely good intentions, but too busy.
Super nice guy and very fair grader. His lectures are engaging, so even if you don't like earth science at all it should be interesting. Great professor!

Dr. Kazemi is extremely knowledgable and he does care for his students. However, this is one of the hardest Econ electives you can take. Unless you are willing to make this class your #1 priority for the semester, it isn't worth taking. The title 'impact of news' is also misleading; the class is more about Fed releases and Treasury instruments.
Worst professor I've seen at Boston College.
GOAT

Prof. Hudson is by far the best professor I have had at BC. He is super caring to all of his students and is super easy to talk to. He is not a hard grader in terms of papers but tests can be a little difficult. I cannot recommend taking his course enough. Super nice. Super funny. And has a ton of respect for his students. He also curves!

best professor I've ever had. he cares more about the students than assigning grades. he gives so many opportunities for you to succeed and you actually learn about moral arguments. he lets you speak your mind and never judges or makes you feel like if you have a different opinion your grade will be affected by it. most caring and thoughtful prof!!

I've taken both his Population Genetic and Bioinformatics course. He's a genius as a computational biology scholar but a has bit of drawbacks as a lecturer. But being said the subjects are really hard for pure biology/math/CS students, he's a good choice. Ask, it makes you feel dumb, but he knows every single things he teach. Cheatsheets allowed.

He tends to be very unclear when explaining things in class, and his powerpoints are very confusing once the material gets slightly difficult. This is the most I've ever learned from a textbook in my life, and the textbook problems (though very easy) do NOT reflect what's on the tests (unclear wording). That being said, he curves fairly well

Sometimes his lectures move a little too quickly, but he is engaging in lecture and truly cares for his students. He adjusted the course as the semester went on if he felt the class was feeling too stressed or if one of his original assignments was no longer effective. He's a reflective dude, and a rarity for a course this big in that way.

Class has no structure or direction, lectures based off of whatever he wants to talk about that day. Very unfocused curriculum (if any), does not use any site like Canvas. No powerpoint to go along with lectures. Changed midterm exam to a 3000-3500 word essay on an opera. Basically changed class from intro to music to music history class.

Amazing professor. She's really caring. When you first meet her in class, you introduce yourself and she writes down details about you life and in discussion, she writes down your opinions. Let's the class take over the discussion. Writes lots of considerate feedback. Seems interested in anything you have to say.

John is a humorous lecturer and cares about the performance of his students. This guy is pretty patient in explaining abstract math concepts. He tried his best to convey class materials to my thick skull...I didn't get an A but a lot of my friends did.

Great professor, made sense of the material really well. He isn't super available for office hours, which was a bit unfortunate. Definitely would recommend for this class, and also just a nice guy in general

John is great for Intro to Abstract Math. The class is time-consuming because you have to write proofs on LATEX, but John is a fantastic teacher. Be prepared to dedicate time to understand the material to perform on exams.

Worst teacher I've ever had. She asks questions to the class and everyone sits there and stares at her. Assigns reading that have little to nothing to do with what we do in class and he readings are outdated, dry, and way too long. I would never take this class again.

Honestly requires too much homework. Class time is a waste of an hour because we often sit in awkward silence as she tries to lead discussions. We also cannot have our laptops out and it is hard to contribute to discussions with specifics if all of the readings are done online! Would not recommend this class at all, just a lot of busy work.
ratingTags_Rating: Participation matters--Skip class? You won't pass.--LOTS OF HOMEWORK

comment_Rating: She is a very responsible teacher. It is normal for this class to have vocab quiz once a week, because students can better learn language with vocab memorized. She is one of the kindest professors I have ever had in my life, and I really enjoyed her class. She is always smiling and is patient even when you cant come up with the answer right away.

Made a snarky comment to me at the end of the semester and made me cry. Cold calls you, and there is a vocabulary quiz every other day. Also very tough on grading. When I told her about my mental health issues and needed a few absences, she wasn't very accommodating at all.

She's a nice person and comes from Japan. Don't get me wrong, i'm pretty sure it's the language department that's strict not her, but this class (any language class) will be a lot of work. There will be a vocabulary quiz every other day. She deducted points cause my answer was right but the character was written incorrectly.
ratingTags_Rating: Lots of homework--Skip class? You won't pass.--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: Clear lectures, difficult tests. You definitely need to study and really understand what's going on to pass. He's really helpful and friendly if you visit him in office hours. He is also funny sometimes during lectures. All of his tests have extra credit. He doesn't curve even if the average grade is lower than a B-.
ratingTags_Rating: Skip class? You won't pass.--TEST HEAVY--Would take again

comment_Rating: I honestly loved Professor P. The 2hour class on Thursday nights is not bad (he usually lets you out early). He is very interesting and motivating. He teaches through discussions that model real-life situations with the applicable laws. He's the fairest and most understanding professor I've had. Keep up with the reading and the online hw.

Your class grade is essentially based off two exams and a paper. He is a cool dude, cop & lawyer but does not use canvas at all so no clue how you are doing through out semester. Exams are hard so keep up with the readings. Lectures were pretty engaging, he even got us pizza once. He cancelled class a lot. truly cares about his students!
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Get ready to read--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: Professor P is a great person, but a horrible lecturer and professor. Classes are extremely messy since he doesn't use any PowerPoints. He just reads random parts of the textbook and gives real-life situations. You don't need to show up to class since it's pretty much useless. All you need to do is read the textbook. Would not recommend
Great professor. You can tell that he genuinely cares about all his students and wants everyone to succeed. That said, he makes you work for it. Keep up with the reading and you will be fine.
Best professor!!!

Overall a great professor HOWEVER this class did engage in some very controversial topics and Prof did not even TRY to hide his personal views on them. People have freedom to be as offensive as they please-- nothing is off the table-- and he won't stop them. It can sometimes feel like you're fighting a losing battle during class discussion.

Professor Coolman is a very engaging lecturer and his exams are difficult but always matches with the information in the lectures and assigned readings. Attending class is important as it is the only way to get the information, but it is not mandatory.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Lecture heavy--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: Professor Coolman gave really interesting classes that were very insightful. However, reading material was extremely long and tests and pop quizzes were difficult. However, he is always willing to meet outside of class time.
ratingTags_Rating: Participation matters--Beware of pop quizzes--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: Prof. Coolman gives engaging lectures and I always enjoyed going to his class. You really have to do all the readings to do well in the class. Not a necessarily an easy A, but I didn't mind doing the work because it was interesting

Professor Coolman was an interesting and insightful lecturer but his exams were hard, even after reading every homework assignment. He has frequent and random pop quizzes based on the reading homework the exams include questions that are very detailed specific. Although he's a great lecturer, the homework was a lot and the exams are hard.

I had Peter as my philosophy teacher some forty years ago and I still hear his voice in my life. He was simply the biggest influence on my thought and on my own personal direction in life. His words come from a prayerful place and if you are willing to actually listen with your whole self you may experience as did I 'the sublime courtesy of God'.

I feel that though he may be a well regarded professor and served for many years it may have gone to his head and effected his teaching now. He seems to have an heir of superiority beyond any other professor I have had here and I think it impedes his ability to teach Philosophy especially.

Professor Kreeft is one of the best teachers and mentors that I have ever had. If you take learning seriously, you cannot do poorly in his class. Yes, his exams are hard (they actually test your knowledge). But extra credit papers are always accepted; thus a poor grade truly reflects a lack of effort.
this professor is soooooooooo boring I cant stay awake in his class!! no visual aid, no power point.
In four years of college and eight years of postgraduate study, at both private and public schools, he's perhaps the best teacher I've ever had.
No Comments
Dr. Kreeft is one of the most highly-regarded Philosophers of our age. His lectures, very well-concieved and organized, clarifies the esoteric and myopic into something palpable and entertaining.
One of the great influences on my life. Take him every semester you can.

Dr. Kreeft is a great professor, the crown jewel of the philosophy department at BC. I recommend taking any of his classes to understand real philosophy. There are those who don't like him, but they are wrong in many things and do not appreciate the truth. Do not listen to them. He is always to talk with you and listen to you. Dr. Kreeft is a true philosopher because he really lives the life of a philosopher.
He is an A if you do the work and extra credit. His Logic class is excellent. I also had him for Death and Dying.

I took Kreeft three times while at BC. Even then I heard something new with each class. As philosophy profs go, you won't find someone more skilled, experienced, published or more interesting than he. Bonus if you take his Tolkien class.

I personally fell asleep in Kreeft's class, but then again it was a huge lecture class. The entire grade was based on 2 large multiple choice tests, so it screwed my GPA freshman year. But he really is brilliant & if I'd had him in diff. class, I think I would've liked him better. So basically avoid his big lectures & stick with the small seminars.
This guy is simply a genius, thank God for Professor Kreeft.  He may be a bit dull in his lectures, but if you actually LISTEN to what he says, it is a treasure trove of wisdom!
STAYYYYYY AWAY   ABSOLUELY destroyed my GPA .  Every single class he put at least 5 outta 20 students asleep.  PLEASE DONT DO THIS to yourself
