Amazing!
Terrible teacher. Get ready for exams with 200 multiple choice questions
Amazing....:) Take any class he teaches.  He is brilliant....and a very good author!
unless you're an aspiring priest, stay away from Kreeft
i don't go to BC. but i heard him give a talk. this guy is awsome. he is very funny and demanding. he is a deep thinker. (that's all you need from a philosophy professor.)
Loves Socratic method. Conservative. Very shy.
Really made me think for the first time in an academic class - he was demanding, but it was well worth it!
By far the greatest teacher I've had at BC. Take his classes!
very interesting, very religious...

Teopaco doesn't manage the class time well. He has rigid lecture/discussion rules and reduces grades for not participating but doesn't let everyone participate evenly. Would never take his course again.
ratingTags_Rating: Participation matters--Skip class? You won't pass.

comment_Rating: Participation will make or break your grade, and this inspires many to comment whatever they can, which was overall detrimental to intellectual discourse. Professor himself offers little insight, and mostly acts as a moderator for class discussion. Essays were graded harshly, and instructions not totally clear. Cases chosen were interesting.
ratingTags_Rating: Participation matters--Skip class? You won't pass.--Tough grader

comment_Rating: I liked Quinn and her PP slides were helpful, but I feel like I learned more from the textbook than her, per se. Homeworks aren't bad at all. Caution: her quizzes and tests will have some curveballs that aren't like the hws you did. Also the MC questions are annoying. But they're not CRAZY hard overall.

Lectures are well organized and coincide with the textbook chapters, which are helpful to read before or after because they break down everything in basic terms. Homework is much more helpful then just busy work. Each chapter also has a set of review problems that are helpful. The quizzes are difficult with challenging multiple choice questions.

Quinn is really sweet, her class is just tough. She seems kinda passive aggressive when you first meet her, & she is kinda nit picky about things like asking her questions after an exam without a gap of time passed. Overall she is nice, I just wouldn't recommend her if you're able to get one of the other fin acc profs. She's good if you can't tho

Professor Quinn is very fair. All of her assignments were reasonable, her grading policy is fair (hw is based on completion) and she doesn't give too much work. I learned so much- she also prints out her power points for everyone and provides detailed study guides before tests which was super helpful

Absolute queen. Awesome teacher. Wanted to see her students succeed and was very willing to help. Very accessible outside of class. Tests were tough but she gives study guides and does some review in class which is helpful. One group project which is very manageable.

Prof. Quinn's accounting class is no walk in the park, but that is the nature of the material. She moves through the material efficiently but in a manner that enables engagement and questioning. Her review problems are very helpful, and she really ensures that everyone is on the same page. Tests/quizzes are tough but fair. Learning is the priority!
Quizes and tests are pretty much straight from review/in class problems and never from homework so if you can do those problems, you will be good.

I really liked the structure of his class; you decide when to complete homework. He takes attendance even though it is not mandatory. He is very engaged and tries to learn everyone's name. The work itself is not difficult at all.
Class is very student paced. just have to do X number of assignment before the semester. Huge essay due for final but class is very easy and not much work. Hes very engaging and personal.

Professor Morello cares about his students and is a great lecturer. He always is well prepared and engages all students in class discussions. His assignments are helpful in understanding class material and are flexible which helps his students.

Really nice professor, informative and interesting lectures! As long as you do the required work, you will do well in the class. Very willing to meet with students outside of class for help/feedback. Definitely recommend!

He's honestly just so mean and did not care about his student's well-being. His emails are very short, impersonal, and rude, even when you are discussing serious topics. The lectures I found to be unengaging and the focus on Latin America was way too broad. Didn't end up learning much in this class and also left with a bad view of this teacher.

Amazing experience with professor Morello in his Introduction to Latin American Societies class. Explains clearly and helps understand the past and current situation in Latin America about many aspects such as religion, political instability, sports, etc. Definitely recommend taking his class and getting to know him as a person.
given the fact that he's a priest he's not compassionate or understanding whatsoever, doesn't take into consideration of student's mental health, and doesn't provide feedback at all.
good professor would recommend his class

The teacher is excellent in teaching and encourages students to express their ideas in class. Using his own vivid way of expressing what he taught us, the students in class seemed to be exploring in a very interesting way. His extra points can greatly reduce stress
He is the best professor I have ever seen. He was meticulous when he typed and lectured in case his students could not understand what he said. The grades he gave were very friendly.
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--Respected--Get ready to read

comment_Rating: Best professor ever. Take his classes. Trust me you wont regret!!!
He is my favorite History Professor !!!! After Finishing His class,I still Miss him and think his teaching is very useful to my future!!!!

He is the best professor I have ever meet before.He is now teaching in NEU and he helps me a lot. He is so nice and his lecture is very interesting that you cannot miss!!!!! I have energe when every morning when I know I will having his class. I enjoy his class very much and he also provide a recommendation for me which I am so appreciate.

Balazs can be the best professor ever! He is sooooo funny. work and tests won't be too hard if you pay attention in his class. I mean, you will always pay attention in his class. His class is the one that you never want to skip! HE is now teaching at Northeastern though.
He is just great! It is not gonna be easy to get a good grade, but his lectures r something that u don't want to miss.
Great teacher and great class. I would HIGHLY recommend this class if you can take it although I think he is moving to Northeastern :(
I am definitely not the biggest history fan but this was such a fun and engaging class. The professor was amazing. Loved it.

Balazs is an amazing professor! I absolutely loved his class. He explains everything extremely clearly and is extremely excited about the material. His enthusiasm and passion for the topics inspires interest in the class and makes students want to do the reading and the work. Very fair grader and genuinely helpful and wonderful professor!
straight g.

Balazs is an outstanding professors. Extremely enthusiastic, knowledgeable, and knows how to make the material interesting. Very understanding and cares about his students. Instead of lecturing from a textbook, Balazs incorporates interesting historical texts that you learn and remember from, rather than just memorize. Take Balazs if possible!
Balazs is one of my favorite teachers I've ever had. Fair grader, which encourages you to do the work. Makes history interesting! So animated and funny. Amazing teacher, take the class if you can.

Balazs is a wonderful teacher. He is extremely enthusiastic and makes dull history core material interesting. Instead of lecturing out of a text book he incorporates fascinating novels and historical texts that you actually learn and remember material from. Very understanding and helpful. Definitely take Balazs if at all possible!

I loved this class. Prof. Szelenyi is extremely knowledgeable in his field of European History, and I really enjoyed all of the readings. It wasn't your typical shove information into your brain type of class; rather, I learned more than I expected through historical lens. The only suggestion I would make is to structure more organized lectures.

Balazs is the greatest man on earth! He is beyond hilarious and has a beautiful passion for teaching history. His class is fair and fun and the work load is not bad at all. He is extremely understanding and intelligent. His knowledge rubs off a great deal!

Balazs is absolutely the man. Understand the life of a student and is very lenient about work. Encourages students to work hard with a fair grading policy and provides a unique lens through which to few the insanity and debauchery of history. A++++
Really enthusiastic about the class, even if you don't like history he makes it interesting.  Reading is a lot but isnt always necessary.  Great teacher especially for a core class

Very enthusiastic. Sort of goes on rants but keeps them interesting. Assigns a lot of reading but isn't strict about it, knows his students have a lot of other work. Renewed my interest in history. Sends out the quiz questions ahead of time. I think he's moving to Northeastern but take his class if you can!

Admittedly, for being an intro to Physics Class, the material is quite tough. Graf however does make learning the material interesting and tries to incorporate as many demonstrations as possible. Physics is tough but Professor Graf does his best to make it approachable.

PHYS2200 is a very hard class, let's get this out of the way. Graf's tests are very difficult and the lecture problems are hard to keep up with. But around finals time you will realize how much you actually learned from him. Graf is very accessible after class and his office hours are pretty helpful! Just put time in after class and you'll be good.

Professor Graf is a funny guy and teaches the example problems well, but the pace of this class was extremely fast.  The textbook we used was intended for a full-year class, but we used it for the semester.  It was often difficult to keep up with his lecture slides if you wanted to write the entire example down.

His PowerPoints were clear and easy to follow with lots of practice problems. I found office hours near finals to be extremely helpful and the exams were fair and predictable. Homework questions checked to see if you understood the concepts since you dont get to practice as much in lecture so I found them necessary.
ratingTags_Rating: Amazing lectures--Clear grading criteria--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: This was over zoom, so keep that in mind. But it was very much lecture heavy, he doesn't explain his example problems the best, but the tests are pretty similar to what we learn & do in classs
ratingTags_Rating: Lots of homework--Graded by few things--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: In-class explanations were a bit more detailed than anything he'd ask on the exam. Standard dude, nothing special. ratingTags_Rating: Lots of homework--Skip class? You won't pass.--Test heavy

comment_Rating: Great teacher!
Enthusiastic, funny, extremely helpful, sometimes too much work

This was one of the most rewarding classes I've taken. The course was definitely difficult, especially the group project which proved to be very challenging for my group. ratingTags_Rating: Group projects--Gives good feedback--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: Professor Law's ECON3382 was admittedly chaotic at some points, but his teaching style and clear passion for the topic made the class my favorite class of all time at Boston College. The easiest class at Boston College I def recommend taking his class.

Prof. Tanner is really outstanding. I got a bad grade bc I was dealing with personal stuff and missed a lot of work, but her lectures are rich and thorough. She expects informed participation, but I highly recommend her if she is teaching a class in which you have a genuine interest.

Professor Tanner really enjoys hearing what you have to say, and the readings are actually interesting. Shes concerned with how students are doing outside of class and is always willing to work with you if needed.
Great professor. Not the easiest grader, but gives plenty of help if you work for it. One of the best I have had at BC.
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--Caring

comment_Rating: Professor Tanner chooses interesting books and fosters really great class conversations. She is a great teacher but more importantly, really kind to her students. She is always open to extensions and discussing how to improve.
I am only halfway through the semester but already Prof. Tanner is so kind, considerate, and helpful as a person and professor. I would 100% recommend any class with her.

Professor Tanner is wonderful. Fantastic educator, kind soul, brilliant literary analyst. I wish Id taken more classes with her at BC! We read amazing books in Contemporary American Women Writers, the themes, motifs, and tales of which were enhanced by robust discussion and analysis. Im so glad I had the chance to take her course!

Very sweet. Asks you about your personal life. Generous grader. Gives you tons of helpful feedback on essays, etc. Mostly discussion based class. She talks majority of the time. ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--Clear grading criteria

comment_Rating: Very good teacher. Learned a lot - and enjoyed the class.
Laura Tanner is one of the best Eng. professors I had at BC- challenging, helpful, really cares about her students!

Does original work that informs the class; is honest and challenging; works with lit in relation to current social issues; if you care about your work she will care about it too and help you get a lot out of it.  Is reserved, but cares.

Prof. McMenamin is the BEST professor I've taken at BC. She is extremely passionate about evolution and development. Unlike many professors who will flaunt their lab research, Prof. McMenamin is incredibly humble. She's there for the students and wants to make sure they enjoy learning. 10/10 would take her class again.
ratingTags_Rating: Accessible outside class--Get ready to read--Amazing lectures

comment_Rating: Professor Li is not a very good teacher. He reads off of slides that are made by the textbook and spews formulas and theorems without ever explaining them properly. In a difficult class like Multivar, you would expect plenty of examples, but he instead just reads off of impossible to decipher slides. At least his tests aren't too hard.

He does not teach in class. He says that material won't be on the exam, then proceeds to put it on the exam. He doesn't make an effort to get to know his students. Office hours aren't helpful either. There is no clear path to success in his class. Worst professor I've had in the math department at BC.
His class is difficult, but that is just the material.  He is a nice man, and his tests are fair. He isn't the greatest teacher, but it could be a lot worse.

Does not teach in class and TA's extra help was useless since you cannot see what he is writing on the board. No review packet or review lecture. Very hard to get a good grade. Do not take. Stress for no reason.

Nice lady but always arrives to class late and always seems unprepared and rambles aimlessly. If you do not align with her views, you will not do well in her class. Also very picky grader with in class essays. If you bring in any of your own views or what you've learned about the text in another class, she will dock you.

Bailey is always 5-15 minutes late to class, takes forever to grade, and is bad at technology. All of that said, she's very sweet, makes some great lectures on comparative politics, and recognizes hard work. Don't take MoPo with her unless you want a world politics class, because that's basically what she does. Interesting class nonetheless

(Actually for POLI3404, Anatomy of Dictatorship)

Great Professor. Caring, considerate, and easily accessible. I took her for Anatomy of Dictatorship for my senior seminar and I had a lot of fun doing that. You're graded by three things: class participation, final presentation (~40 minutes), and final paper (~25-30 pages). Great class & professor.

Bailey is one of the best professors at Boston College. Her knowledge is immense and her lectures are fascinating. I have never been bored in one of her classes (I have taken three of them now) and do not foresee boredom anytime soon. The reading is helpful but not essential and the tests are straightforward. If you are poli sci, TAKE BAILEY!

Professor Bailey is a great professor and is very knowledgeable on the subjects she teaches. I didn't do any of the readings, but understood everything that was going on because she was very good at explaining the material in the lectures. She was very disorganized and always late, but this did not really impact the class.
Take comparative mideast if you're polisci and want to learn a lot. If you do everything thats required you cant do poorly and you learn more from this class than from any other class.

I love Bailey. Took her both semesters of my freshmen year for intro poli sci classes and left with such a good impression. She's been teaching for decades and truly cares about her students, very much mom vibes. Very receptive in office hours. Definitely disorganized and takes a while to grade papers but you come to terms with that.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Lecture heavy--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: Prof Bailey is very knowledgeable and passionate about the subject. She can be a little slow to return assignments, but that is my only complaint. Lots of reading, but you will come out of the course with a greater understanding of politics

Professor Bailey is absolutely fantastic. Her only irritating quality is that she always arrives to class 5-10 minutes late and very frazzled, but she is a very enthusiastic and informative lecturer and you can tell she just wants her students to be as passionate about the material as she is. Would absolutely take her class if you get the chance!

I took Professor Bailey's class in 2004. Looking back on it, it's clear to me that she is a neo-con. It will be difficult to get a good grade if you don't agree with her world view or that of Bernard Lewis.

I agree with the prev. comment regarding Bailey's refusal to entertain dissenting point-of-views, however agenda-driven or ideologically-minded she may appear at times, she is a dynamic lecturer and has a firm grasp on policies, history and theology. She works very hard and expects nothing short of excellence if you intend on an A.

Very lively discussion group.A hard course; readings were dense and voluminous. Was understanding of personal issues, but was late in returning assignments

Amazing professor!! Really connects with her students. Very knowledgeable and encourages in-depth discussion. Well organized even with the online format. Would absolutely recommend.

Burgo is a caring, honest and truly funny guy -- he's also definitely the best fundamentals of music theory professor at BC. Quizzes and tests are frequent, but he preps you well and he will tell you exactly what's on them beforehand. So long as you do all the homework and study a small amount before tests, he'll help out your GPA.
Extremely kind and always transparent with tests and quizzes. Easy class with a music background. Manageable without background too. Definitely would recommend!

Very enthusiastic and kind. Good at explaining and always willing to answer questions. Easy grader, and, if you study hard enough, you may get out of taking the final exam! It sure cut my exam week down (it was supposed to be on the last day of exams - saved my week). Great guy. Would take him again. In fact, I am next semester.
Great teacher, moves a little fast but if you need extra help is happy to provide it!

Good lecturer, provides powerpoints, well-organized. Exams require a lot of memorization and questions are sometimes poorly worded. There is a 10 page research paper where she will nitpick on transitions, brevity, writing style. Content is mainly common sense, but class is unnecessarily difficult because you have to memorize terms, names, etc.

Prof MacEvoy is amazing. She is so passionate about what she is teaching and extremely intelligent. She genuinely cares about each student in lecture and workload is extremely manageable. There is one big paper that is time consuming but doable and then only a quick midterm and a final exam. Highly recommend her.

Prof. MacEvoy is an expert in her field and gives great lectures. She is clear about expectations and grading. Easy to follow and the exams are extremely straightforward, almost common sense. There is an annoying research paper happening in the background of the semester, but she is very willing to help and is understanding when things come up.

Easy class, doesn't let you use laptops though that's a drawback. Kind of boring at times, but she's a really easy grader so I think a lot of people get As. I wouldn't take it if you're looking for an interesting class, but if you're good at writing long papers and are a PoliSci/IS major needing a quick and easy GPA boost you should look into this.

Very participation heavy but also understanding and caring. Probably one of the best professors i've taken at BC. Very knowledgeable about her subject matter and lenient grader too. No in-person tests, just take home exams and in an class mock UN simulation with a short paper write up about that. I highly recommend her, she is amazing.

I just found her Comparative Politics class to be really boring. However, if you are really interested in it, it could be interesting. Reading heavy and also she talked a lot and that's how it got boring. Pretty good grader on papers, papers easy because they are based on readings. Mediocre class.
ratingTags_Rating: Lots of homework--Get ready to read--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: Really nice professor but she was not a great lecturer and I really didnt learn much at all from the class. The material made it depressing to start with and her teaching made it boring as well. She was a caring professor and semi-easy grader though.

Really nice guy, hilarious in class, very receptive to people's ideas in class. Encourages participation but doesn't force it. Homework takes barely any time at all. Two papers (around five pages each) and a final paper (7 pages). He knows a lot of really obscure facts, is very engaging and is clearly passionate about what he's teaching!

Prof. Najarian is a fantastic professor! He's very kind and understanding. The assignments are definitely manageable and pretty straightforward, and the poems he assigns in Studies in Poetry are interesting and diverse.
Funny and personable. Last one in the room and first one out. Two medium length papers (8-10p) and a take home essay final. Attendance required. Fairly interesting!

Teachers freshman core courses like they're senior electives. Won't teach, expects you to digest perfectly 60+ pages of dense philosophy per night, ready to discuss. Will make you feel dumb. I took two classes with Sofer and each one was so fun while also challenging and thought-provoking. You can tell he cares about the material he's teaching. Not the professor, and probably not the class for you if you don't care about English/poetry. Very understanding about late assignments and missing classes as long as you communicate properly.

At first I was not a big fan of Sofer, he hyped up how hard he would grade his papers. But he gives great feedback and everyone does well. There is a pop quiz every class for the reading but they are very doable if have an idea of what is actually going on. He loves discussions and asks very engaging questions. TAKE HIM! Very theatrical. Expect to read and have a fair share of pop quizzes. Expectations are reasonable, overall very nice guy. Participate every once in a while to be in good standings.

Very good at explaining the topic. Relatively easy if you pay attention to class. There are no readings for this class and homeworks are optional. Quizzes are exactly about what is given in class.

I got more than I was expecting from her class. I fell in love with the book we were reading because she illustrated it with funny videos, imaginative conversations and activities. She has high expectations, but it's for the benefit of students. Her classes are fun and engaging.
Excellent topics with clear, consistent information. Available to students for help and approachable.

Seemed to have too many favorites- called on the same students all the time. I didn't feel very engaged in the class, nor did I feel my ideas were very welcome. She was very helpful when I would speak with her outside of class, however.

Great class- do the work and get a good grade.

very abrasive, solipsistic and not at all helpful .  she "teaches" through intimidation, takes forever to give back graded papers. la profesora likes to hide behind this veil of feminism yet it ends up she's just mean.  steer clear of her class...you've been warned.

Very sweet man but a horrible professor. The final grade is based on one midterm and one final worth 60% of the grade. Repeated material for weeks but introduced three new units in the last classes.  Accessible during office hours but makes students feel unwelcome by writing off challenging concepts as "easy" or "simple", overall a terrible class.

Professor Konishi is very sweet and knowledgeable of the field of economics, but he is very unclear and hard to understand at times. Sweet man. but pretty unclear, answering questions either "easy, that's common sense" or "graduate level, don't worry about it" when we did need to worry about it, often left us further confused. comment_Rating: Prof Konishi is super nice! He's clear on the subject matter, and I've learned a lot from his class. He's accessible out of classes. Mo is truly wonderful and very demanding. Learned to read critically and think in depth. She is also very funny and the class was awesome. (also the class was 4048)

Gives long lectures but provides a direct transcript of the lecture notes, which are the most helpful. Tests and quizzes are all online, and a clear schedule is outlined every week. Overall a good professor for a core class.

Prof Mo did a very good job teaching a large online course. The pre-recorded lectures could be dry at times, but she provided detailed notes that were helpful for exams. comment_Rating: Wonderful class and fantastic prof. Highly recommended

Math is not my strong suit, so taking Prof Hulse proved to be a godsend. He holds office hours regularly, is easily accessible via email, and gave detailed explanations of complicated math problems. comment_Rating: Calc 1. Great professor, kind, understanding, funny. Would recommend.

Professor Hulse taught Calc 1. It was a huge course, so there were multiple different teachers for it. He was very funny, and from a teaching perspective he was adequate at teaching information well. He also was available for office hours and helped me a lot (calc is hard). Taking him for lecture is a good idea.

Hulse's class was a random hodge-podge of disconnected math concepts that were poorly explained. Hulse was easily accessible, but he has an arrogant streak that sometimes made him rude and obnoxious. The work for the course is brutal. You'll dedicate everything you have only to come up short with a poor grade. I regret ever taking his course.
One of the most compassionate and understanding professors ever!
Good professor, 5/5, very polite and kind. Class isn't too hard either which is a big plus.
Great professor, took his creative writing class. Very understanding, organized, and clearly cares about all students. Is not unreasonable.

Dunn is a pretty decent lecturer, and makes lots of time for office hours. She does not respond to emails, though. There's a lot of content in this class, but I think she graded fairly and gave decent help before tests and such. She drops the lowest quiz, test, and homework grade, which is very helpful

Professor Dunn's genetics class is EXTREMELY difficult - she's really nice and clearly passionate about the subject but her tests are so hard and there's such so much information she packs in with little help on how to study. She does drop the lowest grades which is nice but I definitely shed a lot of tears in this class, no doubt.

The wording on her exams can be pretty tricky and the questions themselves can sometimes be difficult, but if you pay attention in class and take advantage of office hours, you will be completely fine. Try to get to know her too... she is one of the most caring, down to earth professors you'll ever meet and she really wants you to succeed.
Her exams aren't easy and straight forward, and her wording can be a bit confusing. However, if you pay attention to the class lectures and study the slides in depth then you will do well.

Tests are hard, but Dunn has clear grading policy and doesn't stray from syllabus at all. Also a very kind professor who wants to see you learn. Dunn is your best option for Molecules & Cells, but the class is difficult. That's just how it is tbh.

Overall, Professor Dunn is very knowledgeable and has great office hours, and she cares about her students' success. However, some of her test questions are very weirdly worded, and even if you know the material, you are likely to get some wrong.

It took me about 2 months, 1 rough exam and a few tough quizzes to get used to her exam style because honestly she will try to trick you. If you know everything on the slides and everything that comes out of her mouth you'll be fine for exams but get ready to work. But, she lets you drop one grade from every category which has been a life saver.
ratingTags_Rating: Clear grading criteria--Lecture heavy--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: The way that Professor Dunn presents her content can be quite frustrating at times, but she truly wants her students to succeed and is the most kindhearted, caring person.

She can sometimes be all over the place but if you pay attention to the lectures, use the homeworks as studying material and study from the slides and your notes you will do really well on this class.
ratingTags_Rating: Lots of homework--Lecture heavy--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: Professor Dunn is a good lecturer who incorporates real-world examples and relevant stories, and the tests and quizzes are usually fine as long as you study. However, there are trick questions, and some are so tricky that she even tricks herself, and has to end up removing them from the final scores. Overall, nothing exceptional, but not bad.

She's a good lecturer and is very sweet / helpful outside of class. She wants her students to do well, but she seems to care more about tricking her students with questions that have never been mentioned before in class / the power points

Do not take her for genetics. Tests are impossible, even when you put the work in. Lot of questions are designed to trick you so you get mediocre grades even if you know the material well. She is also very disorganized. She's nice but horrible professor
ratingTags_Rating: Lots of homework--Skip class? You won't pass.--Test heavy

comment_Rating: I loved Dunn as a person but I 100% would NEVER take her class if I was given the choice again. Exams are very hard, questions are worded tricky and multiple answer questions are given even if only 1 answer. Cares more about catching cheaters than students passing. Again, super nice person and caring but class is not worth it. Dont take

Her disorganization for a type A like me is very aggravating and detracts from learning a bit. Bad at responding to emails, too. BUT she is VERY caring and willing to listen to you if you're having trouble. Exams aren't impossible, but are designed to think outside the box a bit. Required discussions and disc HW is very annoying. Good drop policy.
Cool person, bit disorganized

She is amazing, please take her class! She cares so much about her students, and if you get to know her she will be a resource for your entire four years at BC. Her class is challenging because of the material, but if you put in the effort it will be worth it. By far my favorite professor at BC. She's crazy in the best way and slightly disorganized

She breaks down concepts that make them simple to understand. Read the book if you do not understand something, because her slides correspond very closely with material in the book. She is a little disorganized though, and her exams and powerpoint presentations usually have spelling or other errors. She also is helpful during office hours.
ratingTags_Rating: ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--GRADED BY FEW THINGS--LECTURE HEAVY

comment_Rating: I was nervous after having Professor Dunn for Molecules and Cells, but was pleasantly surprised. Her slides are clear and cohesive, and if you study them, the exams are fine. She's funny and sassy too, making lectures not boring. I really liked her; this was probably my favorite class this semester.
Her tests are mainly aimed to trick you, instead of solely based on whether you know the information or not. She's a very nice person just not a good professor

Professor Dunn is an amazing person, a great lecturer and a super smart scientist. My only problem with the class was her lack of organization. She would make multiple mistakes on exams, announcing typos and questions changes in the middle of tests. Also, she changed the grading policy in the middle of the year.
ratingTags_Rating: Skip class? You won't pass.--Amazing lectures--Caring

comment_Rating: She's a great person and not so great professor. She genuinely cares about her students. Her teaching style and exams, which are often riddled with mistakes, can take some time to get use to. I recommend studying the slides. Don't buy the textbook. The material can be difficult, but there's plenty of resources to help you.

With all of my respect, this is not a very great professor to start with your first year. Even though she has her office hours, there are literally at least 10 kids inside the office with you. She has too many slides but you pretty much learn nothing from them. It is mostly self-study! Be alert! You may sleep in class...

A super nice, humble woman whose intelligence shines as she explains simple concepts in a very comprehensive way. She was my bio prof during the first semester of my freshman year, and she made a content-heavy lecture class easy to swallow. She cares a ton about her students and will form a great relationship with you if you show interest.

Slide show presentations are confusing and rarely in coherent sequential order, and this professor insists that the class study from them. Professor tends to have difficulty giving straight answers and doesn't always remain consistent. Lots of trick questions on quizzes and exams, but you can get used to the style if you pay attention.

I took this class to satisfy my History II requirement and I loved it! The class really takes what you read and applies it to real world situations. The professor was extremely engaging and although there was a LOT of reading, it was pretty stimulating and the conversations flowed in class.

Great guy and professor. Clearly cares a lot about his teaching and students. Lots of reading, but you'll manage if you don't do some of it. I strongly recommend taking his History of the Present class for history II credit.

Professor Bourg is a very kind guy who was my advisor and topic seminar professor. The History of Nonviolence is a really cool subject that he has a lot to share about and it's just a Pass/Fail course with about 10 other kids, so you can get to know each other pretty well. If you do the readings, make sure to divide them up, as they are often long!

Really nice and caring guy. Very interested in student opinions, and makes class discussions collaborative and engaging. There do tend to be a lot of reading, but as long as you have a general understanding of the material it's easy to get a good grade. Highly recommend.
Hard class, lots of lectures. But very engaging and interesting
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Get ready to read--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: The lit core was a class on fairytales so the readings for each class were short and easy to comprehend. There were 2 essays the semester which were graded harshly. In her feedback she was very general of improvements to make which were unhelpful for future essays. Even during meetings she were vague on what to improve to do better in the class.
ratingTags_Rating: Participation matters--Graded by few things--Tough grader

comment_Rating: Dr. Ernst is a very well-spoken, and organized professor. She encourages group discussion and creates a really relaxed, open, learning environment. She assigned 3 major essays this semester and provided great feedback on my first drafts that allowed me to succeed in the final draft. She also teaches at Emmanuel College where I took this course.
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--Participation matters--Clear grading criteria

comment_Rating: Professor CK gave incredibly clear explanations and examples throughout all of his lectures. He used guided notes which made class go at a very efficient pace. He is extremely caring and available outside of class multiple times per week. He is also super funny and made sure to take occasional breaks throughout lectures to entertain the class.

I had him in my first semester at BC, and from my experience and what I've heard from others, CK is likely the nicest and most caring professor at this school. He will do anything to help students that want to succeed; and he makes this very clear. His fill in the blank lecture notes are so helpful.

CK is super nice, funny, and kind. He uses guided notes in his lecture which make the material very clear. He's great at explaining the material. Tests honestly aren't that hard, just make sure to master the checklists he posts before each midterm. He's an excellent professor!
CK gets to the point but still tries to make lectures fun here and there. HW sets due every discussion (once a week) and occasional quizzes but he'll warn you beforehand

CK is one of my favorite math teachers or professors I have ever had. He's nice, his class is fun, and he gives great explanations. The class is very easy to follow along with due to his style of lecture (with guided notes) and students will not be overloaded with work. It's been the best math class I've taken in years.
Lectures are fairly disorganized. Group work is emphasized but CK's explanations are normally confusing and don't help much. CK is nice and quick to respond but can be a really tough grader.
ratingTags_Rating: Group projects--Lots of homework--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: CK is one of the best math professors I have ever had. If he is teaching any class, be sure to take him. He is a talented teacher, willing to explain anything to students, and is really hilarious in class. He certainly makes you drill the material but is always there to help.

Extremely good at explaining the material. Attendance isn't mandatory, but his lectures are really good. He's also really nice about meeting outside of class if you miss a lecture to go over the notes. The homework can be long (around 20 problems) but its only due once a week if that.
ratingTags_Rating: ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--GRADED BY FEW THINGS--LECTURE HEAVY

comment_Rating: Professor is very intellectual and interested in the content she teaches. She expects the same out of her students. I learned a lot but don't take this class unless you are looking to go into academia relating to philosophy or political science, not taught at the intro level. Tons of reading and only graded on 3 tough memorized in-class essays.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Get ready to read--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: Hetzner gets a lot of grief for her tendency to go off on tangents during lectures, but I genuinely think there is a method to her madness. She is a super intellectual woman, and the anecdotes she ties in typically make you think differently. Beware that doing the readings is absolutely necessary and final grade is 3 essays. Office hours amazing!
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Graded by few things--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: I love Prof Hetzner! As others have said, the grade is based on 3 essays, but she values improvement, and if you meet with her during office hours, you will find the essays come a lot easier. She is a fair grader who wants to see you succeed. She is super sweet and caring. I would highly recommend the course!
ratingTags_Rating: Respected--Graded by few things--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: Prof Hetzner is a very caring and nice person. She is easily accessible outside of class and willing to help. With that being said, the course is graded entirely upon 3 essays, each worth 33% of your grade. She is a very tough grader and can easily get off-topic during her lectures. You need to do the reading and pay attention in class.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Get ready to read--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: she is such a sweet human and you can tell that she cares a lot about what she is teaching. very few assignments for grading and you need to legit regurgitate the texts for the in class essays. talks about her community involvement a ton. sounds like jane lynch too
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Caring--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: She is impressive and accomplished, and her lecture style reflects her vast knowledge of the subject. The grade is composed of 3 essays (in class) and participation, and although she grades harshly on this, she values improvement and will take this into account with final grades. She is very interesting, and her office hours are worth the time.

Professor Sutherland is an okay professor but she assigns so much homework. She is also a huge fan of quizzes. At one point there was a quiz every single class for a week. She assigns far too much work for a Latin class. I would not recommend her.
Expects too much from students looking to fulfill core. Only good for dedicated Latin majors looking to do translations and tests in class. No variation in classroom activities.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Test heavy--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: She's a good professor, but expects a fair amount out of you (at least in intermediate 2). A good person overall, would recommend.

Dr. Sutherland is a wonderful teacher and I would absolutely take her for Latin again. The class is homework and quiz heavy but if you put in the work outside of class you have every chance to do well. I would suggest going to office hours as soon as you get confused because the material does become difficult as you move on.

Professor Eisenfeld is one of my favorite professors at BC, and my favorite non-major professor. She's a very knowledgable person, and helps you to learn Latin through her various teaching methods catered to the class she has. She is also extremely kind, and genuinely cares about the people in the class. If you have the chance take her class.

The only graded assignments were three essay exams. I put in a lot of work on them and received a B+ on everyone. He is caring, but there is also a lot of reading. He Will try to get everyone to participate, so you cant doze off either.

Prof. Haskin is wonderfully inspiring, caring, and fair. Detailed instructions/feedback on papers. Beautiful selection of readings that is culturally inclusive. Respects students and cares about their well-being. He remembers people, and a good mentor outside of class. He introduced me to literary role models and helped refine my poetry craft.

An exceptional, brilliant and inspiring professor & an equally magnificent human being. He was my favorite professor at BC. Take him. He will help you learn as much about yourself as about the course.

One of BC's hidden treasures!!! Professor Haskin was truly a joy to take class with. I can't imagine any tome in the English language being more thick or more difficult to study than Paradise Lost - but to see how energetic and at times downright giddy he
Prof. Haskin was my all-time favorite prof.  I learned more in his class than any other class I took in college.
Very thoughtful. Cares about his students. Still remembers me semesters afterwards and I didn't even do well in the class.

This professor is amazing, definitely one of the best I have had at BC. He made me really love Milton's work despite the difficulties of the texts. The floor is always open to differing opinions and you will never feel like something you say is dumb.

Maybe this is a hot take from the other reviews, but Prof. Jorring is a very average professor. He did not meet my expectations for how I thought he would going into the class. Your entire grade is based on 3 exams, with the final being almost half of your grade (40%). He was never available for office hours and put everything on the TAs.

Great professor. Homework before each class for completion grade, and he would spend the first half of class reviewing the homework answering any questions, and going over the correct answers. Loved his class.
ratingTags_Rating: Amazing lectures --Clear grading criteria--Gives good feedback

comment_Rating: AMAZING Professor! A must to take at BC.

Great professor, his lectures are easy to follow and he's great with teaching the material. He's also readily available for advice after class. Honestly, a very easy class if you just pay attention and do the homework. Hope this helps.

Awesome teacher. Definitely recommend. Very helpful and wants to see his students succeed. Gives a lot of practice for tests. Allows study sheets for tests and makes it very clear what we should know for the test. Very funny guy. He made his lectures interesting and engaging.

Prof Jorring is awesome! His lectures are easy to follow and he does a really good job of explaining difficult concepts. It's evident that he wants his students to understand the material and doesn't make you feel dumb for asking questions. He's also super smart and funny. The tests are hard but if you study and do the homework you should be fine.

Jorring's class is about as straightforward as it gets. His lectures build concepts logically, and he is great at answering questions. His tests aren't easy, but if you study you will get a good grade. There are no surprises, everything will be like the slides, HW, and study guides. HW takes maybe 30min/wk. Highly reccomend.

Jorring knows a lot about the topic. He is very good at explaining and will give you enough problems in class and homeworks so that you can do well on the exam. Exams aren't easy but if you know how to do the problems he gives in class and homeworks you'll do well. Homeworks don't take much time. Don't even buy the book, you'll never use it.
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--Graded by few things--Caring

comment_Rating: This class is manageable if you keep up with the plays (if you do not want to read them do NOT take it because you have to to do well). Some materials are hard to find on Canvas, but overall recommend for art core.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Group projects

comment_Rating: Took Intro to Theatre with her - if you read all the plays (there are a lot, but they're never too difficult) and put in effort, it's an easy A for art core. Sometimes it felt like an acting class, which I wasn't comfortable with, and I wasn't a fan of the group midterm. But she's very passionate and accessible! Theatre crazy but in a good way
A true gem at Boston College. Workloads are manageable. If you show up, straight-A. Highly recommend taking her class.
He is great in teaching practice work using python, givng me great hope of transition from business to computer science.
He is good

Nice enough guy and a pretty easy grader, but in this class he made the midterm extremely easily graded (don't know if anybody got below an 85) and everyone let their guard down, but then on the final exam the average score was a 73 because it was way more difficult. However, if you take the final he doesn't let you get below a B- for the semester.

Dong is not a good teacher. I don't think I learned anything this semester in finance and feel unprepared for upper-division finance classes. He is also arrogant. Hybrid class. Class is just lectures, but is pretty interesting. HW is pretty easy and helps reinforce class concepts. Quizzes are assigned after class and due the same night, but are simple. ratingTags_Rating: Accessible outside class--Graded by few things--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: Funny, interesting, overall good professor.
Great lecturer who gives fair tests and not too big of a workload. Makes concepts easy to understand. Overall informative and easy class.
The lectures were pretty fast, but the examples were really helpful. Available for office hours, and gave final review packets exactly like all the tests.

Miao Liu is the goat. Seriously, take his class. He's funny in lectures. He prints out lecture notes and practice problems for every unit. His lectures are engaging. And his tests are exactly what you do in class. Not too much work, only studying for exams and one problem set a week.

Professor Liu explains things really well because he does not assume that anyone has prior finance/accounting knowledge coming into the class. His lectures are easy to follow, his explanations are thorough, and he prints out notes where you fill in the blanks during the lecture. Problem set once a wk, super manageable. Definitely take his class!

Professor Liu is one of my all time favorite professors! Very clear in lecture, funny and cares about his students. And just in general a very nice person. Would definitely recommend taking Financial Acct w/ him

Probably my favorite professor at BC thus far. Great guy, makes a boring topic somewhat interesting. Gives great guided notes and practice exams that are exactly like the exams. Got an A without doing a lot of work at all. Just study the notes and feel good about practice exam and you'll be more than fine for the exams.
Class was difficult but really liked the professor. Willing to give second chances and help students out. Definitely take him for financial accounting

One of my all time favorite professors. I would highly recommend taking his class. Professor Liu is very nice and approachable and arguably one of the best financial accounting professors at BC. His lectures are very straight forward and he provides guided notes and handouts at every class which are both very helpful in preparing for exams.

Prof Liu is very kind to his students and helps them understand the material. Classes are lecture based, but he tries to add humor to an objectively boring topic, and does not assign an overwhelming amount of homework. He gives guided note packets and practice exams, which really help to follow along and be prepared for exams.

(class was an enduring questions course) gives hard papers, relies on class participation, and will challenge your thinking. is available for office hours but they aren't always super helpful (particularly for writing papers). no technology allowed in class, only notebooks for notes. really nice guy and a good teacher.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: Great prof with a good sense of humor and he loves what he does. He has a good mix of lecturing and discussing. I took 1776 with him and the grade was 6 papers and participation/attendance, so you do need to know the readings to do well. However, you don't need break your back reading every page because lectures will fill in the blanks for you.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Graded by few things--Caring

comment_Rating: Best prof at BC. Knows so much and is very nice. Exams are extremely fair and if you put in work you'll get an A. So engaging, makes school interesting again.

Best professor I've had in CSOM. Prepares you well for the exams and they are open note. He took the time to get to know all of our names and he's super friendly. He values participation and doesn't make you feel dumb if you answer incorrectly. Will always re-explain things if you need. Lectures are fast-paced, but super thorough.

Fully online, asynchronous class so I can't give a full rating, but the lectures he pre-recorded were very helpful, and he went out of his way to record himself doing 3-6 practice problems for every weekly module which helps a lot especially when you're doing all your learning for the class without interaction with the professor or other students.

Prof. Magubane is one of the most genuinely caring professors I've had at BC. If you want to take a class on race and/or sociology, I highly recommend her. She makes class interesting and engaging, and she is very laid back

As a Professor? She's great. No attendance, lets you use laptops, very approachable, etc. As a class? Insanely difficult. You have to memorize nearly ~600 pages for each exam (there are 4, but she drops the lowest one) and it's impossible to do unless this is the only class you're taking. In sum, great professor, but the class is way too hard.

Very interesting material and although there are a lot of lectures, she makes them interesting. Lots of memorization needed for exams, but it is very doable. Also learned a lot in her class. Love that woman.

LOVED Professor Magubane for AWP! Honestly, the exams are all about memorization, so as long as you study the names and major themes for the lectures of each unit you should be fine. Her and the TA are also always available for help

If you want to learn more about Race or take a social science, you NEED to take African World Perspectives with Professor Magubane. She is one of my favorite professors at BC and cares so much for her students. The course material is easy enough to get an A and interesting to make you come to class. Also, get to know her, she's so cool!

This is literally the worst professor at BC. AVOID. anyone else would be easier to listen to. She doesn't know how to turn on her computer or anything with an electric pulse running through it. She will talk about herself, her kids or her time at bently the entire class and then slam you with a group project worth 40% of your grade at the end.

comment_Rating: Personally, I was confused by her explanations of most concepts in class, though if you naturally understand accounting she's probably a great teacher. Makes contents extra complicated than it should be. Gets super confusing in class but could understand if I just read the textbook without going to class.
Super nice and caring professor. The lectures are pretty great, but there is a lot of homework and exams are pretty difficult.

Prof. Kelly provides real-world experiences in her lectures and also explains arcane concepts in accounting that may be confusing to someone who doesn't know accounting in a clear and concise way. She's definitely not easy though but is willing to help at all times.

She presents as being available and kind, but in reality her exams questions are worded weird and she puts all the blame on the students, without accepting any responsibility. comment_Rating: Overall not a good teacher. Grade is almost entirely tests that she does not make herself. Study guides are super inconsistent from test to test. You can study for weeks for her exams and still not do well. Most people get Cs at best on exams. Not a great teacher but unfortunately the only option for Anatomy.

She is by far the worst teacher Ive had, she is very confrontational, holds students to unrealistic expectations during a pandemic and entirely online classes. The biggest indicator of her bad teaching is the fact that she is okay with over half her class failing the same exam every year, and even seems proud of it at times

Very passive aggressive. I did pretty good in the class and still felt like she expected more from me. Shes the type of teacher that expects 110% even though you have 5 other classes. You have to study 2-1 week before exam or you might not get the grade you want. Your grade depends heavily on exam grades.

comment_Rating: she gives dense, poorly organized lectures with outdated powerpoints and information inconsistent with the textbook. decently nice to converse with, provides flexibility if necessary, however not open to criticism whatsoever. overall, class was very difficult and she made it no easier, she did not teach any better than the info textbook provided.

Good professor and very caring of his students but the class is not easy. He will fly through the material as if everyone already knows it. Will spend a lot of time going over quantum mechanics and physics. Tests are very difficult, no matter how many times you go over the readings, the slides, and lecture notes, you will not get an A.
Great Honors Chemistry Professor! Extremely available for office hours and helps you get through difficult material at a fast pace!
ratingTags_Rating: Clear grading criteria--Test heavy--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: If you can review the textbook problems at the back of the chapters before exams, youre set. Test questions were very similar. The curve was to be a B- on the syllabus but bumped up to a B+ !

Personally, I found office hours to be extremely helpful and he answered my questions with care, and overall grading policy was great. I was unsure/intimidated at first but office hours cleared up my confusion and I found the exams to be relatively predictable.

Thinks everyone in the class is already an expert on the subject material and is no help in office hours- just makes you feel dumb. Puts things on exams that have never been touched on in lecture or in the textbook.

I had Professor for Gen Chem II and thought he was a great teacher. He's always willing to help and his exams are extremely straight forward. Reading the textbook is fundamental in this course to gain a solid understanding before watching the lecture.
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--Respected--Get ready to read

comment_Rating: Professor is an expert and organizes lectures well in an easy to understand format. Really inspired my thinking. Your notes are the slides from class and his exams are thorough. Pretty helpful when it comes to answering questions outside of class, but won't spoonfeed you the answers. Math heavy material.

His lectures tend to drone on for all 75 minutes. He gets unnecessarily irked when we pack up to leave once time is up (as if we don't have other classes to go to) if he's still lecturing. Don't care much for his attitude. He's somewhat dismissive towards students and just seems like one of those professors that doesn't want to be here that much.

(at UC Davis) Flexible with COVID related situations. Terrible professor otherwise. Unclear explanations of material during class, gets annoyed when he has to explain why he skips steps in example problems. 2nd midterm average was a 62%, which really shows his awful teaching skills. Easier to watch YouTube tutorials.

Doesn't know how to teach and doesn't answer any questions in lectures. Doesn't provide clear methods on how to solve a problem and many times will teach something for a good portion of the 50 minute lecture and then say "that won't be on the midterm" or "you don't need to know that though". Waste of time.
He cannot explain anything and grades harshly. He doesn't know how to teach or answer questions usefully. The whole class struggled and we never broke a 75 average on a test. Do not recommend EVER

Overall the class was fine and definitely not too hard though I had already taken Probability in the math department (MATH4426) and had a really good understanding of most of what we did. If I had not taken this before hand it would have been brutal because he did the bare minimum for explaining the math behind things making it harder in the end.

Avoid this class if looking to take it for natural science requirement. A lot, a lot, a lot of memorization. If you want to do well, study weeks in advance for every test. Otherwise, an incredibly understanding and caring professor. One of my favorite professors so far at BC. If you're up for a challenge, I would definitely take this class.

Gives really great lectures that never miss anything. Super clear and pretty funny if you like dry humor. Exams are basically just memorization, so if that's not your strong suit I recommend studying weeks in advance. So. Many. Office hours. All around great guy and professor.
Prof Dacosta's tests a very straight forward and fair. He's a nice guy and his lectures were easy to follow

This guy is the best lecturer Ive ever had and his class is well organized especially for a large lecture. It is super interesting, the only thing is he writes the hardest tests man or god has ever seen and his grading system is brutal.

I found it very hard to connect with the the material we covered in lecture; lectures are easy to understand and follow, but not engaging for me personally. The content is very vocabulary-heavy, specific, and spelling matters (this can result in deductions)!
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Test heavy--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: Lectures were really clear and engaging. He includes a lot of cool videos about what you're learning that keep class interesting. Exams were difficult, but very straight-forward if you study. The tree project was a fun way to get connected to nature on campus.
Not necessarily a bad professor, but definitely not for me. I would recommend taking the other prof for eco evo if you are not up for a challenge.
