Wide selection of novellas, novels, poems, and films in class, mostly modern. He's from Chicago and assigns a lot of Chicago writers (Gwendolyn Brooks, Stuart Dybek). Very good at paraphrasing and expanding on students' half-baked opinions and moderating the discussion. Humorous and easy-going character. Gives detailed feedback. Very considerate.

Professor Rotella was awesome! Reasonable amount of reading and writing and compassionate with students' needs. Fair grader and available outside of class to go over essays and feedback. Class very discussion-based, with little to no lectures.

One of the most interesting, intelligent, and peculiar professors at BC. Father Weiss expects a lot from you but in the best way possible. His PULSE class is very unique and will push you to think about the world and yourself in new ways.

Enrolling in his Courage to Know class was the best thing that I ever did. He cares so much and wants his students to succeed. I would tell any person to try to get into a class with him. He does cold calls, so be aware of that but they aren't too hard and are more opinion-based than anything. I am taking another one of his classes next semester.

Based on what I've heard from others, Weiss is 100% the best CTK instructor. Really nice environment and we had a lot of great discussions. Fair amount of reading, and he does cold calls to make sure you did them, but you can easily BS that. You'll ace the papers if you do what he asks.

WEISS is a GEM. Very considerate of student life and wants people to succeed. Get ready to read a lot, but mostly for your own comprehension and understanding. Does some lecturing but I always found it very helpful and cohesive. Reminds me of my grandpa. Definitely need to participate but I think that just helps you stay on top of workload.
He was the worst professor at BC.I would avoid his class.
Good readings, good lectures.  Engages students, provokes thoughts with interesting insight.  Speaking up in class will earn his favor. He is a good professor and it shows.
Extremely nice in person but does have favorites in class. If you're it, great...if you're not....

Without a doubt the finest professor I've had in 4 years at BC.  Rigorous in the best sense, high expectations, engaging, and truly knowledgeable about the material he teaches.  He cares not only about the issues his classes address, but also about positively affecting the lives of his students.
If you want a professor who cares about you as a human being, take his classes. Prof. Weiss strives to embody the values he teaches. He's a rare breed.

Painting 1. Spent a LOT of time on the projects but was enjoyable. A few write ups during the semester but nothing awful. Doesn't expect you to be an amazing painter, and meets you where you are at. Fair grading and very instructional. Great for fulfilling art credit requirement in my opinion.

Professor Biswas is intelligent, caring, and has a strong understanding of comp. org/architecture. While her class is boring, you really will learn a lot about low level circuit design. Exams/quizzes are fairly difficult, but over 50% of the grade is from homework/labs which are quite fair.
She is very energetic and organized.
Prof. Biswas was great in explaining concepts and pace was good as well.

This is an excellent class where we design a processor and Prof. Biswas did an amazing job of teaching this course. She uses technology to effectively create notes. Her enthusiasm for this subject is felt by the students. Some of us have developed deep interest in this field after attending her lectures.

Does a great job of teaching pretty monotonous and tedious material and making it interesting. If you attend every class its not hard to do well. The parts where she has you write code along with her are particularly helpful. Would 100% take for computer organization.
Many quizzes are difficult and in fact, actually make up a higher percentage of the grade than the midterm. The professor's note-taking ability is awful. The content isn't that hard though.
ratingTags_Rating: Clear grading criteria--Lots of homework--Test heavy

comment_Rating: This is a unique course and Profesor Biswas does an amazing job in writing the code in class with the students to boost their confidence.

Prof Biswas codes in the class and encourages students to code along. Those who follow her advice will really benefit as she says that the best way to learn Python is by coding. I felt it was a well balanced course. Most of the professors just show slides and write code on the board but she takes the effort and courage to code live in the class.

Got a C in the class. Lectures were consistently mediocre. Not the best professor but not a bad choice either. If you are good at coding I am sure you would do great, but for those of us not STEM savvy it was pretty hard. Starts out super easy and then very quickly the class gets very hard.
She just doesn't seem interested in the course and doesn't really stimulate excitement. If you study for this class you should be fine it's not too bad, just very "bleh".

Caring professor with amazing feedback on papers. Readings aren't necessary but are very helpful for context. Pretty easy A- and a very doable A if you do the work and address his critiques for future papers. He also made the final paper optional if you already have an A for the class, which was phenomenal.

One of the nicest professors I've ever met. He really is an awesome guy. You are graded by a small number of things (4 papers and a cumulative participation/attendance score), but if you try you will do well, and he gives great feedback on your papers to help you do better on the future ones. I would take him again and again he is so engaging.
Awesome professor, but even better person. You're graded by a few things, but so long as you make a decent effort outside of class, it's fairly straightforward.
Easy A, lenient grader, fun person all around, very accessible outside of class. Did all papers the night before and still got an A in the class. Highly recommend Prof. Mcgraw

Great professor and very engaging. You'll be excited to go to his class. Your grade is mainly based on participation and the papers. Paper topics make you think, but you learn a lot. He grades papers kind of hard because he pushes you to be a better writer but basically doesn't give below a B. If you earn an A he will give you an A. Would recommend

In a word: awesome. Enthusiastic lectures, fair grader, gives great feedback, very well organized, and easily accessible outside of class. As long as you excel on the essays and participate, you will succeed in his course. McGraw stands out as a very professional instructor who cares about his students. I loved his course.

I had him for Comparative Politics for my major requirements. He doesn't allow laptops which was a bummer to me, but attendance is mandatory at all. Very fun lecturer, and very understanding/caring person. Very flexible with deadlines as well! Just email him. Outside of class is he a really sweet and caring person. His lectures were ok, course 4/5.

Prof Christensen is a great teacher for a great class. He taught us a lot about the broad field of globalization but made it understandable and interesting. Definitely one of the better classes I've taken with an engaging professor. He does take a bit to send back assignments, but he's a good grader.

I took this class because everyone said this professor is very nice. Turns out he is the worst professor i have ever had at BC. Very irresponsible, never replies to emails, fun lecturers but very tough graders and give bad grades for no comments and reasons.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Lecture heavy--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: Easy A-, difficult A. Flexible deadlines, no attendance, fun and interesting class. Doesn't allow laptops in class. I wouldn't take him if you're looking for an Easy A but you shouldn't have any difficulty getting an A- with some effort.

Doesn't take attendance. Lecture almost every class, very little participation required. Grade based on two medium length papers (8-10 pages), one long research project (20 pages), and a take home essay final. Super chill guy. Definitely a communist. Legitimately interesting

Very interesting class and an amazing professor. He grades fairly and the effort you put in will be reflected in your grade. He has fun with his midterm and it's take home. Midterm allows you to put your knowledge to use and also have fun with it. Would highly recommend taking his class.

Prof. Christensen is my favorite professor at BC. I've had him for multiple classes and have worked with him outside of class as well. He is engaging, intelligent, and not scared to critique the status quo, whether it be at BC or the broader world. You must take Prof. Christensen while you are at BC. You won't regret it.
ratingTags_Rating: Accessible outside class--Get ready to read--Inspirational

comment_Rating: Geniunely one of the best people I have ever met. In another life I would've been his friend. Not only is he an amazing teacher that loves what he is doing but he actual cares about his students. He helped me out a lot, in and out of the classroom, and I really want to take more of his classes in the future. An incredible teacher and human.
Really passionate and engaging. He's not afraid to comment/critique the university and is aware of his space. Awesome guy
Possibly my favorite professor at BC. His class was hard but if you work on your papers you will be rewarded. Take him!!!

Took Christensen for several classes - Globalization, Intro IS, Social Movements.  He was one of the best teachers I had at BC.  Gets students excited about issues and lets you write interesting papers.  Final/Midterm can be difficult, but if you pay attention and participate, you will be fine.
Take Prof. Christensen before you leave BC

Professor Feldman is one of the best professors I have had during my time at BC. Her FAST II class is not easy, and attendance is definitely mandatory, but I would 100% recommend to any accounting major. Feldman cares about all of her students, and is extremely knowledgable about the CPA track.

Be prepared to be cold-called every single day and DO THE HOMEWORK. The midterm and final matter a lot for your grade, but the exams are extremely straight forward and there are no curveballs. As long as you do the homework and study, there's no reason you should do poorly. Every exam question is a different version of something you already saw.

Feldman is the best financial accounting prof in the department. She prints out lecture slides for every chapter and explains difficult concepts really well. There are online reading quizzes before every class and lots of hw. exams are easy if you do the hw and understand the concepts. she also grades generously.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Lots of homework

comment_Rating: Hardest Class offered in CSOM hands down but Diane will get you through it if you work hard. This class will require a LOT of effort, studying and staying on top of your game. it is NOT for the weak and she will say that on day 1. If you work hard and show her that she will give you at least a B. You WILL learn ACCT or die trying in this class.

(First year writing) She truly cared about the topics and was super nice. Lectures were often a bit dry when we weren't actively working on a paper but otherwise were ok. There is an opportunity to revise a paper as well as extra credit assignment which is helpful if you didn't do to well on one of the 4 major assignments (3 essays all 5-8 pages).

Very nice professor, the only drawback to the class is that the papers make up the majority of the grade. That being said, there's lots of time to complete the papers and great feedback with the chance to revise an essay at the end of the semester for a better grade. Overall a very caring professor that genuinely wants her students to succeed
Essays are graded pretty harshly but plenty of easy homework assignments and extra credit opportunities. Use them to your advantage. Very nice teacher.
Very nice professor who makes sure that you are succeeding. She always has extra credit opportunities and there is rarely ever homework besides the essays that are due.
Okay class. Quizzes are kind of hard to do well on. Lots of reading but if you do it youll be fine.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: Really difficult. So much reading. Do yourself a favor and DO NOT TAKE
ratingTags_Rating: Lots of homework--Get ready to read--Tough grader

comment_Rating: Professor B is phenomenal. I earned As both semesters. The trick? Participate, participate, participate. Attend his office hours, and it will make an enormous difference. He is extremely passionate about the material. His exams are easy so long as you read the primary sources and understand that he is making a historical argument each lecture.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Test heavy

comment_Rating: I took a Globalization. It was a lecture class. His lectures are very straightforward (all on ppt). Participation matters, but because it's such a big class, he considers office hours as participation. The exams were difficult. The final is a take home comprised of multiple choice and 2 essays.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Clear grading criteria--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: The lectures are very long and pretty boring but he is a super nice professor and super approachable. He is very knowledgeable in his subjects and is easy to have a conversation with. That being said, if you really want to be engaged in a class I wouldn't recommend.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Group projects--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: Nice guy but long boring lectures, lectures would always run long. Tough grader, shows clear favoritism. Turns everything into a political debate.
Had him in a complex problems course with another professor. super nice and understanding, really cares about his students but lecture heavy and can get monotone. Fair grader though

one of two professors in complex questions course (crisis & storytelling in the age of climate change- natural science and lit core). he was funny during lecture but that entire class was just lecture. nice grader

Very rigid in what he expects in discussion, has a pre-decided idea of how conversation should go and if it doesn't then class falls really flat. Assigns a lot of make-work that hits on hot topics but doesn't really add to your knowledge or grasp of the class's subject matter. Can be really dismissive and disrespectful if he disagrees with you.

Had him for American and English literature in Yonsei. He is such a bright guy and knows what he is talking about. I'm not sure how he is in BC, but at least in Yonsei he was pretty cool. He has a cute way of talking.
Awesome! Interested in the student and his/her progress. Also incredibly insightful in terms of literature, mordern society, and your own psyche
No Comments
No Comments
No Comments
No Comments

Took her complex problems class with another professor. Very nice person and really cares about her students. Fair grader and gives good feedback. The course was lecture-heavy and her lectures could get boring.

this class was a complex questions class (crisis & storytelling in the age of climate change- natural science and lit core), and the class and hw itself was pretty easy but lecture was kind of boring. a bit of a tough grader but not too harsh. personally not my cup of tea

Its a really tough class with a lot of work but Prof Palevsky is very nice and kindhearted. She is a lenient grader and is very understanding with extensions, etc. The labs are also not that difficult given that it is a core class. All in all it is a lot of work especially for non-science majors and be prepared to do a lot if you want an A in class

I genuinely was excited to go to this class every day I had it because TKM always kept us on our feet and never failed to tell a good joke. definitely would recommend doing the reading and participating to get a good grade but TKM was one of the best professors I have had
No.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Participation matters--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: As a person he is amazing.  If you read the material and participate you will end up with a good grade.  He is super fun and exciting to listen to and is probably one of the most interesting professors I have ever had.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Amazing lectures --Beware of pop quizzes

comment_Rating: If you're a junior or senior, take creative non-fiction with TKM. It was by no means easy, but I met lifelong friends.

I don't know what else I can say about TKM that hasn't been said already. He's amazing. I highly recommend his class. Just be prepared to put in some hard work. He is tough but fair both on exams and essays.

It is difficult to write a review about TKM given that I have never had a professor quite like him. I genuinely never looked forward to coming to a class more, not because of the material but because of TKM himself. Hilarious guy, but genuine too. Genuinely a prof I will never forget.

If you enjoy thing that are confusing and dont make sense, take this class. If you are a very math-science kind of person this class is probably not for you. A ton of people absolutely loved this class. I hated it. It is stressful and can be great for some people and awful for others.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Participation matters--Beware of pop quizzes

comment_Rating: Had him for Lit Core. Paper prompts were extremely difficult and entire grade was based on 4 assignments along with 2 pop quizzes. Class discussion was lively, but was often completely unrelated to the coursework. It is hard to earn an A in this class, but it was a fun experience nonetheless.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Beware of pop quizzes--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: Had him for literature core Freshman year. There are only 4 grades in the course, all of which are harshly graded. There are 2 papers, a midterm, and a final. All are graded based on whether or not he agrees with you not how strong the argument is. He gave 2 pop quizzes which were very difficult. Don't let the 5 star reviews deceive you.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Beware of pop quizzes--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: He's great I'm just dumb and didn't really do any work. Still got a good grade, however. Really nice guy, and not a traditional professor. Ask him how he grades at first.
Love this man. You have to take this class.

One of those professors whose class changes your thinking in a fundamental way. Hilarious, engaging, and thoughtful. Lectures and assignments demand you to think in unique ways and exercise the full faculties of your brain.

the funniest and most interesting prof i've ever had. take this man's class. he's the best and once you take a class with him he considers you family. super sarcastic and loves ppl who banter with him.

TKM is the best teacher you will ever have. He has given me tremendous amounts of extra help and support for class, as well as with personal issues. He is hilarious and will crack jokes all period, but also teaches you a ton. He really helped me grow as a writer and as a student. Seriously recommend you take his class as a freshman if you can.

You have to do all the readings to be able to participate in class, which is key. Exams and papers also require you to do all readings. He is a very outgoing and funny guy who really cares about students. Easy to approach.

Kaplan-Maxfield is the type of professor you will never forget, and with good reason. He questions conventional teaching methods, and makes classes genuinely interesting (I have never enjoyed an English class before taking this one). His assignments and exams are all interesting, there's honestly never a dull moment.
This man is awesome. Will blow you're mind with some of the things he teaches you. You must go to class and never pull your phone out, though honestly, you won't want to.
kaplan is absolutely amazing. he will try to confuse you at first but stick with it! hes an amazing teacher
Evans is fantastic. He is a great professor who is very conversational and fun.

Unfortunately, you can't pick your Portico professor, but if you end up with Evans, know you are in good hands. He is so nice and really funny. There is one group project and the tests are just essay exams. Make sure to participate bc your TAs pay attention to that! Portico is really an easygoing class. If you get Evans, you'll definitely enjoy it!

Professor Evans is hilarious; I enjoyed laughing with him in class. Portico material is often dull and rudimentary, but Professor Evans did a great job of making it interesting. I especially appreciate his criticism of the grading curve he was forced to use, which is bull----. I would recommend him to any BC student.
Participate in his class and you will do great. He's a super funny guy and one of the nicest people at BC. He's also a really helpful academic advisor.

AMAZING TEACHER. Such a good advisor, too. I thought that Portico was an easy course consisting of three take home essays, but I still left knowing the information and taking it to heart. He tells the class through memorable stories and wants you to understand the material rather than cram knowledge for a test. 10/10 absolute king.

Professor Evans always had engaging lectures and was very clear with what he expected in papers. He does need to follow a strict CSOM curve, but so does every Portico professor. Our essay exams were take-home with plenty of time to complete them. He is very generous with extensions and understanding of his student's stress levels.
Prof Evans is such a kind person, and his class is as entertaining as a business ethics class can be. He is hilarious and his class is pretty laid back.
Great teacher and course. Super easy only 3 essay exams and no tests. Evans is super nice, a very easy grader, and hilarious.

Great professor for CTK. I really enjoyed all the books we read and I feel like I took a lot away from the course. As long as you put in the same amount of effort you would for any other core course and show that you care you will get an A.

Prof. Donnelly, is a great guy who cares about students and is always willing to meet outside of classes. Grading criteria and instructions for some homeworks and papers were unclear. I would say there are easier options to take for Perspectives in terms of workload but if he sees you are putting the work in, you can do well!
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Lots of homework--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: best perspectives professor

Perspectives is a tough course, but so worth it and Prof. Donnelly is one of the best professors in the program! There is a lot of reading and writing involved in this class, so it takes up a lot of outside of class time, but it fulfills lots of credits so is very worth it. He assigns shorter papers, but takes a while to grade. Overall great!
didn't always prepare a lot for the class but good books and so so easy. Did get a little boring though.

Donnelly is a funny guy with lots of wise cracks and knowledge of the Perspectives courses he teaches. There's a lot of reading and writing, but you get used to it after the first couple of weeks. Would definitely recommend.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Lots of homework--Respected

comment_Rating: The workload can seem like a lot, but it's consistent and you get used to it. I genuinely learned a lot in this class and I want to take another class with him but I think this is his only class. He's funny and can make dry and complicated texts easy to understand, all while making it entertaining. He genuinely cares about all of his students.
discussion based so if you do not like talking do not take this

Professor Donnelly is by no means an easy professor, but his class is engaging and his lectures clear up otherwise confusing readings. The workload is consistent, although it may feel heavy it is easy to prepare for. His lectures are engaging and his sense of humor, although subtle, adds so much to a would-be boring class. Cannot recommend enough.
He genuinely cares about his students and their well being. He is such a nice guy!
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--Accessible outside class--Get ready to read

comment_Rating: He is a nice guy, but his class is so BORING. I can't help but fall asleep in his class. The class is easy enough if you do all the readings and you can also get by spark noting the readings.

Professor Donnelly is an amazing professor who you can tell is very knowledgeable in his field. I had him for Perspectives I, which was a lot of reading but you can get by using SparkNotes and attending class. There is a one page writeup due for each class, 1-2 papers per semester, and an oral final exam. He genuinely wants to see you succeed!
Hit or miss professor. You either really appreciate his dry humor or you let his snarky personality get to you.

The class was a lot of work and he expected a lot of effort, but if you consistently go to office hours and make a visible effort he will absolutely help you. He clearly cares, and even offered to talk to me about my options when I was considering transferring schools. He is definitely a bit moody, but overall I loved his class and would recommend.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Clear grading criteria

comment_Rating: Good teacher.
ratingTags_Rating: Lots of homework--Lecture heavy--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: Professor Spooner is an amazing professor. She conveys the course info very clearly and if you forget something or want to look back at certain material to study before a test, she posts all her Panopto recorded lectures that go over the exact information she went over in class. Tests are MC/short answer and hard but not cumulative, including final

Rachel Spooner is by far one of the best professors I have had at BC. She is so passionate about law and it comes across. She posts videos before every class that are so helpful, read the cases before class too. Most of class is just working through cases, very discussion based. Make time to go to her office hours, she's great to get to know!

Prof. Spooner has by far been my favorite professors at BC. She is extremely kind and considerate, and respects everyone in the class. She is always available outside of class. She is passionate about the material she teaches. Even though Business Law is content heavy and be a lot of work, she helped make the course interesting and engaging.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Caring--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: Prof. Spooner was by far the best professor I have had. While I am not sure I was particularly memorable in this class and did not receive the highest grade, it was an incredible experience. Spooner cares that material is understood and will answer all questions. She will answer your emails within 24 hours. Definitely make use of going to OH.

Gives silly 9/10s on nearly every homework assignment, no matter how thorough or complete. 

That being said, she is very knowledgable, sticks to the syllabus, extremely available and willing to meet outside of class, clearly cares about her students, brings in interesting guest speakers, has a good course structure. 

Overall, a 9/10 teacher ;)
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Get ready to read--Participation matters

comment_Rating: Great professor, extremely knowledgeable. Lectures were always very interesting. Open-note exams, but she is definitely a tough grader. Very accessible, grades assignments promptly, has clearly put in a ton of effort into the course. Had several guest speakers come in, which was always interesting.
She is amazing! Dont coextensive an awesome grade, but its worth it.

Professor Spooner is an awesome teacher for Business Law. It is very easy to get to know her well and her sense of humor lightens class every day. Law ultimately is a relatively tough subject but doing the homework and reading the textbook simplifies the concepts immensely. Not overall difficult to do well if you put in the work and time!
Professor Spooner has been one my favorite professors I've had. Class is fun and interesting, and as long as you care, you'll do fine. Highly recommend!

This class (EALC1121) is quite hard for a true beginner, even though it's an elementary chinese course. 
That aside, Professor Lu is very kind, caring, and wants you to do well. She'll give you points back on dictations and tests. Just remember, this is by no means an easy class! I wouldn't recommend taking it unless you love learning Chinese.

The best Chinese teacher at BC by far, had for newspaper & media chinese, and she was really thorough and caring throughout the entire semester. She is extremely accommodating too, makes you feel confident in your abilities.

Had for advanced chinese, she is AMAZING, my favorite prof at BC by far. It is obvious that she cares for everyone and pays attention to every single student, super easy to ask questions if confused. Incredibly lenient on assignments as long as you tell her, literally cannot go wrong with her. Only difficult thing is frequent dictations.

Elementary Chinese I with Professor Fang Lu is definitely NOT a course for beginners! She is a great professor: very kind and helpful, but she insists on having daily graded quizzes on the vocabulary and difficult tests which require hand-writing essays in characters. Even if you have experience in Chinese, don't expect this class to be easy!

Classes are strictly lectures, homework is usually reading, and only graded on midterm, paper, and final. He is accessible outside class, but does not answer emails (at least not mine). He is a nice man and passionate about theology. Not my cup of tea though.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Lecture heavy--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: Lots of reading. Answer some HW questions about the reading each week, but it's doable. Really have to pay attention in class, as he'll ask questions on the exam that comes straight from class discussion, and not the reading. Seminar, but was mostly lecture heavy bc of Covid. Grading based on HW, midterm, and final, and not much else. Good class.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Skip class? You won't pass.

comment_Rating: Taken online. Lots of reading each week. Reading reflections and write ups are time consuming, but not too hard. Finding relevant articles for class is HW and difficult. Class is very long and pretty much all lectures; can get boring very quickly. Get a 15 minute break in the middle. Tests are really difficult and specific. Gotta study a lot.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Skip class? You won't pass.--Test heavy

comment_Rating: Very dry in lecturing such that you want to fall asleep. He gives no preparation for any exams and they are often very hard. Wished I could've switched professors earlier. Nice human being but not so much prof. Wont miss the class when its over. Seems like he's trying too hard to make us into biblical scholars for it just being a core class.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough Grader--Skip class? You won't pass.--LECTURE HEAVY

comment_Rating: HW is done in groups, and is doable, just takes a while. Class is pretty much all lectures. Exams are pretty difficult, but if you study, go to the review sessions, and do the practice exams, you'll be fine. Friendly guy and available if you need help. Early material is just like corporate, but later material (options) is very tough. Recommend him

Professor Tomunen was awesome. His lectures were very helpful and he really loves what he does. He's also late-20s by my estimates (based on his CV on his website) so he doesn't have that long-term fatigue that middle-aged/senior professors might have. He isn't "energetic" per se but he's definitely passionate behind the outwardly restrained look.

Professor Neale is super nice. I found his class decently difficult, but he had a very generous curve at the end. He does a flipped classroom where you do the homework first and then learn the material which was pretty challenging.The lectures were 2.5 hours, so they were pretty boring but he was very available outside of class for extra questions.

Took for Sports Analytics. Class is a lot of lecture, but you about 3 practice problems each class. Exams were fair; given formula sheet and need to know how to apply it, and know reading terms. Final project is easy and interesting. If you like sports, you'll enjoy this. Really knowledgable professor and always willing to help. Highly recommend!
ratingTags_Rating: Test heavy--Graded by few things--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: Big Excel assignments with Solver each week. You read the material, then do the assignment, then he teaches you how to do it in class, but grades fairly. Tests are pretty difficult, but he gives you the chance to explain your thoughts. Some group cases where you present, but it's not hard. Helpful in office hours, but won't tell you answers. Fair.
ratingTags_Rating: Skip class? You won't pass.--Graded by few things--Test heavy

comment_Rating: Class is pretty good. Readings can be long for the discussion, but you only need to talk in 2/4 to get full credit. Material can seem hard if you don't know R already or don't know how to code, but he is a good teacher and you'll learn. Exams were fair and doable if you do the review. Final project was tough bc of the models complexity; good class
ratingTags_Rating: Participation matters--Graded by few things--Clear grading criteria

comment_Rating: Prof Whalen was awful for intermediate accounting. He constantly disses finance majors and says everyone will end up working for a CPA which is not remotely true. His lectures are useless as he just reads off of textbook slides. I learned nothing in this class, and this sentiment is shared by many. It felt like a waste of time.

Prof Whalen was great. He would sometimes go on tangents but overall taught the course well. There was a lot of homework but some counted as participation, and it honestly made me grasp the material better. I wish I counted how many times he snapped his fingers and said "everyone up here." He says it before saying something important. Every. Time.
ratingTags_Rating: Participation matters--Lots of homework--Graded by few things

comment_Rating:
Fin acct is a hard class because of the content, not because of Prof. Whalen. A lot of homework but there is always ample time to do it, and it ensures I am actually prepared for exams.
Occasional open book quizzes, not pop quizzes even though syl. says that.
20% HW/quizzes
25% each-2 midterms

I really liked Professor Olins' class. She explains the material really well, gives a ton of review material before midterms, and drops the lowest midterm. The homework load is super manageable and interesting. You can tell she's super passionate about ecology and wants her students to do well.

The textbook is online and given to us for free at the beginning of the year. The material is not hard, one test is dropped, one is take home, and she really tries to make class fun!

Olins is a fair professor. Her assigned homework is not too bad, and you are graded mostly for completion. The exams are all memorization, and there is a ton of material she expects you to know. However, she is super passionate about biology and is understanding and accommodating.

I really enjoyed Ecology and Evolution with Prof. Olins. She cares a lot about the subject and the homework assignments were less traditional ( go outside for nature walks, learn about scientists, etc.) there is still reading and the content can be very difficult, but I think she does a really good job with this class, and I'm sure her others too.

Literally do not listen to the other reviews. This woman is strict and her exams are difficult for no reason. I took her course asynchronous with open-note exams and she still managed to make this difficult and blame my section when no one got good grades on the exam. I did not learn a thing.

I took abnormal psychology with her. Great professor: knowledgeable, funny, but strict. A lot of people say that her class isn't easy which is true. Three exams and a cumulative final plus mandatory attendance. I studied pretty hard and got 91 on the first exam and 88 on the second. A- and B+ are possible, but getting an A is pretty difficult.

Attendance is definitely mandatory to get a good grade. Her class isn't easy, but it is informative. Definitely don't get on her bad side but otherwise you'll be okay if you read the textbook, go to class, and study.

3 Exams and one cumulative final. If you mess up one exam, there goes your chances for an A. A lot of material to memorize which makes it difficult to enjoy the subject. I have done everything to prepare for the exams and have not gotten anything higher than a C+.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Skip class? You won't pass.

I really feel like I am learning, rather than just memorizing.

The class is hard but i seriously LOVE Dr. brooks. Shes super enthusiastic about math and teaching and puts a lot of effort into trying to make the material understandable. Took Complex Problems/ Enduring Questions class called Death in Russian Literature and Ancient Greece. Professor Epstein taught the part about Russian Lit. The prof chooses really interesting readings and engages the class well. He also always has really insightful analysis.
Very nice guy, not a hard class. Very writing heavy. Sparknotes the reading before class and it'll be fine.

Professor Epstein is the sweetest man. He has a solid sense of humor and wants to know all his students. Sometimes he goes on tangents during the lectures and deviates from the original thought. The class is entry questions and essay prompts. He is a fair grader and willing to give extensions.

she is incredible, take her if you have the chance- CCR is hard but that's for any professor, the syllabus is standardized across all sections

take the other person for CS2 this is not worth it unnecessarily difficult for simple content matter.

comment_Rating: Clearly an expert but churns through new concepts rapidly.  With no CS background it was a struggle to absorb the lectures. Homework sets required a min of 8 hours a week. Challenging questions combine python operations with mathematical concepts that you need to identify intuitively.  Felt like writing a novel while learning the language.

Tristan is a nice professor, who clearly cares about computer science and coding. However, his introduction class is RIDICULOUSLY difficult if you have no background in the subject. Five substantial coding assignments every week which took me between 4-8 hours to complete depending on the week. Extremely difficult if this is your first time coding.

Marta Hernandez was far and away the best professor I've ever had in my undergraduate career. Her lectures left me nothing short of awe struck at the new spanish grammatical rules I had acquired. Her lectures were fast, but educational, rigid but fun. If you want to learn more about the song writer Camilo, I would strongly recommend this class.

Marta Hernandez is a good professor! She goes pretty fast through the lectures but if you pay attention and participate in class, it is manageable. She is super nice but you will have to review a lot on your own as well.
She's very nice and the class overall isn't that hard if you pay attention and participate. We have a bunch of grades, so its not that challenging to get a good grade if you put the effort in.
THIS IS FOR WESLEYAN 231. Clearly knowledgeable on the material but fails to communicate it effectively. Yes he curves the grades but I learned very little from the course.

DO NOT TAKE a class with Professor Pollio. I took ECON241 at Wesleyan. Tests are extraordinarily difficult and unfair. Frequently brags about how difficult the exams are going to be and how poor the average grades are. Creates unreasonable stress for a 200 level course.

NOT ECON 2202! Econ 241 at Wesleyan University. If you care about your GPA stay away. Exams are impossible and his review sessions are about how hard the exam is going to be. Nice guy but doesn't quite understand that almost everyone in his class just failed the exams. Couldn't find his Wesleyan University page so had to leave one hear.

Meh. Great guy, bad lecturer. Luckily the tests and problem sets are straight out of the textbook, so I just read that to learn all I know. I see he's teaching econometrics next semester, and since econometrics is much harder and harder to learn on your own than macro, I definitely don't recommend him for that.

Kinda what the first review said; he doesn't teach and barely lectures from the slides. Homework is bare, but the tests are out of hand and unfairly difficult. He also is hard to understand. If you care about your GPA, find another instructor.

The undisputed GOAT.

Good Professor, Good class, good grading, I definitely recommend taking a class with her before she retires

She is the sweetest professor I have had. This class was very easy. The exams were not heavily weighted and you get partial credit on everything. Homework you get a 100% on as long as you attempt it. Dr. Ward is thorough with the material and abundantly clear with her expectations. If you put in any effort at all, you'll do alright. Good choice for finite.

I could not recommend Erika Ward enough!! She is the sweetest and most patient teacher. She truly cares about her students and makes sure that everyone understands the material. Insanely easy and a 1/3 of the grade is completion based. You will never do more than an hour worth of work a week.
Very caring proffesor, she will help if needed and lectures are not bad at all. Gives a lot of partial credit on problems as well.

If you have to take math core take Professor Ward!! She is great, super super clear on what you will be graded on and a very structured class overall. She wants everyone to do well, could not recommend her enough!

Professor Resler is easily the best professor I have had at Boston College.  He is extremely engaging and makes what could be a boring subject very exciting.

Amazing professor, very entertaining and knowledgable.  Will make you love the material.  Take him if you can

Resler is the greatest language professor you can ask for. He's a cool guy, knows how college is, and is always willing to help you get through his course. DEFINITELY take a course with him, you won't regret it.

Awesome professor.  Makes all kinds of information interesting, and his lectures and notes helped me learn so much so well.  Take a Resler course!!!

Prof. Grube is a fantastic professor! You will never be bored in his class.  He really cares about his students as people and as scholars.  The assignments are interesting and challenging.  Highly recommend!!

Prof. Grube is such a great professor.  I signed up for the class because I needed a History II credit, and I wasn't really looking forward to it. Because of her, I'm now a philosophy minor.

I love this woman so much. She is so funny and entertaining. Participate in the first class and she'll love you. You just need to say one thing each class and it's easy A. But, if you don't say anything she will hate you and call you out on everything.

I definitely agree with the previous ratings. I usually participate a bunch in other discussion-based classes, but had no motivation to do so here. She has a iron grip on the direction of the discussion. Disagree with her? Good luck

This was the worst Professor I have ever had. She is rude and degrading. Courage to know is supposed to be a nice friendly freshmen class and prof made it horrible. I would call my mom crying about the disrespect and the way she treated her students. Do not take.
ratingTags_Rating: Lots of homework--Graded by few things--Tough grader

comment_Rating: Looking back, I really got nothing out of the class, so I wish I got to learn more. We got sidetracked in class a lot. Professor clearly was not fond of some people in my class haha (it wasn't their fault at all). Idk what grade they got though

I was so excited to take CTK coming into my freshman year, and I am sad to say Prof. Michalczyk made me feel like I wasted a class slot. Her class had no direction or organization. She would get upset when people didn't talk in the discussions, but no one did because she would rudely cut people off and belittle them when they spoke. 0/10

I took this professor for the first-year self-interest seminar and she's my advisor. Love her, she's so sweet and caring about her students. Definitely do UNCS2245 with her. The readings are long but the discussions are very easy and meaningful. She's also a very knowledgeable and good advisor.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Amazing lectures --Gives good feedback

comment_Rating: Prof. Duggan is a great and caring prof for CTK! She is super interested in getting to know her students well. She isn't necessarily an easy A but her work is definitely doable. In addition she was very lenient on due dates. She's very funny and hyper and has a ton of very Intresting stories. I would definitely take another course from her!

I took Professor Duggan for Courage to Know and absolutely loved the class. There is a lot of reading (3-4 articles per week) and there are weekly written reflections, but honestly, it's well worth it. She cares for her students and will say hi if you see her on campus. :)
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--Inspirational

comment_Rating: I thought this would be my "BS class"; man, was I wrong. Very tough grader, but you can tell she does it for the better of her students, as we're all freshmen, who are unaccustomed to the college grading system at BC.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Participation matters--SO MANY PAPERS

comment_Rating: Professor Duggan is not a good teacher at all. She gives an unbelievably unfair amount of homework (at least one 3 page reflection paper each week, but usually two). She tries to provide real-life examples in class, but none of them fit the notes AT ALL. In reality, she's just self-centered and enjoys talking about herself. She doesn't belong at BC

Khani's approach to teaching sociology is truly multifaceted. His readings and lectures reflect his interest in studying the discipline through the lens of intersectionality that keeps his class very fascinating. His in-depth analysis and feedback on your papers really help you hone your skill as an academic writer.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Gives good feedback

comment_Rating: The best professor ever. He is amazing at teaching. He is super passionate, understanding, and very knowledgeable. HIGHLY RECOMMOND!!

One of the nicest professors I've had thus far. Clearly wants to see his students succeed.
Especially for a grad student, Saber is engaging during class, and his lectures revolve around the main concepts from the textbook. Straightforward and grades fairly.

Graded assignments were easy as long as your notes are reviewed. Exam review is thorough.

Although the time of the class is not ideal, take him. He is underrated in the law department 100%. He tells you what questions are going to be on the exam, so pay attention. Because the time of the class is so long, it can be hard to pay attention but take notes and you'll be fine.
Prof. Alvarez is a good professor, but I think the class structure can definitely be tweaked. His class is mainly on exams, so if u are not a good test taker, its really hard to do well in his class.

Alvarez is an extremely knowledgable professor, whose classes tend to delve deep into theoretical topics. He tries to link this theory with practice, with moderate success, and the theory definitely helps develop good CS skills. Would highly recommend him.

He is very into what he teaches and speaks of very interesting moments that he has experienced himself.  Lots of reading however, if you pay attention and take notes in class, you can get away with not reading.  Tests are open note and he grades based on creativity.

Prof. Lovitz was clearly very passionate about her work and worked to share this interest with us. Paper and project expectations very reasonable, clear instructions. Lecture heavy, can be tough to follow at certain points. Overall, I would highly recommend!

I really enjoyed Prof. Lovitz's class.  It was obvious how passionate she is about education and psychology, and her energy was contagious.  She is very knowledgeable about what she teaches and was able to present the material in a clear and interesting way.

An exceptional professor who exhibits a deep passion for the subject matter. This enthusiasm is palpable in every lecture, creating an engaging learning environment. Success in this course is largely attributed to consistent participation and keeping up with the readings. The professor's fervor for the material is contagious.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Get ready to read--Participation matters

comment_Rating: Very caring teacher who is approachable outside of class. Wishes the best for her students. However, her class tends to be a bit harder than the other sections. Still I highly recommend as she is the head of the department and a fantastic teacher. One of my favorite professors this far.

LaCombe was my Portico professor. She is a lenient grader who gives fair exams based exactly off of what was gone over in class/the lectures. Incredibly kind, discussions are always engaging and fun. Takes the time to actually get to know students.
gets off topic in a very logical accounting class, making it hard for us to catch up with our peers taught by other profs. cool person tho.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Beware of pop quizzes--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: not the best lectures, gets distracted/off topic. Sometimes annoyingly hard grader.

Professor LaCombe is my favorite professor at BC. She is super sweet and caring! She is also very intelligent and makes classes worthwhile. I know accounting better than any of my friends who took other professors. That said, her exams are difficult and you will have a lot of work. If you are an accounting major, take LaCombe. If not, maybe don't.
Great professor! Cares a lot about students and does a good job explaining things, and is always happy to help.

Though financial accounting isn't the most fun course to take, Professor LaCombe is always available outside of class to meet to go over concepts if you are struggling. She gives a good amount of partial credit on exams for showing your work and just wants the best for her students.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Gives good feedback--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: Best Lit Core professor; class is based on completion. If you complete all assignments you automatically get a B, if you do 3 extra she'll bump you up to an A.

Professor Crotty's class is a bit disorganized and boring, with the bulk of every class being spent on mostly meaningless discussion. But she assigns only a few papers and is a pretty easy grader. Fine option for lit core.

Prof Crotty can be a bit annoying sometimes, but once you figure out how to write for her you're good. She genuinely cares about her students and is a good person. Lots of class discussions on readings. Really tries to create an open and comfy classroom. Very accommodating and reasonable. Pretty specific in her grading but no super long papers.

I really admire Professor Crotty as a teacher. She is also a caring and flexible person. While her grading can definitely be tough, I ended up doing very well in her writing seminar class by following the rubrics for papers/other assignments as closely as possible. Attending her office hours can also be helpful!

For writing assignments, which are the bulk of your grade, it is difficult to tell what she wants you to write. If you go to office hours, she will give more helpful specific feedback. Class time is mostly spent discussing reading or doing small group activities, which can get pretty dull. Overall, she's pretty nice and an ok option for lit core.

Very unclear grading criteria. It is possible to get a good grade, but you need to write for the professor. There is not much freedom for writing and I didn't feel challenged in the necessary areas.

Extremely disorganized - the syllabus and schedule for what we do each day is very unclear. You need to spend a lot of time just to organize yourself.

Professor Crotty is a kind person and a fair grader so long as you make a clear attempt to fulfill all the points on the rubrics she provides for papers. She always seems willing to help her students improve and grow as writers. She isn't the most amazing English teacher I've had, but she's definitely not a bad option. Also, participation matters.
Very kind nice teacher. Class is a quite difficult with a few close readings and papers representing most of your grade. Tough grader

Classes had frequent lapses of silence the class just was not that engaging for me at least. Grading is pretty darn tough she will always ask for a 'so what' in your paper but never explain what she really wants. In the end English is quite subjective and you have to bend your writing to what she wants.

Professor Gareau is very kind and caring, and ecosystems with her was pretty easy. There are weekly quizzes, but most of them are relatively simple. I'd recommend studying at least a little bit for them, though, as there are some questions that are a bit hard. The labs are pretty easy, and she gives an extra day for you to submit them if needed.

I really liked Tara! Her section is very science-heavy and the lectures can be hard to take notes on sometimes (not many words, lots of graphs, etc) but she is very knowledgeable and passionate. Her chemistry with her co-professor Brian Gareau is entertaining and they bring a lively vibe to class. I'd recommend :)
W professor
Terrible professor, would not recommend taking this class. One of the least enjoyable courses that I've taken.
Dr. M taught me real good. I feel very, smarter because I learned nice things.

Good guy and he's really passionate about what he teaches, but he does make you work for it. Lowkey a lot of reading and he expects you to know it well. Hard-ish grader for papers. But overall a really interesting professor and I think as long as you like the material you're studying, you'll like him.
Such a cool guy, very smart, recommend

He really knows the material and has a passion for his work. Hes very relatable, so its easy to connect with him. He gives out a lot of reading, so watch out for that, but they are all very relevant and interesting.
Not a bad prof. But not those type that really encourage you to think, question, and challenge from the OTHER side.

Intro to African Diaspora Stufies is a phenomenal class. This was my first Black Studies/African Diaspora course but it will not be my last. There are 10 papers in the course and he gives you really good feedback on how to improve. I definitely see myself and Africa in a new light. And yes he is hot. Those eyes OMG those eyes!

Prof McGuffey is one of those rare gems of a professor. He can make complicated issues understandable without watering down just how difficult these social issues are. The only down side to his class is that its too big. A class dealing with such touchy issues like racism, sexism & homophobia should be much smaller. But definitely take it!

Definitely one of the top 5 profs at BC. I think it's to much reading for a intro level course but I really did learn a lot. I see things differently now, which I guess is the point of the class. I'm a total straight dude but can see why the chicks think he's hot

Prof McGuffey is amazing! He Loves teaching and it shows. I like that he makes his views known but completely respects the views of others (as long as they're well reasoned and supported by empirical evidence). And he is as gooD looking as he is smart.

Prof McGuffey is the best professor I've ever had. I've had him for 2 classes and as summer research advisor. He is very demanding, expects a lot but it's totally worth it. It's impossible to see the world the same after one of his courses.
Shawn rocks. Great prof and he will change your perspective on life but be prepared to read A LOT.
Although, alot of reading, McGuffey's classes are so worth taking.  He is a very brilliant man, and his classes have changed my life, my majors, and career path.  A little unapproachable.
Take lit core with her! She is the sweetest professor and truly cares about her students. The reading can be a lot, but she is fair with the amount of time given.

I took her class because she got great reviews... not sure why. The class was frustrating and disorganized. The lessons were horribly boring despite us not covering much at all. She returned our first essay grades in LATE APRIL with almost no feedback. By March, she gave up teaching the reading on the syllabus. My writing didn't improve at all.
Super passionate about creative writing, tough feedback but wants everyone to do their best. A lovely person

Don't be scared when she says no one will get an A - it's not true. I came with no confidence in my writing and she completely flipped that around. She is a wonderful professor with immense knowledge and is very helpful and accessible. She truly cares about her students and also often gets off track with tangents which makes class interesting.

Very entertaining professor. I hate writing but her class and her freedom with the essay topics made it not so bad at all. Definitely a tough grader, but the trade off was worth it at least for me because I actually enjoyed going to writing seminar, something I never thought I'd ever say.
She is a little bit wacky, sort of off the rails and has unclear grading criteria but her class is pretty low stress and as long as you participate you'll be fine

Professor Roberts is my favorite professor at BC. I actually looked forward to going to her class each day and she really cares about her students. If you ever get the chance to take a class from her, don't hesitate

Professor Roberts is the most amazing teacher I’ve ever had in my entire life. If you come in with an open mind to her class your perspective for everything will change! Attendance is mandatory if you want a good grade, but either way I suggest going because you’ll have a good time.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Gives good feedback--Hilarious

comment_Rating: Roberts is one of the most genuine and real professors Ive had. She gets easily side-tracked which makes conversations interesting and entertaining. It is clear she cares about each and every one of her students. I enjoy coming to class to hear what she has to say.

LOVE Prof. Roberts. Cares so deeply, is down-to-earth, hilarious, and such a uniquely interesting person. Lit core made my days a bit more colorful than they would have been otherwise. You'll get so much more out of it if you actually do the readings.

A very discussion-based professor. She's hilariously opinionated and wants to hear what you think. Go to her office hours and talk to her! I'm so glad I was able to build a connection with her. Professor Roberts is listed as Top 10 Professors You Should Take Before Graduating BC for a reason!

An amazingly caring and heartfelt professor who takes her job and her love of the English language very seriously. If you are ready to work, she is just as ready to work with you. She knows exactly what she's doing when trying to help you. Can guarantee you won't see anyone else with as much experience or care at BC. Highly recommend.

She enjoys having conversations with her students, and she has a lot to say about a lot of things, which means she is easily sidetracked! Yay! But seriously she is an awesome English teacher and as long as you do the readings you will be fine. If you ask her nicely enough she will help you out. Genuinely wants you to succeed.

I had her back when she was a teaching student. I don't know how, but I left high school with a D in English & left BC an English major w/honors. Now a gainfully employed writer. I owe it to her for helping me find my voice. She introduced me to the world of writing & literature that changed my life. After 20 yrs I still remember that first day.

Interesting lectures! FUN! BUT... not a class for an easy A... you really have to work for that! But if you do put in some efforts you'll get a B for sure~ I still love her even though I didn't get an A (:

Loved her. She is very sweet and makes an effort to try and make learning spanish fun even though a majority of BC students taking it are forced to. A bit tough on grading, but the class is fairly easy to get a good grade so long you put the effort in to do good. I did the bare minimum and even stopped taking notes and still did fairly well.
Not the easiest grader but not her fault her rating is reflective of the horrible Spanish department at BC. Still, she is not a great teacher of the material

I had Pia Cuneo for Intermediate Spanish I, and absolutely loved her. Super caring, funny, kind, and an easy grader as long as you participate in class. There is a lot of homework and the grading criteria was unclear at times, but that's just the nature of the Spanish department. Highly recommend!

He is an amazing lecturer and hands out printed slides to make it easier for students to follow along with lectures. Grades fairly and as long as you pay attention and understand the concepts well you should do well!

Very good lectures: they're short, and to the point, often ending early. Many classes will have a small classwork assignment to do in small groups, which makes the class more interesting and reinforces concepts. Amazing guest speakers! Projects seem intimidating, but are manageable. Professor is very knowledgeable and a captivating lecturer.

Not incredibly easy but not hard either. Lectures are not the most interesting but still helpful to understand the material. Quizzes aren't challenging as long as you take good notes in class and know the lecture material -- lots of memorization. Personally, did better on the quizzes than projects. Nice teacher overall, I recommend for principles.

Good prof for Marketing Principles. Not the most interesting or dynamic course content, but a good introduction to the business and marketing fields. Tests were fairly easy as long as you attended class and watched the lectures, and there were individual and group projects to boost your grade as well. Overall nice guy and a solid teacher.

Dominicci is a great professor. He's super funny, very kind, and teaches the material very effectively. I'm not great at Spanish, but he made learning it very easy and straightforward. Any negatives of the class are solely the fault of the Spanish department, not his. Definitely would recommend him for anybody taking Intermediate 2.
ratingTags_Rating: Group projects--Clear grading criteria--Gives good feedback

comment_Rating: Really nothing special, but I found his attitude kind of arrogant or fake? Just rubbed me the wrong way. Assignments were super boring but nothing too hard.
Professor Buzo really cares about his students and is available to help whenever necessary. Highly recommend him as a professor.

Falconi is a great teacher. She is super passionate and makes sure everyone is involved in conversation (cold calls). Her class isn't hard to get an A- in, but all Spanish Intermediate 2 are hard for an A. She's super nice and willing to meet with students. Often small group projects and lots of easy and quick homeworks.
Energetic class, consistent participation and homework is necessary. Fair grader and super helpful in office hours.

very nice prof. she is generous with participation grades and most classes are just spent doing speaking activities with her and the class. felt a bit difficult to get an A given the cutoff for whats an A- vs A. with a bit of effort though, the A- can be easily earned.

Professor Falconi is all-around a good teacher, very energetic and active, and usually runs class well. She is a bit strict on getting homework in on time, so if you forget to do even one or two assignments, it can tank your grade a bit.

Professor Falconi is great. She makes class enjoyable and has a great sense of humor. There is nightly homework but only takes 10 minutes to complete. Occasionally there are other homework assignments that don't take long either. PSE, Live Chat Assignments, Written exams, Oral exams, and in-class writings are graded fairly. Great class
Nice person
Learned some valuable information
She talks a lot. Used a lot of life examples from her background and current experiences. Cares a lot about students and wants everyone to do well.
Good class, but a lot of writing. Prof DeVoy made a huge and boring textbook into interesting conversations and activities.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--So many papers--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: Devoy is a unique educator. You have to be ready to write essays though and you need to do the reading to write all the papers.

Completely bizarre and unorganized class run by the undergrad TAs alone. Frequently late to class and when she did show up, she had absolutely no idea of what to teach. Ridiculously out of her depth! The whole class was a joke, people would just watch sports highlights or do work for other class while being here because attendance was "mandatory".
After taking 3 courses and being a TA for her I can say that she is amazing and genuinely caring.

I took introduction to feminisms with Professor Devoy and was so disappointed. She was almost always late to class, if she showed up at all. There were a ton of papers, and despite having a Professor, a graduate student, and a TA running it, it didn't seem like anyone put much effort into organizing it.
ratingTags_Rating: Participation matters--Lots of homework--So many papers

comment_Rating: Took Intro to Feminisms and wrote a paper almost every week. Unclear directions and harsh grading. She was very understanding if you approached her with a problem though.
ratingTags_Rating: Lots of homework--So many papers--Tough grader

comment_Rating: Took him for playwriting. Incredibly nitpicky and meticilous with grading for such a subjective medium and boasts that "you won't see a grade in this class until the final letter is posted." If you put in the work, you'll do okay. And if you're theatre department adjacent or truly interested in the material, you'll get a lot out of it.

Unreasonable amount of reading (way more than can be realistically done in time frame). Will never grant an extension no matter what. Subpar exam formats; questions are unclear and wordy, riddled with typos etc. I guess one positive is that he grades assignments very quickly. Would not recommend.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--So many papers

comment_Rating: I took his classes nearly a decade ago. While I didn't pursue a poli-sci career, his lessons stayed with me. I find myself for recalling not only history, politics, but also international policy and applying them to my personal and professional lives. Deese gives his students a better understanding of the world they live in, and hope to change.

Prof Deese was a great teacher. He is sometimes known as "D minus Deese", because he doesn't play around. He doesn't inflate grades, nor is he afraid to give an A when appropriate. Do your readings, engage in class, and you should do fine.

Logic & Computation w/ McTague is fast paced and rigorous. I probably put in two classes amount of work in his class. However, McTague will be there to support you if you reach out and he is helpful during office hours. Biggest tip for success is to really understand how to solve the homework assignments. Great experience just put in the work.

Like a professor from a movie. Went to show him code from a side project I was having trouble with. Thought he wasn't paying attention because he kept talking about goldfish. But then he suddenly typed out a short program which efficiently solved the problem. Weeks later he emailed a news story about goldfish and an even better version of the code.

Professor McTagues intelligence and passion for the course material are truly present in his lectures and it is amazing to hear him talk about very difficult concepts. His downfall is his organization relating to homework and exams. Over the half of the homework was still ungraded by the time of the final exam.

PROS: The guy is an absolute genius, just look at him. Very passionate about his work. 
CONS:  Sucks at responding to emails and is very disorganized. Doesn't know how to structure a class. Final is insane. He put 2 massive questions on content that he barely went over on the last day of class. No practice. good luck

A legend. Awkward but hilarious..so many funny stories. Explains things so well, I ask him to explain things from other courses. Once I asked him what he wished h'ed known when he was my age. He thought hard with a really serious look on his face and then said "I really wish I'd known about infinity categories". He was so earnest lol!!

Professor McTague is an incredibly inspiring lecturer, and his passion bleeds into his lessons. He is always willing to re-explain a concept or talk after class about homework or lecture questions. The course material is difficult, but it would be regardless of the professor. I think he's very kind and encouraging, although intimidating at first.

As soon as you meet the guy you can tell he is a genius--definitely the smartest professor I've had at BC. However I think he's almost too smart for his own good, in terms of being a professor. Doesn't really comprehend that students won't fully understand topics the first go-around and throws some extremely difficult problems on the HW.
Definitely the best class I've taken at BC so far.
inspiring prof -- his passion for the subject is infectious.

Professor McTague is a very nice guy, but man does the structure of how the class is run makes no sense. All the lectures that are watched outside of class are at least 3 hours long, and the exams cover the most random topics, especially the final. There aren't many who teach Logic, but its gonna be hard to say "choose McTague for Logic".

Professor McTague is a College Professor despite not teaching in person because the class is reversed, where you watch long lectures outside of class. His final test was not printed out before the beginning of the test and had 5 errors that he notified us of. He posted review problems with only partial answers the night before final.
ratingTags_Rating: Lots of homework--Lecture heavy--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: This class is going to be really difficult regardless of who teaches it. McTague is really chill, but the class itself is kind of taught poorly. The homework is really difficult and the lectures hardly help, and the exams are the most random things you would never prepare for. However, he does try to help when asked, even if its not very helpful.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Lots of homework--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: McTague is one of the smartest but worst professors in the comp sci department. I spent countless hours after class working on assignments only to receive a B (barely). He gave us assignments over break and during finals week. He doesn't care about his students or their well-being. I do not recommend taking a class with him.

His exams were all online which really eased my nerves. He was a nice guy. Lectures were boring but he was pretty funny, and honestly I'd take it considering any econometrics is most likely going to such. A lot of STATA work but you can work with others so it's fine

Economics of Inequality
personality and teaching wise perfect, but his grading was tough. His grading for papers was okay but on the exams, there's a HUGE chunk of multiple choice worth a lot of points and even on the ones where it's "choose all that apply", if you get anything wrong you miss all the points. grade drops quick in this class
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Get ready to read--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: Amazing professor, he manages to make econometrics exciting and explains really difficult concepts in easy to understand terms. He's available outside of class and is really helpful at scheduling reviews before homework is due and before exams. If you have the option, take him!

So kind, he will always be there for you. He's so funny too, he totally understands that being in college is not a simple task so his occasional little jokes during lectures help a lot. Overall, amazing professor.

Geoffrey is a theatrical teacher in some ways which makes lectures far more entertaining. He cracks jokes about himself while also effectively explaining the basics of supply and demand. He's an extremely friendly guy who is also looking to help however he can. Great professor that is a helpful resource and fair grader.
He is absolutely amazing! His lectures are so funny and easy to understand. He actually cares about the students, answers every question, and he brought candy to class:)

Prof. Sanzenbacher is one of the most passionate and caring professors in the Econ department. He has a super busy schedule, yet still tries his best to answer students' questions. Though the materials of Financial Econometrics seem mechanical, it is nevertheless the most useful Econ elective for consulting jobs. Take his class, you won't regret.

Professor Sanzenbacher was a gem. He's incredibly passionate and knowledgeable in what he does, and does his best to make sure students succeed. I'd say studying is important, and your grade is a reflection of the effort you put in, however the material is very easy to understand and he's incredibly accessible and helpful if you are struggling.
Awesome professor and all around great guy. Amazing at what he teaches in Real Estate and Urban Action.
Great professor. He's very understanding and genuinely wants you to succeed
One of the nicest people I have ever met. He cares so much about his students and is so invested into their education. Also is actually so funny.

Professor Sanzenbacher is quite possibly the best teacher/professor I have ever had in my life. He is super intelligent, very good at explaining concepts, kind/patient/understanding/empathetic, and so much more. You MUST take prof. Sanzenbacher for Econometrics if you ever get the chance - he makes the content so easy to understand. He is an angel!
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--Accessible outside class--Amazing lectures

comment_Rating: Best econ prof at BC. Tough material, fair exams. Super nice guy, extremely accessible outside of class and is willing to help at any hour of the day. Take as many classes with him as you can, you won't regret it.

you should ABSOLUTELY try to take Professor Sanzenbacher's class if you can. He's a really nice guy and he's really great about explaining confusing concepts multiple times. He's also wonderful in office hours, and his exams weren't too hard. He's very smart & experienced, and he's also a sweet and funny guy

Best prof for music theory, even for people who don't know anything about music. Genuinely cares about making sure her students learn and love music and will do whatever is in her power to help students struggling with the material. Grades very fairly on tests and hw and concert reports are easy (two 1000 word reports). Brings food for the class.

The bulk of the class is graded on exams and two papers. The questions on the exams are the exact same as the questions on her study guides and she says exactly what she wants for the papers. The grading is super clear, and pretty much anyone can get an A in the class as long as you put in a couple hours to study and show up to class.

Professor Solere is easily the most knowledgeable professor out there. He is extremely smart, but breaks it down for you really well. He is witty and kind and is always willing to help you out when you need it. If you can write and you pay attention, you'll do well. There is lots of reading, but he goes over it all in depth in class.

few things for class but pretty harsh grader. Not a lot of homework because she spends a lot of time on the reading. If no one is talking in class she will cold call on you. I don't think she understands how a lot of things at BC work because she would get mad at kids registering for classes during class or when there was noise outside of stokes.

Class lectures were informative and interactive, the content was very well described. Readings were never long, and there were not that many of them. There are only two papers for the class, and one group project that is graded by peer evaluation. SO much better than another philosophy professor I had, so glad I switched sections.

Professor Magri cares about her students and wants them to succeed. She continually asks for feedback on assignments and lecture speed to ensure that none of her students are getting left behind. She encourages student discussion and makes everyone feel like their points matter and that they are not dumb.
Very nice, helpful, doesn't make things hard but also makes sure you understand the material
Great prof
she is legit the best spanish professor I have had at bc. such a kind heart and you can tell she wants us to learn and do well
Class wasn't the most interesting, but it's a required part of the core curriculum. Overall, she grades essays very fairly and is good about giving feedback on how to improve your writing/grade.

She is sweet and approachable. You are allowed three absences a semester which is nice but kind of annoying because at times classwork can feel like busy work. Although you do not need a textbook you do have to print out a lot of readings and copies of your paper which is frustrating because it used up a lot of my printing dollars. 100% recommend
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Gives good feedback--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: she is really nice and always open to meet for office hours. there's three essays and one group project that determine your whole grade + participations and some small easy assignments. definitely reccomend for FYW
ratingTags_Rating: Participation matters--Gives good feedback--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: Wouldnt recommend taking a class with her. Lots of awkward silence in class she waits for students to answer even if they dont know the answer. I love Professor Hendler! She truly cares about her students and wants you to be the best you can be. She lectures for the majority of the class and we work on some pratice questions. Only graded on 4 major assigments (2 exams + final exam and a paper). Overall, a easy class if you pay attention.

Sweetest person ever and super passionate about the material! He is wholesomely amazing, i think im in love

Taylor is awesome! She makes Philosophy easier to understand and more fun to learn about! If you have to take Philosophy of the Person I or II, take it with Taylor!

Taylor is one of the best teachers I have had thus far at BC. It is obvious that she wants every single one of her students to succeed. She gets into the heart of philosophy by asking questions and engaging with both the material and her students' opinions. I could not recommend her more!!
