Professor Baldelomar is one of the best professors I have had at BC! He is an amazing lecturer, is extremely knowledgeable on anything to do with theology, and is very engaging with the class. This is not your normal lecture and more discussion based than anything!!

Professor Baldelomar is hands down the best teacher I've had at BC so far (I'm a sophomore). He cares about his students, is super understanding, and delivers great lectures. Professor Kim is amazing! I took Interpersonal Relations with her and all of the lectures were so interesting and applicable to the real world. Lectures are really engaging and you get groups at the start of the year who you do a final project/ in-class activities with.

Easy A class to take for first-year writing

the sweetest human on earth. very nice, cares about her students, and very passionate about visual communication.
Everyday I walked out of his class saying how much I loved it. So so smart and inspirational. By far my favorite class of the semester and I wish I could take it again!!!!

THIS MAN IS A SAINT!!!! he is the kindest and most understanding professor you will ever have. very easy to do well if you study and do the readings. i cannot wait until i get to take another class with him. TAKE PROF SCANLON!!!!!!!!!

Dr. Pauszek is a dedicated professor who cares about each of her students. She gives valuable feedback, and her lectures are always engaging and thorough. She's so passionate about her work! It is evident that she attentively works to make her course accessible to all her students. Be prepared to put the work in, but you'll be better because of it!

Professor Pauszek is an incredible professor. She's incredibly responsive to student needs, and her care for both her students and her teaching practice is evident in each class. She uses videos, songs, poetry, and other types of readings in her class, which make it engaging and fun.

I highly recommend Dr. Pauszek. Her class was inspiring, interesting, and intellectually stimulating. The coursework included both written work, group projects, and multimodal options. She really cares about each student's individual interests and fosters and environment where you master the course materials by following your own path.

Professor Martin Sotomayor is a wonderful professor! He truly cares for his students and takes into consideration their feedback. Professor had many interesting questions and ideas to pose to us based on our texts, and made the class material extremely accessible. He is always willing to meet, as well. His teaching was a worthwhile experience.

Prof. Wilkins was by far my favorite professor that I've had at BC thus far. I was in his Perspectives class, and though there is a great deal of reading, I found it incredibly fascinating. This is a challenging class, but I would absolutely take it again.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Hilarious--So many papers

comment_Rating: Purely discussion based class. Absolutely no lectures and all classes are spent in discussion, even the 2 and a half hour long period is used fully. Essays are harshly graded. Oral exams are tough. Not an easy class.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Get ready to read--Participation matters

comment_Rating: Definitely one of the most interesting and caring professors at BC. She is bad w/ tech and does take a while to respond/grade, but is very self-aware. She also notices/appreciates participation which can help since you're only graded on only 3 things. Material is easy to comprehend so just pay attention and you'll be fine.

The only assignments are a midterm, paper & final. Class is 2hrs&30mins, so class can drag b/c she is quiet & monotone, but she showed lots of videos and the material was very interesting. She is not a harsh grader at all, but she takes forever to return your grades. Midterm was easy, and you can choose any topic for the paper. Bad w/ technology.

I did not enjoy this course or this professor. We had to do homework and learn the content for the work we had the next day the day before the class and she often did cold calls in class. Getting below a certain threshold on a test always makes her ask if you actually care about the class. She oftentimes responds days after seeing emails.

She's a nice professor and the class isn't bad. She calls on everyone at least twice in every class and there is a test every week. She is a really easy grader with homework you just have to get in your work on time. The one complaint is that you have to teach yourself the work for class before the class starts and there's homework every class.

Undeniably one of the best theology teachers at Boston College, cares about their students and helping them improve their writing skills, and also has cool activities like looking at different bibles from different time periods, to just having really interesting readings, in regards to Christianity in more broad and varied genres in due time itself
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Gives good feedback

comment_Rating: Prof Bonar gives very interesting, accessible lectures that actually make Theology fun. Very organized Canvas sight and very nice. Few papers, easy grader, good class for Core.

Was definitely a goofy character, and he seems a bit awkward in front of the class, but for me this made the class more fun. Chaotic energy, and you know things are getting gritty when he starts using the chalkboard to explain something.

Nice guy but cant teach for the life of him. Unless you can teach yourself the material dont take a course with him. Doesn't complete notes in class or submit completed notes on Canvas. Constantly says he doesn't know what he's doing. Forgetful and unable to actually teach.

If you have to take finite, Contreras is a solid option. The class is boring but the concepts are clear with the packets he gives. The exams are ok if you study and attendance isn't mandatory. I would take it if you have to get your math core.

This course is so frustrating because he does not teach in a style that works for me. His lectures aren't helpful whatsoever. He mentions a definition one time without using it in context, and then uses that word in a future definition even though the class still doesn't know what it means. Tests are meh. Uses Pearson which sucks. Frustrated.

Super super chill. Class is not mandatory and he is really lenient on homework deadlines. Tests are easy and the homework questions will prepare you for them. Lectures can be boring and he is a bit scattered but overall an easy course.

The class is really boring and his lectures are not super helpful. It sometimes seems like he doesn't know how to explain some topics (like you just have to know them), and he's definitely all over the place. Kinda conceptual course material but it's not that hard if you study the course worksheets.
He is a very knowledgeable person, but not the best teacher. Very scatter brained in my opinion and slow lectures. Mostly, I just took my own notes outside of class.

He was a fine teacher, if you took AP 4 in high school and placed into ele 2 the class itself is pretty easy.  He is accommodating if you get severely sick which was helpful for me but for any spanish class you have to try because they want you to fail

One of the best Spanish profs, wish I could take him for Intermediate as well. Lots of interactive learning, in-class activities, and clear & concise instruction. Prof. Moon explains concepts very well in class, and is easily accessible for extra help as well.

Prof Moon is super organized and a very interactive teacher. He truly does want you to succeed, despite BC's Spanish Department doing every little thing to make it difficult to finish even with a B. He is super accessible outside of class for emails and office hours. He is a very good prof.

He is a great professor. I had him for Elementary Spanish 2. He makes class interesting and interactive. I have taken Spanish for many years, and he was easily my best teacher. It is the most I have learned Spanish. I highly recommend. He is also very accessible for office hours, easy to talk to and ask questions to, and helpful for tests.

Professor Moon really takes the time to explain Spanish concepts to students and this makes learning easier. He also makes clear what he's looking for on exams and this makes it easier for the student to get a higher grade.

Professor Moon is a great professor. He cares about his students, and makes Spanish fun. We did a lot of interactive learning which was enjoyable. I learned a lot in his class. He is really good at explaining why things are the way they are in the Spanish language which definitely enhanced my experience in his class.

Genetics with Prof. Losick is very easy. There are four exams, but the lowest one gets dropped. Exams are easy, and there are other assignments that boost your grade. Attendance is mandatory, but lectures are extremely boring.

Petillo is amazing. Chill beyond chill. His lectures were very discussion based and quite interesting. Learned a lot from him. Didn't think I did well on some of the papers, but he still pulled through and gave me pretty good grades. Final was a take home paper. Would 100% recommend.

Took an Enduring Questions class with him and it was super chill. Very easy-going, has very informing lectures, and always provides good feedback. He placed more emphasis on discussions in class than lectures, but as long as you listen and seem engaged you'll be fine. 10/10 recommend.

Professor Petillo is an excellent professor! He made theology so much fun to learn about, and he is so passionate about his teaching. I would recommend him to anyone who needs to fulfill the theology requirement!

Best professor I have ever had, and he deserves a 5.0. Class is a perfect balance of open discussions and him talking. It is not lecture heavy but all ideas of different philosophers are clearly explained, and the discussion really gets you digging into philosophy concepts and sharing them. Just take this guy-smart, kind and open minded. Love him.

Professor Petillo is truly amazing. I had a family member pass away toward the end of this course. He was so accommodating and let me take my time to catch back up with the rest of the class. His assignments are easy to do and don't take much time, yet are designed to make you engage with the course and learn well. Cannot recommend him enough!

Professor Petillo is the GOAT. Super easy but also very engaging. Not to mention he is the sweetest guy. Other classes complain about him because they're jealous of how easy his class is compared to others. One of my favorite professors

Professor Petillo is amazing! 10/10 recommend, he is a super caring and relaxed professor. The class has a lot of interesting discussions, and you don't really have to do the readings. Exams are take home and can be worked on collaboratively. As long as you participate and put some effort into the class you will be able to get an A.

Professor Petillo has a way of explaining the content and ideas of different philosophers very eloquently. So much so that you don't really have to read the readings since he ends up covering most of the important/relevant points in the texts. Can't stress enough how engaging his class is. If I could have him for all my classes I would. He the GOAT

Petillo is hands down the best perspectives professor. Classes are extremely relaxed and discussion heavy. Participation is 25% of your grade so talking in class. Exams are all take-home and collaborative. He basically says all of the answers in class so take good notes. A lot of dense and heavy reading but really only need to skim before class.

No clarity whatsoever in grading policies, likely doesn't grade the final exam. Discussions are common, but will often be poor quality because the professor does little to prevent repetition. The class itself is easy, but avoid this professor if you want a professional course

Petillo is truly great at explaining concepts for PHIL and THEO while allowing great discourse. I recommend at least skimming the readings before class, but you can certainly get a good grade if you just participate in the thoughtful discussions he supervises and apply class notes to the exams. Petillo is one of my favorite professors at BC!

One of the best professors at BC. Kind, caring, passionate and an easy grader. Just show that you're listening and engaged. Goes over assigned readings in class to the point where actually reading the textbooks is unnecessary. If you have the chance, take him.

Prof. Petillo is extremely kind, caring, and compassionate. Although the class is discussion heavy, he makes the environment welcoming and genuinely listens to what every person has to say! You should try to talk in class as often as possible, but dont worry if thats not every day. The exams require some thinking, but the class is interesting!
The best professor I've ever had. He is very engaged in his classes and no reading or attendance is necessary to keep up. Interesting

Best professor I have had. If you wanna take perspectives I would recommend Petillo over any other prof. Extremely light work load but the classes are EXTREMELY discussion based and highly informative and interesting. Doesnt even feel like class but like a genuine intellectual conversation. He really engages every point from students. 100/10

An amazing professor. I wasn't looking forward to Perspectives since I just wanted to get core out of the way but he taught it in such an interesting way that it became my favorite class. Understandable and knowledgable professor and very flexible.

Amazing professor. Truly cannot speak highly enough on him. Made class so interesting and fun but also had a light workload and understood we had other classes. Incredibly engaging and empathetic. If I could give him a 100/5 I would.

By far my favorite professor. His class is very manageable, and he is very lenient with deadlines, office hours, or any kind of accommodations. His lectures are also very interesting, and he brings a new perspective and passion to what he teaches. Definitely want to take another class of his again.

Not too hard, participation is pretty much a guaranteed A, pay attention to review classes for the tests, homework is reading but not mandatory. Really awesome professor, interesting, makes the class actually fun to go to

hes not very hard, all the answers to exams are given in lectures so you should go. take good notes, but you don't really have to do the readings he assigns and you will still pass. but someone does to create a conversation Lol.

literally changed my freshman year for the better. one of the best educators i've ever had. I only wish he taught more classes so I could take him again this year. I will be visiting his office hours often in the next 3 years just to hear his opinions on things. truly awesome person

literally one of the greatest people you will ever meet (and you'll get to know a lot of profs). He's super chill but genuinely listens to what each and every single student has to say and think. Also really into meditation and awareness, and is just a genuinely kind person in general. Pretty easy with workload, too.
Has a very laid back teaching style. The first test may catch you off guard because it's fairly hard. But after that, it's easy to do well.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Participation matters--GRADED BY FEW THINGS

comment_Rating: She's very passionate about what she teaches, but extremely hard art core. The exams are all memory-based, and there over dozens of works of arts to learn and compare/analyze significance. She talks very fast so its hard to keep up with notes sometimes. She is a very sweet person and cares about her students. Don't take if u want an easy grade.

Staudinger is one of the nicest professors I've ever met. Kind of like a crazy grandma, she is super caring and passionate about what she teaches. Class is tough though if memorization isn't your strong suite. Lots of information to know for the quizzes, midterm, and final. Otherwise, you don't have any homework or readings that you have to do.

I admire Prof. Staudinger's passion for Art History/teaching. She's an exceptional conversation partner with a kind soul. Lectures heavy, expectations abnormally high for a core class (Level 1000), assignments are tedious. Don't take this class unless you're using art history in your career. Better classes out there that fill core requirements.
ratingTags_Rating: Lecture heavy--Graded by few things--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: She's caring and funny, but not that precise of a professor. The class is all memorization and her lectures stray away from the material we need to know. I respect her passion a lot and personally didn't have a problem keeping up in class, but memorization is my strong suit. It's not for everyone, so take another section if you think that's best.

Clinically insane. Not sure how anyone could actually think this course makes any sense. Final included a 200 PAGE STUDY GUIDE and had to go on useless trips outside of class on our own. Will never apply any of the useless information I learned in this course I took for a core. Worst mistake of my life

Has a crazy obsession with tympanums. Loves what she does but nobody else does and she can't get the hint. I had to go to the MFA for no reason and take a selfie... like why? Twice actually we had to do that. Worst class I've ever taken, she reminds me of the receptionist from monsters inc.

Most useless and ridiculous class I've ever taken. The class is basically looking at churches and its so so boring. The test study sheets were almost 200 pages long each and we had to memorize everything. She expected at least 7 hours of work a week which is insane for an art core. I used to have an appreciation for art, now I can't stand it.

The class was harder than it needed to be especially for those with no experience with physics. comment_Rating: Took Prof. Herczynski for PHYS1400. Grading criteria are often unclear (esp. for midterm project and final project). I got a lot out of the class but the vague criteria was frustrating. That being said, he is generally very open to meeting outside of class

The other reviews are some cap. I took Herczynski freshman fall and he was super energetic, passionate about physics, and always stepped in the flyest fits. I mean he pulled up straight bleeding. If you take his jokes the right way and do your best to avoid taking things personally like these other lil dudes, it can be a very rewarding class.

Kersch is a great guy, and his lectures are some of the most interesting I've ever taken. comment_Rating: Honestly the best class I've ever taken. Reading gets a lot, but the things on the tests mostly cover the parts of readings focused on in class. Sometimes I wonder what the point of learning about these older authors is, but as soon as I'm in class it all goes away. Truly enjoy it and professor Kersch is so invested and accommodating.

Like all poli sci classes the reading is insane, but if you at least skim and make an effort to participate fairly often, you'll find that the exams and papers will come a lot easier. He is a really engaging professor, but do be warned that 65%+ of class time is based in group discussion, but it doesn't feel forced and he doesn't usually cold call.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: Awesome professor who does a good job at starting class discussions. He has a really witty sense of humor and gets to know students who participate. Taking him next semester again!

comment_Rating: Professor Kersch is very engaging with the material and clearly cares about explaining it and sparking class discussion. The class does not follow the syllabus exactly, but he still teaches well. Not the hardest class ever, but I would not recommend taking him if you are younger.

comment_Rating: Avoid him at all cost!!!!!
Arrogant. Inapproachable. Super disorganized classroom setting and study materials. Super knowledgeable about the subject though. Not my favorite. Probably would take a different professor next time.
Makes topics understandable, still difficult class. Homework is manageable and graded easily, helps you to learn the material. sense of humor.
Spent most of the time showing off how smart he is and how well connected he is to the industry. Probably the most arrogant college professor I've ever seen.

This guy was a HORRIBLE professor.  99% of the time I couldn't understand him, and the remaining 1% of the time he spent being condescending and arrogant.  He didn't care about the student's willingness to learn, and was always unapproachable.

Is always very excited about literature and does a good job in getting the class interested as well by encouraging class discussions, about the book at hand, and it honestly makes LIT CORE much more doable, than if the class consisted of just lectures, so overall a pretty good professor. comment_Rating: DO NOT TAKE FOR LIT CORE. There are better professors out there. Doing the readings is not necessary. Pop reading quizzes are only on Wordsworth and the first part of Hamlet. comment_Rating: Professor Ohi's "Studies in Poetry" is a solid choice if you just want to read and talk about poetry without getting much deeper. Homework pretty much just consisted of reading and. summarizing poems, and there were only a few tests or papers. It is hard to know where you stand grade-wise. He's really kind and understanding.
Prof Ohi is the greatest!
Very funny, very nice, very confusing.

Great professor, always around to help students in need of help understanding the course material. Remember to always do the practice exams, and also to check them over with him before each test for the best results, overall the class was very manageable, and organized. Got me interested, in going down a more applied math route, because of him.

I absolutely love this man! He is kind and jovial, makes a few jokes in class and is very approachable at office hours! He just wants to be your friend. He's also a good teacher and will answer even the dumbest questions without making it seem like a dumb question. He's also brilliant but never flaunts it. Will be taking him again if able to!

Maksym is an above-average professor. He is very friendly and respects every question coming from students, no matter how easy they are. Calc 3 exams in his class got gradually harder throughout the last semester. Still, if you work hard enough you get at least A-. I will definitely take his other higher-order electives if he still teaches them.
ratingTags_Rating: Clear grading criteria--Lecture heavy--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: If you're good at math, this is a good professor, but if you're bad, find someone else. Exams were easy despite what the other reviews said, ended up averaging in the low 90's on them w/o a scale. He's a good dude, I never went to office hours or anything but from the classroom interactions we had he was friendly and approachable.

He is a very nice person who has a weird range of humor which fits us math nerds :-). He's very humble and approachable, and makes me feel like I could do math! I really like him! Also his exam 1 and 2 are not so hard but exam 3 is hard so get ready for the course content to be gradually more difficult as time goes on. Good luck.

Entire grade off a midterm and final, both of which are closed-book and closed-notes. Course material is ridiculously hard, and Derber expects you to memorize all readings and blindly regurgitate them for the exams. Completely out of his depth and a horrible class overall. Save yourself the time and take literally anything else the IS dept. offers.

Prof Derber clearly cares deeply about what he teaches. He is an inspiring teacher and his course truly changed my views of the world and how we interact with each other. He asks thoughtful questions that truly challenge you and your preexisting views.

Derber has written many books on sociology, some of them moderately influental throughout the nation, so I was excited to take his class. However, his lectures are very broad and don't give that much extra insight. Also, research any statistic he gives, he misrepresents most of the statistics he gives. I'd recommend taking a different class.

Great professor who is passionate about what he teaches. He often uses past studies as examples to teach concepts, which makes his lectures engaging and interesting. You can do well if you put time into problem sets and show up to lectures/office hours. Definitely worth it for econometrics.

Econometrics is hard with any prof, but Hughes cares about his students and puts a lot of effort into being accessible outside of class. He's very smart and does a good job teaching material. Problem sets are really hard but I think they are with any metrics class. One midterm, problem sets every 2 weeks. If you reach out, he's nice and helpful.

Once, we were in class and he said that we shouldn't be afraid of raising our hands and giving out answers whether they're right or wrong, and then when someone gave out an answer he literally said "Are you joking?." WHAT?Decent guy, knows a lot about finance but he doesn't have the experience to teach a Finance class, especially at Boston College.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Test heavy--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: Gives a lot of practice (including old exams which are very similar to the real exams) and gives detailed solutions to all the practice material. Also, makes panopto recordings and full lecture notes with the solutions annotated public. If you do the practice, you will do well. Nice guy, decent lecturer, available for help outside of class.

Try to get into the other professor's classes if you can. The fact that we're paying 80k in tuition for a PHD student to teach us is bizarre to me. He lectures a lot, but often goes off long tangents that don't apply to the exams. He speeds through the slides and uses finance jargon to explain harder finance jargon. Decent guy, awful professor.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Lecture heavy--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: Professor Quinn's Linear Algebra class was taught using standards rather than traditional exams and it allowed for more emphasis to be placed on learning the material rather than doing well on exams. While it was challenging to perfect each standard, the repetition of material made it easier to study for the final(which was optional).

I took linear algebra with him and almost all of the test questions were based on weekly homework. He's very awkward but that makes him hilarious. His lectures were sometimes a bit boring and hard, but he explains much more clearly and easily in office hours.

Professor Quinn is a really nice guy and is extremely skilled at math. While he is still adapting to teaching, he gives good examples and does a good job answering questions. His exams are hard but fair, and he is very helpful during his office hours. More importantly, he is a really nice guy and cares about his students.

Prof. Keen is a phenomenal professor. As a math major, he moves at a quick pace, which I appreciate. He is extremely knowledgeable and makes sure that each concept is explained thoroughly (with examples) before moving on. I would highly recommend taking his classes, even if you do not like math.

I did not take calc in high school but as an intro level calculus course, this class was so hard and it really was because of Professor Quinn's teaching style. He used really elaborate examples when we were just learning of a topic and it kind of felt like he was showing off versus teaching the class. Def recommend someone else!
Amazing prof for Calc II! Exams were all very similar to the practice exams that he provided. Written homework was difficult, but manageable. Would definitely recommend.
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--Graded by few things--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: Went to like half of his lectures, so I watched the recordings. Tests were very easy if you complete the reviews and understand how to do each problem in the review.
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--Lots of homework--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: Loved this guy so much--a little awkward but very caring. Great at explaining processes and answering questions. He used colored chalk to help illustrate graphs and equations better, which I thought was really thoughtful. Overall, had a great time, but I did take some calculus in high school (IB Math AI HL) so that may have affected my experience.

Keaton is extremely knowledgeable in math and super nice. He's a great lecturer and takes his time to answer his students' questions. He also takes into consideration students' opinions and suggestions in pretty much anything related to the course. He may come off as rude because of his awkwardness, but genuinely he's super nice.

Keaton is HIM. While a bit awkward, he is very nice and cares for all of his students. He is easy to access outside of class, and he is fun to talk to because he is relatively young. He explains the material well and gives handouts during each class to help students keep up with lectures. Overall, he is a super smart, genuine guy.
He basically humiliated me when I went to his office hours to talk about a problem that I got incorrect in my test. Terrible experience it destroyed my confidence in that class.

I think that he was a really good lecturer,pay attention in class and take notes- youre fine, gives you papers to follow along with what he does in class which is also really beneficial. Only thing is you can tell when he gets nervous or anxious and he gets kind of messy and scattered but overall one of the better math teachers I've had for sure
ratingTags_Rating: Amazing lectures --Clear grading criteria--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: Professor Keaton Quinn is a new teacher. He is a nice man and gives an organized lecture. Calc 1 all follows the same syllabus and he prepares you well for tests.

Quinn's tests are reasonable, but the homework and labs are really hard. I use my notes from high school to study- if you took calc in high school it's good review, but I'd be screwed if this was my first calc class. Lectures are boring and drag on, but he's good about office hours and providing exam study materials.

If you took Calc in high school you'll be fine. 
If you haven't taken Calc before, you're screwed.
Tests are hard, homework comes in reasonable amounts and is good prep for tests.

Professor Quinn is very nice and organized. Sometimes goes a little fast through materials. you must go to class and keep up with the work or you will fall behind. There is a good amount of homework but not to the point of busy work.

Prof Quinn has very organized lectures and covers plenty of practice problems. Going to lecture is vital but the material covered on exams is very transparent. Plan to go to office hours if you struggle with calc, they are very helpful
ratingTags_Rating: Skip class? You won't pass.--Clear grading criteria--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: I took professor Fenn's philosophy of the person 1, and this class was so stressful as she never graded anything, but by the end I got an A. All you need to do is take notes and pay attention, and you'll do fine, but I did not have fun during this class.

Prof Fenn's classes are very lecture heavy and are often difficult to understand. She gives weekly quizzes and requires a lot of reading. Her final is an oral exam and a long paper, and she requires an in class debate. She is an atrocious grader, always late and does not give exceptions. She is a nice enough person, just  not a great professor.

Geniunely awful. Her lectures are unclear, and she is not at all understanding of absences. She takes forever to grade anything, aI was lucky enough to come into the class with a pretty extensive background in philosophy, and I was actually looking forward to it. She sucked the joy out of the topic completely.

She is honestly so mean and grades things last minute and then expects you to finish them at her will. She has no forgiveness for tardiness or absences even though she is late every day and has no sympathy for anything.

Professor Fenn is a very sweet professor and is very well-studied in Philosophy. As intelligent as she is, her lectures are often not the most organized. She does not allow online notes, so oftentimes it is pretty difficult to write down everything she says, and organize the way she says it onto paper.

Professor Fenn was the easiest teacher I have had at Boston College so far. I took her class for both Philosophy of the Person I and II, and it was an easy A. Attendance is mandatory but you get three skips each semester which is super chill. Make sure to take notes during the lectures, because she won't test on anything not covered in class.

Good at explaining material in a clear way. Frequent quizzes but they're quick and easy and she gives lots of study resources

comment_Rating: Because of Covid, it was half in person, half online. Professor Fenn is very good at explanations, and you need to go to understand the material. Great professor!

comment_Rating: Professor Fenn is amazing. Very nice, accommodating, and will make time for you. There are three essays, two exams and an oral final. The essays aren't difficult, but you don't get a lot of time to do them, so start ASAP. Tests are easy if you read. Pay close attention in class; Professor Fenn is really good at explaining things, especially Aquinas

I loved Professor De Vito when taking Intermediate Italian 1 and 2. She cares deeply about her students. I genuinely enjoyed her classes, and I felt like I learned a lot while also having fun enjoying the Italian language and culture.
Shes great but the department is awful
Di Vito is the best. She is very passionate about teaching her students and is super sweet to the whole class. She is also a good grader and is lenient with minor mistakes!

She is literally the nicest professor I've ever had. She cares about students a lot and works hard to see you succeed. The dept. head creates the syllabi for the Italian classes, and he can be out of touch, but she and the other profs fights for the students. The class is mostly pretty easy and enjoyable. I 100% recommend taking her class!

Professor Di Vito is hands down one of the best teachers that I have ever had. She truly cares about her students, and is always available (even after hours) to answer any questions or go over any concepts that are not clear. Tests are difficult, but she goes over the material in class. She's mother-tongue, which is great, and has great humor.

Took this class because there were no options for macro, my biggest mistake. He cold calls, does not teach (told us to learn how to read the textbook because he simply didn't want to teach), and assigns at least two textbook homework per week. Very passive aggressive, treats class like a middle school class. Excessively harsh on grading, and needs the entire class his way. Take another writing teacher and do not be fooled by his niceness the first week.

She is nice enough, but her class structure was sub-optimal to me, the quizzes were worth way too much to only be 5 questions, she would not help you if you asked a question after an assignment was assigned. Accounting can difficult enough without the teacher making it harder.
Professor Rovin is a amazing professor who is super kind and cares about her students

Professor Rovin is one of my favorite professor's I have ever had in my life. She is so easygoing and works with you every step of the way if you need anything, if I could take her again and again, I so would.
Professor Rovin was my favorite professor at BC so far, hands down.

Chirba is the best professor. She's passionate about the subject and wants students to discuss and think about the topics instead of just memorizing information. No tests or papers! The grade is composed of participation and 3 reflection memos, 2 of which act as the final. She prides herself on giving students high grades, so definitely recommend!

Probably one of the best professors I've had at BC. Very approachable and accommodating especially to a first semester freshman. You will read a lot in her class but if you find law interesting then you will love it.

Chirba is awesome! The course is interesting, especially if you are pre-law/med. She is disorganized and I still haven't received any feedback or grades on anything, which is my biggest critique. ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Hilarious--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: Chirba's portion of class consisted of lots of legal reading and court cases. If you do the readings, it's fine, but still exhausting. If you like law, definitely take her; she's an incredibly smart lawyer and learning from her is interesting. A downside is that class was disorganized and readings were sent late over email from time to time.
Very hard tests

super nice guy and wants everyone to do well, but he is not great at explaining concepts. I've taken calc before his class and many times he'd be explaining things that felt irrelevant to a certain topic making it unnecessarily difficult to follow. if you've taken calc before you'll prob be fine but if not it will be a challenge
great teacher overall help a lot to boost your grade and offer a lot of extra help. textbook wasn't needed much.
Nice guy but the errors in lecture and office hours are insane. Took calc in hs, only way i survived (and I barely survived).

Dude can't teach. Simple as that. He's nice but he messes up in class which makes this confusing, and most times he doesnt fix his mistakes until the next class. His homework is nonstop, and his tests are nothing like the review he gives us. He doesnt curve, and overall just isn't lenient with grades. Would not recommend it. Also, he cant spell.
overall nice dude, but can't lecture or explain concepts well
lectures are extremely confusing and unhelpful. Ended up having to teach myself all of the material. I feel dumber when I leave the classroom and more confused then when I entered.

Cal1 (math and science). He's caring and friendly person. BUT, lectures r confusing and he doesn't know how to teach concepts. I did Calc AB and BC, but I got confused when I listened to lectures, so I ended up not going to classes. wouldn't recommend unless u know ur calc, u can get away with not going to classes, and just trying to get the credit
Doesn't explain concisely or well, likes to wander off during lectures, and doesn't focus on exam material. Sounds very nice, but take another professor.

Please do not take her. She is a great person but her class is insanely difficult for an intro to econ class. When 1/3 of the class withdrawls and 1/3 of the class takes it pass fail you know it was not a good learning environment. Take any other intro to econ teacher.
This class blows. The tests are ridiculously hard for no reason. Full of overcomplicated, vague, and confusing questions. I think an Econ Ph.D. would struggle to get an A in this class.

Avoid at all costs. Seriously. I know you are trying to get the core done but don't take her. The exams are difficult in terms of content and she writes the exam for 2.5 hours when we only have 70 min. Her lectures are headache-inducing. I studied for over 20 hours for each exam and took econ in high school, still wasn't enough.
don't take this class, you won't get an A, the exams are literally impossible and she does not curve.

Professor Regan was super nice, approachable, and cared about the wellbeing of her students even amidst a 250 person lecture. Only non-ideal things about the course were the tough/long exams and the homework assignments that didn't exactly follow the lectures, but that's about it. The class wasn't easy, but I thought she explained concepts well.
ratingTags_Rating: Clear grading criteria--Lecture heavy--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: Homework was incredibly frustrating as it followed along with the textbook rather than her lectures. Does her best to make lectures engaging, but overall, not my favorite professor.

Nice prof, but terrible class. Boring, slow lectures w/ long tangents about her life. Slides filled with typos & equations on single lines, hard to read. ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Lecture heavy--Graded by few things

comment_Rating:
Nice prof, TERRIBLE class. Boring, slow lectures w/ long personal tangents. Slides littered with typos. Worst of all, all equations/examples are typed on single line, unformatted. 
Overcomplicates material; terrible explanations of basic concepts. Slides confusing & lazy, exams rushed. All 3 midterms contained errors. Talks too much during exams.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Lecture heavy--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: Lectures are extremely long and boring, the professor tends to repeat the same points constantly. The professor is extremely nice but just not an engaging teacher. If you are an incoming freshman, do not have incredible study habits, or have not taken economics before, taking this class is going to be a challenge. She is a very nice professor and offers a course pack to fill out. Her exams usually take the entire 1hr 15min and her test questions are tricky. Lastly, her lectures are long and boring.

Lectures are painful. Goes off on unrelated tangents about her life in a weird, one-sided conversation with the students in lecture hall. comment_Rating: I liked how this class wasn't curved, making grading transparent and fair. Regan has high expectations, but you'll learn a lot. Highly recommend Regan's office hours before exams.
Lectures are largely uninteresting, exams frequently have errors, class is not very well organized. Avoid if possible

Ignore anyone praising her. She is not good. Tests are full of 5 answers each, and 4 of them are difficult trick answers. Almost every exam she has to give extra credit because somehow her questions don't have answers??? Her lectures were BRUTAL. She sucked at explaining and you must do work out of class to hope for an A

You must-take this course! Regan is nice, passionate, and listens to what you have to say. No tests! 3/4 of semester is lectures, and 1/4 is presentations. Group projects are fun, but harshly graded. Takes up the entire time of the class, brings up random stories that prolong the class time instead of learning actual material. There will never be a time you can leave class early. Prof Regan is very friendly and peppy, but her lectures are not really good for learning. She talks so fast and rambles about a lot. She uses every last second of class but we are always behind. You have to put in SO much effort out of class if you want to understand it. I would have taken another professor.

Prof. Regan goes on tangents on easy/unrelated material and then talks a mile a minute for the important stuff. She also doesn't post lecture slides until exam week. Great introduction to modern health economics! Good at pushing students to connect economic concepts to modern healthcare problems. The lectures were enthusiastic & she welcomed questions. She loves her students and is always willing to help. She truly loves teaching and is very engaging in her lectures. 10 out of 10 recommend!!!

Although this was an asynchronous class, Prof Regan did an excellent job explaining the lecture material in her videos, and always appeared so friendly. She seemed to have a good grasp of how to explain economics to younger people. She is very caring. I recommend taking her class.

Lots of people thought she was difficult this year, but I found her to be very helpful and very kind. Cares a lot about students. Just pay attention during lectures and read the textbook, you should be okay... but not necessarily an easy A.

I took her enduring questions course this year and she is very enthusiastic and a great lecturer. She makes a true effort to know all of her students and appreciates everything anyone has to say. ENGL1009. He is the most caring and understanding professor I have had during my time at BC. He is so sweet and will help with anything. For the multilingual students section we had individual conferences with him to receive feedback on every paper

Puente is a really great professor, especially for first-year students. He is an easy grader, doesn't assign much work, and the class itself is pretty low-key. Papers are given well in advance, and he is super understanding about extensions and absences. Overall, highly recommend!

THE GOAT. Such a nice and caring man. Soft spoken and not intimidating at all which makes it lovely being near his presence. Very understanding. Doesn't require you to do any assignment that is dreadful.

Alex is so nice. He cares so much about students and even though he is a little shy will help them out. I found our FWS class to be kind of boring but maybe because it was my 4th class of my day. He also is an easy grader and doesn't assign a big reading load.
Professor Puente is one of my favorite professors I've ever had in my entire life. He's extremely kind and genuinely cares about all of his students. He made me a better writer and person.

Drones on. Very boring lectures and just goes over code. Does not make sure people are following along. I would avoid him in the future I don't think I really learned much at all because of him.

Easiest class I've taken. It's really boring but you literally don't have to do anything. The mid term and final were essays and we got the prompts a week in advance. He's the nicest guy ever as well, so kind and forgiving. The goat.

Super sweet professor. Homework is easy and even sometimes consists of watching movies. Lectures were mostly him talking and then leaving some time at the end for questions and discussions. lecture were super boring but read the notes and lecture slide and it is easy to pass. no textbook but a lot of short readings. not exam in person but need to writie paper follow main jist of lecture and can easily pass.

such a pleasant professor to have. comment_Rating: Prof. McLaughlin was so sweet and caring. He values discussion above all, so be prepared to read and care about what you're reading. He genuinely loves this subject matter and is dedicated to learning more while teaching. Loved him!

comment_Rating: Professor McLaughlin is great! His lectures can be long, but he really values participation and discussion. Really kind and not too hard of a grader, just be sure to proofread.

comment_Rating: Professor Radillo's class is a breath of fresh air among the first-year writing courses. She grades quite harsh, so it's easy to get a B, but quite difficult to get an A even as a fairly strong writer. You can get away without reading, but most of class is composed of discussion. ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Participation matters--EXTRA CREDIT

comment_Rating: Radillo's assignments were centered around pop culture and media. She allowed us to choose the media we write about for several of our essays, and I was more excited to write since we got to choose our topics. Participate in class and dedicate time towards editing each draft. She genuinely wants her students to have confidence in their writing.

Professor Radillo is young, energetic, and extremely passionate about writing. I think this can kind of rub some people the wrong way. She truly wants her students to succeed, but she is a difficult grader and can be very opinionated sometimes. Attendance is mandatory and she is difficult about excusing it.

comment_Rating: Rutledge was the most amazing professor. Failed the final and still got an A- in his class. If you see him outside of class and try, he will make sure you do well in his class. Hard concepts to understand and a decent amount of work, but worth the hard work for such a great teacher.

Rutledge is an amazing, caring professor! Take advantage of all of the resources he provides. Also, his office hours and help sessions outside of class helps a lot. Make sure to stay on top of material throughout the semester, and don't get discouraged if you're stuck--stick with it. Also, put in effort to get Rutledge to know you. He's great!

Rutledge is one of the nicest and most caring professors in the Econ department. He remembers everyone's names and makes the class actually engaging. I really like him as a person. As a professor, he explains things well but his exams are challenging. However, he really makes it difficult to fail his class. A lot of working in groups in this class

Probably the best Econ professor at BC. Really cool guy who is caring and passionate about what he teaches. Class is challenging with hard and long exams but he gives you so much material (e.g. many old practice exams) that if you just take a week or two before the exams to do them you can do great. It's basically in your hands to do well.

I thought that Prof. Rutledge was a great teacher and tried to make econ stats as clear as possible. He really cares about his students, and while it is a hard class, I think it is worth it to take it with Rutledge as his lectures and test prep materials are very useful.

His class is hard, but stats are hard in general, and he teaches the material well. He has a lot of other assignments that can boost your grade. Very accessible outside of class and is genuinely a great person.

He makes an easy class hard with excessive statistical jargon and does not explain the math of the course well. The grade is composed of many components and there are so many things of which to keep track. However, he is an engaging lecturer who is always available for help if necessary and is always encouraging.

Prof. Rutledge is a great lecturer and I think the increased lecture size this semester made it harder for both him and students to be as involved in the course and help others understand everything. You need to go to the lectures to understand the material, as it is a hard course, and he has review sessions every week if you feel behind.

His exams are way more difficult than the class material and they are very verbal and long. It is very tiring and there is no curve on that difficult exam. I recommend you finding another professor if you want to invest equal amount of time on other classes.

I took his class because people said he is nice and make materials interesting and his notes are great. He is pretty good at explaining things. BUT! there are SO MUCH THINGS that you need to take care of. You have lab project, lab hw, lecture quizzes, lecture p sets, and three exams on top of that.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Lots of homework--So many papers

comment_Rating: Professor Rutledge is tough and will definitely challenge you, but to the extent to that is the case, he is one of the best professors at BC. He cares not only about the material but about you as well as long as you try your best. Highly recommend!

Rutledge is a great lecturer and makes stuff easier to understand. Material is harder on tests than in class but he provides a lot of prep resources and wants students to do well. I feel like I learned a lot, and he assigns a pretty chill amount of homework. I never feel like I'm wasting my time going to class or doing work for it.

Professor Rutledge is an amazing professor. He is very accommodating which I really appreciated when taking this course. His review sessions are great when studying for the class! His lectures are very straightforward, and the exams can seem intimidating but they aren't bad at all. Just have confidence!

Professor Rutledge is elite at what he does. Econ Stats can be a difficult subject, but he puts it in a clear way. Outside of class if you have any concerns he is an efficient communicator and truly cares about his students.  Would absolutely recommend trying to register for his classes (if there is space).

Rutledge is the best professor I have ever had. He isn't easy, but is fabulous at what he does. I had no interest in Stats before his class and now I find myself looking for examples of stats daily. He is really that good. Highest recommendation.

Really great teacher. I usually find economics classes to be dry and boring, but his classes were always engaging. The assignments and class notes prepare you well for the exams if you are willing to put in the work and study them.

Great guy. Huge fan of Rutledge. You'll need to put in some hours, but he's super encouraging and engages course material with his own personal anecdotes/examples and ties them really well to statistics concepts

Exams were incredibly difficult and had very little to do with the homework and lectures. Take home exam at the end of the semester that was impossible. Had no idea what my grade was until the class was over

Prof Errico was a super nice guy, but his lectures were dull and the tests were very difficult. Professor Hale is nice enough and a pretty easy grader. His lectures can be a bit dry and mostly a review of the readings.
Tedious lecture. Easy A.

comment_Rating: Dennis Hale is a boring lecturer, but a kindhearted professor with an easy class that allows you to get an instant A if you just try even a bit. Super lecture heavy and hes a bit dry, but hes really knowledgeable and youll learn a lot. Good amount of writing but if you pay attention then youll do good on them. You can get away with skimming the readings if you pay attention and take good notes during class.
Class is very lecture heavy and lots of readings
Great professor, charismatic and straight forward grading

Reading isn't necessary if you take good notes in class. His lectures are dry, but if you stay awake he will really help you to understand the material. Tough grader, but only assigns three, three page papers and weekly one page summaries.

A complete charlatan. He is often far out of his depth and believes his cruelty to his students makes up for his own lack of rigor. He should not be teaching. I think he even liked me and I performed well, but he will give meaningless work to beat his students into submission (many of those successfully beaten have already written reviews).
Absolutely great guy and an excellent conversationalist in class. Teaches his subject well and really cares about what he teaches. However, his tests are quite difficult so be very very prepared.

Braman is a wonderful professor and a great person. He obviously cares about his students and is always available if you have questions or need help. The expectations for the class were made very clear. DO participate in class because it matters for your grade. Our class was discussion based and it was very enjoyable.

LOVE THIS CLASS! Braman has made me think more than ever before. Best teacher I've ever had. Though he cold calls, it is the best & most life changing class. Get ready to read & be prepared for class. He expects you to give your all because he always does. Sometimes we just chats instead of lecturing. Very good talks. 10/10 would recommend!!!!
Perspectives should be mandatory for all

The subject material is something that demands thought, that being said Professor Braman demands the best from all of his students. He is helpful, cheerful, and a true master of the source material. ENJOY THIS CLASS ASAP!!!

braman is an amazing professor. He damands and deserves respect. The reading can be tough but the class is so worth while. class discussions were always really positive and I learned a lot. Braman's "homilies" are full of wisdom, I wish I could have recorded them to share with my future children. An excellent class that demands work but worth it.

Prof Braman is a great prof. He knows that alot of the students don't really have an interest in philosophy and are just taking his class to meet core reqs, because of this he tries to make it as interesting a possible. Class always seems to get out early, and he will sometimes give you exact answers to a quiz right before he passes it out.

Dr. Braman knows how to do what many college profs fail to do well at and that is 'connecting with his students'. The goal of intellectual development is taking something complex and myopic and making it digestible and easy. Braman excels at this. He's also incredibly funny!
Best teacher I had at BC...  still think about the things from class almost every day
Excellent professor.  He and Fr. Joe Flanagan taught our class.  Both brilliant individuals!

Prof. Braman is awesome - definitely the best professor I've had at BC. He has so much real life experience and he opens himself up so that you can relate with him. The class itself wasn't my favorite, as being a CSOM student, but I learned so much!
One of the best teachers I've had. Maybe the best. He is both caring and able to compromise with assignments, as well as confrontational, making you really think and support your ideas.
Possibly the best professor I had at BC.  Try his Perspectives electives- worth 6 credits but not nearly the work of two classes.

Best professor I have ever had, super great person and very accessible to talk to. He deeply understands the material he teaches and always makes sure to leave time at the end for discussion. Dr. Hudson is amazing!

Defiantly the best Perspectives prof. Only a reasonable amount of papers, and the exams are super hard but curved. He is flexible to move exam dates and due dates, and is interested in any comments students have.
Amazing prof,  need to take another one of his classes!!

Professor Hudson is hands down the best professor to get in terms of Perspectives. He is quite literally the best person ever and is super kind and understanding. Perspectives with Dr. Hudson is your best bet. He's super funny and passionate about philosophy and theology. He's a great guy who just wants everyone to learn and do well.

Dr. Hudson is amazing! I took him for global justice and cosmopolitanism and the class is graded based on 2 or 3 exams and 2 papers. Would highly highly recommend Dr. Hudson
Best teacher I have had at BC. Super caring, interested in what he is teaching, and not difficult if you pay some attention. Cant recommend Hudson enough. 100/10

Very good for intro philosophy courses. Passionate and gives interesting lectures. Always respectful of students and really values discussion.
Great Professor. Great class. Hes the reason Im a philosophy major.

best professor I've ever had. he cares more about the students than assigning grades. he gives so many opportunities for you to succeed and you actually learn about moral arguments. he lets you speak your mind and never judges or makes you feel like if you have a different opinion your grade will be affected by it. most caring and thoughtful prof!!
Dr. Hudson is definitely the best professor I've ever had!
Hudson is a great prof. would take his classes again.
Would recommend
You cant (Kant) pass up an opportunity to take one of Dr. Hudsons classes!

I had Father Gallagher for Courage to Know in fall 2020 but I absolutely loved him. At first, I couldn't find any reviews so I was worried but it turns out he was super nice and chill, and made class fun. He is super understanding and very flexible. However, he may not be the best professor and can get off topic quite easily.

Overall, Professor Gallagher is pretty solid. His lectures are really interesting. However, he's not very organized. His lectures jump around and don't follow the Powerpoints on the board. There are no papers, however, each individual question on any given test can determine an entire percent of your final course grade. He's a nice guy though.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Test heavy--Amazing lectures

comment_Rating: Father Gallagher is an adorable professor (he reminds me of Samwise Gamgee from Lord of the Rings). His lectures are fast-paced, but effectively given and easy to internalize if you're a fast typer. Homeworks are readings that are somewhat tied to the lectures; I've read three readings and I'm doing fine (quizzes and tests are only on lectures).
ratingTags_Rating: Accessible outside class--Skip class? You won't pass.--Hilarious

comment_Rating: This class is the worst I have taken in my academic career. I had to rewatch each lecture twice to understand the incredibly-in-depth-word-vomit that he spewed each lecture. Quizzes were weirdly specific and take home tests had no partial credit (failing was not uncommon). Please spare yourselves your sanity and never take one of his classes. Ever.

Folker is a hard professor, but my favorite at Boston College. He forces you to change your way of thinking and approach problems more effectively. I had more success in classes I took after this class because it changed the way I learned and studied for the better. If you are struggling to understand in class, office hours make a huge difference.
ratingTags_Rating: Accessible outside class--Skip class? You won't pass.--Amazing lectures

comment_Rating: Avoid at all costs. HE DOES NOT TEST WHAT HE TEACHES. You can study 20 hours on his lectures, but then he'll test you on material you've never heard of. In the final he asked us questions about concepts we'd NEVER EVER studied, the questions are terribly worded, and he won't clarify the question if you ask. He's not an educator.

This man took over for our biological chemistry class it was the worst thing to ever happen to me. He is the least empathetic creature on the planet and his final asked questions that our class was incapable of answering since we never learned them. If you have the choice between getting hit by a bus or taking a class with him, choose the bus.
ratingTags_Rating: Skip class? You won't pass.--Graded by few things--Tough grader

comment_Rating: Folker wants you to meet his standards. By that, I mean that the class will be one of the hardest, if not the hardest Bio you'll take. You need to consistently keep up with the material every day, focus on literally EVERY WORD he says, and go to office hours--he has hours every single day, 8 AM. You do that and you'll be fine. Book is useless.
ratingTags_Rating: Skip class? You won't pass.--Lecture heavy--Tough grader

comment_Rating: Folker has to be one of the most irrational professors I've ever had. He gives no partial credit on multipart 25 point questions. And openly jokes about how poorly his students are doing and about "failing half the class" without making any effort to ACTUALLY help. Take this only if you want your self confidence and dignity slashed.

Wait for Weerapana to come back! Folker takes off points left and right and hates partial credit. And gets mad at you if you try to ask him for points back. Your grade is out of the average of the top ten students, but most of the top ten students have the old exams so don't take the class unless u have the old exams. :)

Worst professor I've ever had in college. Extremely elitist and snarky. Does not teach you the material nearly as in depth as his exams are. Explains complicated topics so vaguely and brief yet expects you to know how to perfectly design whole experiments. Grades exams extremely hard (no partial credit). Raw exam averages are in the 30%'s.

Folker is so irrationally difficult as a professor, I felt it was my duty to warn future students about this class. Average for exams were 40-50s, so it's not about a student's "mentality", this professor is 1)Not teaching in a meaningful manner 2)Testing for an unwarranted & insane level of understanding. Getting run over is a better use of time

Best lecturer I've had. Changes the way you think about biology (from thinking about probabilities to thermodynamics to forces). I could not stress how awesome he is. At the end of the day if you're whining about the grade it's probably cuz you have the wrong mentality going into the class. Also, I have no idea where those numbers came from.

Be aware, this class, is advertised as being an easy and fun class, to freshman, and although it is fun and very eye opening, it is definitely not easy, there are a bunch of papers, most of which have some side process one had to do to get the paper done. That being said, Dr.Bracher, definitely helped me become more confident in who I am in time.

Let me burst the bubble--Biz is overrated. She talks about open-mindedness, yet only listens to povs that agree with hers. She made me cry more than any other professor. Her class is hard and she is a tough-grader. If you want an easy A, take any other professor. Biz has a big ego and is intimidating, but the topics discussed were interesting.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Get ready to read--Participation matters

comment_Rating: W professor and a great person to know at BC. Hardest CTK class out of the professors bc she is the head of the department. It's worth it though bc she is an amazing advisor. She cold calls, so at least skim the reading or be the first to participate. Do the readings at the beginning of the year bc those come up throughout the course. Mom energy

Prof. Bracher is one of the best Professors at BC ever. She is genuine, caring, and wants the best for her students both inside and outside of her classroom. She is very easy to reach and you should go to her office hours during the semester to talk about the class and life in college in general. She's a bit of a tough but fair grader, but worth it

TAKE BIZ!  She was the best professor I've had at this school so far.  I wouldn't say her class is necessarily an easy A, but if you do the readings and participate in class you'll do fine.  I would highly, highly recommend her!

Biz is a phenomenal teacher, who is readily accessible during office hours. Do know though that her course of CTK is much harder than the others. ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--Lots of homework--Get ready to read

comment_Rating: TAKE THIS CLASS. Biz works hard to make the class informative, worthwhile and interesting, and I feel like I have grown so much in this class. She holds you to high standards and there's a fair amount of reading, but helps you to be your best. I look forward to going to class and have learned a lot. Not an easy A but fun and interesting

Lectures are a quick 50 minutes, midterm/final are taken home with multiple days to complete. Prof. Peychev is accessible through email and you can contact him with any conflicts/questions and he will respond. You have a take-home quiz once a week with ten questions- very easy- and that is your only homework. Occasionally will offer extra credit.
Peychev is an understanding and respectful professor and is very straightforward with grading and content.

Globalization is the easiest class at BC. Quizzes and exams are all take home. Lectures were recorded, so 2/3 of the class would not show up. Participation makes up 15% of your grade, but if you respond to the discussions on Canvas you'll be fine.
Easiest class I've taken at this school.  Quizzes and exams were all online and notes are posted on Canvas.
Extremely nice professor, helped me a lot in learning R code. She cares about her students. Even though I wasn't the best at coding she helped me a lot and supported me through the semester.
ratingTags_Rating: Participation matters--Clear grading criteria--Lots of homework

comment_Rating: The class itself is fairly challenging and reasonably fast paced, however Wei's lectures were extremely easy to follow and understand. At least once a week she would have an interactive activity in class, she genuinely cares about having her students want to come to class/office hours. Incredibly accessible by both email/office hours.

Professor Wei is a great professor and an even better person. Super accessible outside of class and really wants to see you succeed. Although there is a lot of homework, she is really understanding if you need to submit anything late. Would definitely take her again if I had the chance to.
Very kind professor, pretty good lectures. Cares about her students and gave fair exams. Sometimes a lot of work, but the class itself is pretty easy.

Professor Wei is one of the kindest, sweetest teachers I've had. She always makes jokes, spiced up lectures with activities, and has a genuine love for statistics and seeing people succeed. It's a hard class, don't get me wrong, but she's a great person!

Probably the best professor at BC. She has a beautiful personality and is very approachable outside of class! Although the course itself is challenging, you will learn a lot if you put in the effort! I will recommend her to everyone I know.

Great professor; definitely tough and pushes her students but great class overall. She is very accessible and does a great job at explaining concepts. But you definitely need to be on your toes during lectures!
Good professor definitely explains concepts well.

Wonderful and extremely knowledgeable professor. Easy to talk to and get help after hours. Definity a fast passed class, and the material isn't the easiest, but stay on top of things and you will be okay. I would recommend her to anyone.

One on one prof moore is an amazing person! I really like her and her accomplishments are great. Definitely go to office hours to meet her. Slightly difficult for a intro to psych class- other profs are easier. But she is by far the most interesting.

Great core class. Midterms/quizzes chill, lectures move quickly but I still feel like I've learned. Class moves quickly, can miss 3 classes before it affects participation. Would def take again - workload is very reasonable and midterms totally fine if you study the lecture slides/videos she posts on canvas.
She went over course material so quickly and had us do quizzes every single week EVEN DURING SCHOOL breaks. She didn't explain very well I wouldn't recommend her at all.

Quizzes are online and super easy. Exams are just as easy, but you'll still have to study for them. Moore is nice, and I suggest you go to office hours at least once because it boosts your participation grade.
She was chill, definitely read off the slides a lot, but the tests were pretty straight forward and she was very enthusiastic about the material.

TAKE THE OTHER INTRO TO PSYCH PROF! She does not explain concepts that well. She makes the class SO hard for an intro class. Doesn't know how to work canvas/ she erased all our quiz answers. Bad at grading (inconsistent and takes up to a month). Harsh on attendance even if your sick
She talks too much about her adopted son with no relation to class material.

She deleted all the Panopto recordings, making it difficult for people who missed class to catch up despite having a final coming up. Unnecessarily difficult class by requiring stupid polls with questions that don't help. Way too interactive for an introductory class. You will have to do useless discussions.

It seemed like every single day was a race to cover as much material in as little depth as possible, while giving the students the least amount of time possible to take notes and absorb the material. Although my typed words per minute have skyrocketed during this class, my cortisol has matched it. At least she seemed really excited about teaching?

Professor Moore always approaches class with enthusiasm and keeps me very engaged throughout her class. She implements interesting and fun ways to learn the information, and the tests are manageable so long as you pay attention in class and study the slides. I am definitely going to try to take another one of her classes in the future.

She is a very good professor although not that reachable. Her classes are fun to go to and she tries to keep it as lively as possible. Her tests are easy if you pay attention in class and read the slides, but overall very easy. She requires you to buy the book but honestly I have opened it once and never again so dont waste the money.
Professor Moores lectures are interesting and clear, and she seems to be very kind, positive, and accommodating! The assignments and exams are manageable, and overall the class is great!

Prof Moore is always energetic and ready to go with a smile on her face. Every class is lecture based straight from the book, but the slides and recording are posted to canvas. There is lots of textbook reading, but you can probably get by without it. There are 3 tests, which aren't hard if you prepare and know the basic terms.
Prof Jacobs is among the best lecturers I've ever seen. His paper grading is fair, unlike his exam grading.
Love this man. He lectures with such a theatrical flair that I personally enjoyed and I appreciate his humor. Has quite a sass that I loved

Professor Jacobs is a polarizing professor. I know many who like him. Personally, I couldn't stand him.

He talks too fast and is prone to making unnecessarily rude comments on graded papers. 

I took my dad to one of his lectures during parents' week. He was not impressed, saying "He just seems to like the sound of his own voice"

Prof Jacobs is the most memorable professor I have ever had. After every lecture he left me with stories to call home about. He is hilarious and extremely well-spoken. The grade is 100% based on exams and my TA was kinda strict with grading but if you study well before the exams, you'll be fine. Cannot recommend America and the World 2 enough!

Seth Jacobs is a magnificent man. I've always had a somewhat loathsome relationship with history but this man has made me enjoy coming and learning about failures of america. you can tell he enjoys what hes teaching & he makes it funny to learn. adds his own special spark to every lecture. would take a million times over
I hated history in high school, but this class completely changed my view. He is so engaging and there is never a dull moment in his lectures.

AMAZING professor! Such entertaining lectures. I hated history in high school, but this class changed my perspective. All of the exam content comes directly from lecture. Wouldn't say it is an easy A, but definitely an interesting class.

Seth is the man. As a former dramatic performer, he knows how to make a captivating lecture. I think I only got bored once or twice during the entire semester. It's amazing how he manages to speech for 50 minutes without a single stutter or "um" or "uh." Unlike most History courses, it is entirely graded on exams, but they are very easy.

Jacobs is easily the best lecturer at BC. I'd often go to class tired and leave feeling like I had just chugged a six pack of Red Bull. The material is extremely comprehensive, and conducive to developing a nuanced opinion on a controversial subject. The class is based off of four exams, but as long as you dedicate time to studying you'll be fine.

I love going to this class. The exams are a little harder than I expected but he sets you up to do well. He's really passionate about the material and I feel like I've learned a lot. He assigns a lot of readings, but they aren't necessary to do well in the class. Overall just a very nice guy who wants students to learn every perspective on the war.

a very good lecturer but he talks very fast so it was hard to take notes. Took america and the world with him and the final killed my final grade becuase of so much lecture material it was hard to study. still his impressions were entertaining

Took foreign policy expecting an easy history class and I got a pretty bad grade. Paper grading is pretty subjective and there are basically no office hours to review. But the professor is a really nice guy with fun lectures, just not an easy A.

His lecturing style is on another level. I've heard he is a former actor and this comes out when he reads quotes imitating a historical figure. As someone who never really liked history, he made America and the World one of my most enjoyable classes at BC.
Prof. Jacobs is the single most engaging lecturer I have ever witnessed in my life. If you have the opportunity to take his class, do not pass it up. Trust me.
Love this man
Interesting lectures. Very chill. Quizzes are easy. I had him for America and the World II.
Amazing professor. His Vietnam War class is a must-take at BC.

Favorite professor i've had at BC. Super passionate about the material. loves it more than his wife. i took vietnam while it was asynch bc of covid and he killed the recording lectures. we had 4 papers no exams. highly recomend this class even if not history major/minor. send it

Great professor, lectures were interesting and engaging even though they were on the computer. Would recommend for anyone to take if looking for a history class/elective. Falls short in the hotness category. Overall one of the best lecturers I've had at BC.

Although Mr. Seth Jacobs is well-respected in the academic world, as I am sure he should be, his concern for his students is far below average and he is quite an incompassionate hardo who lacks the ability to truly reflect on the effect a GLOBAL PANDEMIC has on his young, malleable students.

Professor Jacobs is a former actor who gives lectures that are equally informative and entertaining. Tests are pretty basic (IDs, short-answers, long essay) based on his lectures alone. Overall the class is super easy and really interesting. Take the class!

Thoroughly enjoyed Professor's Jacob's America's War in Vietnam class because he presented stimulating lectures by providing a variety of viewpoints. He is captivating with his energy and accents. Professor Jacobs is incredibly passionate about every course he teaches, with this one being no exception. Thanks, Seth!
Hilarious, honest, humble and brilliant. One of the best at BC.

Professor Jacobs is a hilarious and extremely interesting professor. He assigns a ton of reading, but if you attend the lecture you don't have to do ANY of it. If your a BC student his class on Vietnam is one of the classes you have to take while at BC. My friend and I used to record the lectures and listen to some of them later on.
One of the best teachers ever, and by far! Great charisma, 1000% available to help his students, correct drafts and introductions, great readings and very entertaining lectures...

Absolutely incredible man. He is really passionate about 19th century Russian Literature and history. Definitely not an easy Lit Core class, there is a LOT of reading involved, but he is inspirational and if you have even the slightest interest in Russian Literature (19th cent ideally) take him!!!
