comment_Rating: Linear Algebra is a difficult class, especially if you don't have practice exams...Don't get me wrong, David is a nice guy and approachable, but I did not find his way of teaching a best fit.

Professor Treumann is one of my favorite professors I have had. He's really nice and understanding, and was willing to give us more time on hard homeworks or if he knew we had a lot going on. Tests varied in difficulty, the first one was easier, but the next two were harder. We had weekly homework graded for accuracy, but they were not too long.

Wow! I literally created a Rate My Professor account to talk about Prof. Ucerler. I took his Premodern Japanese History class and this guy is amazing. So incredibly smart with an insane knowledge of Japanese History! Found myself in class wishing it was longer so we could learn more. Amazing must take prof!

Prof. Uyan was very friendly and made an exceptionally tough and reading-heavy course much more palettable. She didn't design the course, it's not hard because of her, and she did her best to make it a smooth process for each of us. Very responsive to emails and was incredibly kind and helpful across the board.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Lots of homework--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: Your grade in Professor Williams course relies mainly on a semester long project. The class is curved down and results in a much lower grade than what you actually deserve. One missed homework assignment when the entirety of that grasp is worth 7% of your grade is the difference between half a letter grade.
Shes chill ngl

Chandini is a very charismatic Prof; she explains concepts well with clear examples. Homework assignments and discussion sections will be very helpful in understanding the material for this class. Exams are straightforward if you review the practice exams, practice exercises, and attend review sessions.

All good stuff is past tense. She is now tough. Her standards are really rigid and no extra credit is available. She is not nice. If you have necessities, she will not accommodate you at all. She is not good at reassuring but being mean when you are in downtime. If you try to reach out to her after the semester, she will treat you as a stranger.

Say what you will but I loved Chandini. She was funny and approachable outside of class, and was passionate about teaching though lectures would get very long and boring. The curve in her class is the worst part about it because people's grades are lower than they should be. Tests are manageable if you study her lectures and the practice tests.
ratingTags_Rating: EXTRA CREDIT--Lecture heavy--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: Chandini really isn't a bad prof at all. She is a bit of an odd-ball, but very sweet! She offers extra credit too! She gives out good study guides for exams, and the textbook and her PP's are very useful tools for exams. Make sure to be in class since she does PollEv questions.

Nice professor. Super easy materials so she needs pollev as participation to make you stay in class. Easy exam as well, but stay focused. Any potential mistakes may make you from an A to a B+ since only 30% can receive A/A-, I believed almost 40+ students received 95+ in exam2 so even a 95 may can't make it to an A in that exam. Pretty insane huh.

Prof Chandini is sweet and understanding, and she is really thoughtful to her students. For exams, she provides review sessions and old exams for practice. She definitely has an interesting personality, but people make her sound so bad for no reason. The class is easy, the homework is simple, and the exams are manageable.

This class is a complete joke but only the top 30% of students can earn an A or A-. The content itself is really easy, so the competition for the grade is intense. The lectures are painfully boring and repetitive, and the professor is very rigid and not accommodating at all. I missed an exam due to severe illness, and she would not allow a makeup.

Honestly i did not understand why some people did not like her class; honestly her energy is unmatched with other professors. Econ 1101 was easy breezy. econ dept here is nice. love you chandini although u wont see it

Chandini tries her best to make class engaging, but lectures end up being mediocre. Tests are VERY difficult and it is nearly impossible to get one on one feedback because she has 400+ students. She has poor control over students in lecture, so the room is often loud which makes it difficult to focus. Homework is light and extra credit matters!!!!

The only thing interesting about Chandini is how annoying and obnoxious she is. I'm honestly at a loss for words for how much I disliked her class despite my interest in economics. Her only "guuds and suhvuces" are how awful of a Professor she is in an entry-level class despite years of education.
Makes things way more complex than they have to be. The lecture hall is loud and not verge engaging
Lectures are enjoyable and easy to follow. Weekly homework is very light. Exams are full of questions that try to trick you, so read carefully.

Chandini makes me want to get up in the morning. She is what every student ASPIRES to be. Her lectures are always funny she likes to play funny music. Her exams are straightforward because she gives great study guides and learning opportunities.
I enjoyed my class a lot. She was always very engaging, and helpful. She also gave good study guides and often encouraged the class to do well.

Chandini is very funny, she is very high-spirited in all her lectures. However, the grading scale she has makes me not like the class. her lectures are not that engaging and there is a lot of talking between students during them. For an intro class, she is a fine instructor. A lot of it is on you to succeed.

Anyone who gave this woman a five star is either a chandini burner account or someone paid to do so. The only reason she isn't a 1 star in my book is because she isn't the worst instructor I've ever seen, though she's close. She is geniunely a dislikeable person who is outright obnoxious and annoying, I feel bad for anyone who has her for their PHD
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Lecture heavy--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: she's a tough grader for this course. Think about it, it's ONLY an introductory class!
Chandini underrated

Very unaccommodating if you have something else come up in your life.  Seemed to think that her basic economics class that students take because they have to should have been the center of my universe.

Prof. Chandini was definitely NOT my favorite professor. She is really obnoxious and her exams are difficult. That being said, working hard will pay off, and it's not impossible to do well (especially given the fact that she gives extra credit)! Please take the other professor if you can, but know that studying a lot can still get you a good grade.
Good professor
Good professor but tough. Overall, worth it though because you learn a lot

Chandini is awesome! Her class was my favorite class at BC this semester. I learned a lot. She always played music in the beginning of class and related it to Econ. She does a good job explaining the material. Sometimes she would get really excited about the material. I never thought I would like Econ but after taking her class Im majoring in it.

I took her final today. Honestly was one of my favorite classes at BC so far (I am a sophomore). She was really engaging, knew the material very well, and was enthusiastic. Overall, a great professor and would highly recommend. Material can be challenging, but definitely worth it.

Amazing person who cares very much about the content and her students. The material is difficult, but that should be expected based on the i situation. If you want a professor who will challenge you and cares to see you succeed, this is the person for you.

Took AP Micro and AP Macro in HS. If you are serious about economics, I would avoid her. Wastes time, skips material and doesn't go in-depth during the lectures. I am doing fine in the class, but I have past econ experience. Kinda funny, but obnoxious overall. If you are new to econ, take Erbil. Despite my grade, I regret taking her. Not good.

The worst professor ever. Just an obnoxious person. She talks to the students like we are in preschool. When you have a test, suddenly you are expected to understand advanced ideas. The average on our second exam was 75%, which says a lot. If she is the only econ class open, take it next semester with different teachers. She should not be teaching.

Probably would not recommend, but also wouldn't strongly discourage someone from taking her class.  If you put in the work and are interested in the material you will do fine.  Grading curve can be absolutely brutal.

Love her!!! she is so funny and passionate about econ. Class was a big lecture that was structured with a Powerpoint. Only one homework assignment a week. Exams are not too hard but a lot of people get As so your grade can get curved down.

Dr. Chandini was a good professors. I took her while she was at the University of Arizona. She is friendly and willing to help. The class is pretty straight forward so long as you attend class, study, do the home-works, and attend her office hours for help. Overall, if you like economics, I would take her class.

Took her for principals of econ. The recorded lectures seemed to drag on, and were pretty low quality. There is weekly homework and discussion questions, as well as a discussion group. Not a hard class for an A, but you have to stay on top of things. Overall meh, no complaints I suppose.

Does negative curving. Try to avoid if you are trying to get a good grade. I had a 90 in the class but it ended up being a B because of negative curving. She is also apathetic. I am not mad at her. This is just my honest opinion. Good luck :)

I heard she was easy from a few friends, but this year she implemented an unforgiving harsh curve which PUSHED DOWN our grades. Her tests are too easy so everyone does well on them. However, only 30% of the class of 250 can get As so you have to do extremely well. She is a good teacher though, but the TA for your section grades everything.

She knows the material, but it does not matter because she is unengaging and boring. The class has not provided me with anything I could not find online. Curve at the end of the semester is brutal. Also, she really does not care about her students. She is self-righteous and fails to acknowledge that we also have our own lives.

Professor Chandini's lecture style is not really engaging, but not bad. The curve is crazy. I was expecting an A or a A- and maintained the grade throughout the semester, but I got a B in the end. The course is deceptively easy since the material is simple, but the curve is gonna pull you down if you don't put in more effort than its worth.
Prof Chandini is so cute. She is one of the few women Econ profs here so take her if you have the chance! She really wants her students to succeed.
Meaningless lectures and tests. Never listen to what she actually said but study the night before exams make me get an A
She is an amazing Professor. I learned a lot from her class. She is also really nice and cares about her students.

Professor Sankaran tries too hard to be engaging and fails miserably. She knows her stuff but can't explain it. The only reason why people come to class is because of "clicker" questions that count for attendance. It feels like she rather the entire class fail than pass. I was better off learning the textbook. To top it off, she is VERY arrogant.

Professor Tseng is a nice guy and he is passionate about the topics he teaches. He doesn't only teach the theory, but also tries to incorporate real-life examples and readings that relate what we do in class to the real world. The class is one of the most difficult classes I have taken at BC, but if you're willing to truly learn I recommend it!
ratingTags_Rating: Respected--Accessible outside class--Get ready to read

comment_Rating: I took Professor Tseng's Algorithms in the fall. He cares about his students and truly wants them to succeed. I would recommend taking him. Any algorithms class is hard, so expect this class to be no different. But take my word that he is a great professor.

I took Prof. Tseng's Algorithms (CSCI3383) and Distributed Systems (CSCI3359) at Boston College. I really liked his way of teaching, especially in Algorithms. For Distributed System, I think the subject itself was hard so I had trouble understanding materials in that course. But I really enjoyed his Algorithms course and I learned a lot.
nicest woman! gives good feedback and wants to see her students succeed. class was super interesting but readings can be a little long sometimes. Definitely take her if you can!

Highly recommend this professor for Freshman Lit core. She is a very generous grader, and the essays are all interesting and easy. I got by participating once a class, while not really doing the readings. Very light workload all things considered. Take this class if it works for your schedule.
One of the best choices for Lit Core. Reading can be heavy but managable, and Prof. Lane wants to help and gives good feedback on essays. Attendance mandatory. Would definitely take again.
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--Participation matters--Clear grading criteria

comment_Rating: Matus is a great teacher, don't let the reviews scare you. He is very funny and keeps lectures engaging despite some content being pretty boring. There are take-home online quizzes based on readings. Midterm and final were open note. His slideshows only have images so take good notes in class. Take advantage of lecture recordings for your notes.

Matus is a good guy who clearly cares about his students. Aware of the negative reviews and jokes about it, but ppl in class liked it. Take it with a few friends, will get high grades on the quizzes. Lectures were interesting and he didn't focus on how people lived and some of the crazy stories that happened in medieval times.
He was very understanding and accommodating to my medical needs. Loved his class. Make sure to introduce yourself to him!

Matus isn't nearly as bad as his ratings are. Both the midterm and final were open note, but he only projects pictures in his lectures so you have to take notes all by ear. We had 10 quizzes on readings, some easier than others, worth 45% of the final grade & the lowest was dropped. The course isn't the best, but it's definitely fair and doable.

Not terrible but not good either. His lectures were a bit disorganized and his slides basically had no info just pics. His quizzes were fine if you actually read the weekly books he sent. Tests were a bit difficult. Kind of too much for a core requirement but not the worst.

Matus honestly get a bad wrap. His lectures are not super interesting but the class is so easy. Biweekly canvas based quizzes on book that are actually interesting, and grades with a curve. Lecture attendance isn't mandatory but discussion sections are. No papers, super easy core. Give him a shot.
Mediocre class/professor.

Very disorganized class with little correlation between lectures. Professor Matus's lectures consist of him rambling for 50 minutes while presenting a few slide pictures that he probably found on google 20 minutes before class. In terms of actually learning medieval history, this class is about as useful as watching Game of Thrones.
Learned almost nothing about European history. Midterm and final were incredibly difficult, and his quizzes are totally unrelated to readings. Stupidly difficult for a history core. DO NOT TAKE.

His approach to European history was extremely different to what I have ever seen and that is what I think made class engaging. We discussed really odd topics like the specifics of the beaver trade instead of the traditional approach. If you take notes during lectures and go to the discussions (don't even need to participate) you should be fine.

Terrible all around. Lectures are strange and lack meaning. Tests are subjective and on little details from lecture. I learned nothing close to European History. Worst class I have ever taken in my whole academic career. TAs are also terrible and impossible to contact. DO NOT TAKE THIS COURSE!!!!
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Test heavy--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: I genuinely do not understand the hate for this prof. He is slow at grading, and usually contact with him is through TAs. Readings were long, but weekly quizzes were easy. Only two exams, and he just changed the 2nd from an exam to a short essay. Learned about super cool topics I have never learned about in any history class. Cool dude

Worst professor I have ever had. No direction in his course and he sits in front of the lecture mumbling for 50 minutes with no text on the slides. Impossible to go in contact with him outside of class unless you email him several times. Do not take this class or any with this Matus; take any history core besides this one.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Lecture heavy--Tough grader

comment_Rating: Incredibly confusing class and completely lacks logic and direction. All of the quizzes and tests are subjective and you basically have to guess his opinion. This is by far the hardest course I have taken and it is not at all worth it. Take any other history core! I do not know one student who liked this class. Emailed 6 times before he responded.

What some have described as an "interesting style" is really just Matus talking for 50 straight minutes about seemingly unimportant information. You are expected to read 200-300 page books biweekly, and the quizzes are awfully subjective. The tests aren't based on "big themes" of the class but instead small details from his lectures.

The reason everyone angry is because the first midterm was take home and online, so cheating was rampant which messed up the curve. However he quickly offered a reasonable make up. He has an interesting style, but you actually have to take good notes, read, and think. Most expected an easy A and are angry that an elite university class was hard.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Test heavy--Tough grader

comment_Rating: I accidentally killed my pet betta fish this year, and taking this class is still my biggest regret.

Class isn't hard, but the midterm and final make up quite a bit of the grade. The midterm and final are pretty tough, but the worst is how the only other grades are quizzes on whole books that you have to read. The quizzes are just a few obscure questions, and difficult to do well on. 10/10 do not recommend.
ratingTags_Rating: Graded by few things--Test heavy--Tough grader

comment_Rating: He is quite possibly the worst teacher I have ever had in my academic career from K-14th grade. He engages more in the act of flaunting his knowledge of Europe than he does teaching (relevant) material. Incredibly difficult grading, does not supplement tangents he calls lectures with notes or bullet points as a guideline, and is not accessible.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Test heavy--Tough grader

comment_Rating: No one seems to care about the class, and Prof. Matus doesn't seem to notice (or care) himself. Seemingly endless lectures about nonsense that has only left me more confused than when I began the course. Prepare to absolutely grind (400pg books biweekly) or cheat for an A (not endorsed), otherwise take it P/F. No available notes/references, either.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Lecture heavy--Tough grader

comment_Rating: he stands in the front of the class and mumbles about irrelevant stuff

By far the most unorganized and out of touch professor I've ever had. Began the semester pitching Europe in the World as an easy A if we did all the reading/attended lectures. Even his syllabus quiz was hard. The guy doesn't make deadlines for quizzes and makes them super hard with only subjective questions. DO NOT TAKE HIS CLASS!

You read a book and take a quiz every 2 weeks, which is an insanely quick pace. I know many people had to withdraw from this class because of how brutal the midterm was... do not reccomend at all.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Lecture heavy--Tough grader

comment_Rating: Do not take this class as your history core. Its ridiculously hard and everyone drops after the first exam. The way Prof. Matus teaches is fast paced and doesn't put notes or names behind him so 90% of the time you have no idea what he's talking about.
Unnecessarily difficult and strenuous for a core class. Would not recommend.

Hes a funny guy, but his lectures are really fast paced and no computers are allowed. Doesnt put any text on his slides or post notes. He deletes the lecture recordings and doesnt put them back up, so if you dont go you're screwed bc theres no textbook and the books are basically their own separate class. He will never respond to ur emails either!

She is a little soft-spoken and boring but she is so so sweet. Pretty easy grader and if you pay attention in class and do the homework you will succeed. She is always available if you need help outside of class too!

As someone who didn't take stats in high school this was a pretty challenging course. Pan is very kind though at times a bit impatient with questions. However she is an easy grader and definitely knows the topic well.
She is extremely sweet but the class periods are quite boring. Overall she teaches the content pretty well.

Professor Pan is the easiest business stats prof. The lectures are really boring especially since she talks super soft, but overall, the class isn't bad if you keep up with the weekly homework. Exams are pretty easy and are similar to the practice exam she gives you. she is an extremely generous grader.
Homework took me a long time to complete and often involved group work. Tests were reasonable and as long as you attend class you'll do fine.

Professor Pan is a great lecturer and knows what she's talking about. The only downside of having her is that she's very soft-spoken, so sitting through her class could make you tired. All in all, she's a solid teacher that is a good option for Business Stats at BC.

She's super nice. took stats in hs, so this course was relatively easy. It's going to be hard no matter professor, but her tests are as straightforward as it gets (if good at stats, think 92+ on exams). She's the nicest lady ever, class goes by quick, just slideshows but super relaxed.

The class can be a lot of information, especially if you've never taken a stats class before, but if you're willing to put in some work it's not that bad. She's very helpful in office hours so take advantage of that!
ratingTags_Rating: Group projects--Clear grading criteria--Lots of homework

comment_Rating: Lots of work at the beginning, as you have to learn R code. Gets easier and more enjoyable throughout the year. Homework takes a long time but not extremely challenging.

Pan is so sweet and you can tell she really cares about her students. She is always down to meet and even extends her office hours during exam season. I did horrible in the first exam but after going to office hours, participating, and even going to tutoring, I eventually got the hang of things. Just talk to her if you have any doubts.

She's a very sweet professor. She usually just reads off the slides that she made and posts them afterward, so she's definitely a more neutral-good teacher. Absolutely make sure you do the homework (even though there's a lot) because it'll help you understand the key concepts, and the textbook can help if you need to reference it.

BZAN is inherently a very difficult and work-heavy course, Pan is no exception here. She speaks quietly but is a pretty sweet person and good professor. When compared to other BZAN professors, I actually think she might be one of the easiest. Still difficult though.

This class was pretty solid. You dont really need to pay attention to the lectures, just read over the slides when she posts them. For the second half of the semester I would just do the weeks homework during class and look over the classes content later. I tanked the first exam, but once you figured out the class it was a cake walk
ratingTags_Rating: Group projects--Clear grading criteria--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: Professor Pan is very sweet and cares a lot about her students. She is always available for extra help. It's important to do textbook readings ahead of class to understand what is going on.
ratingTags_Rating: Accessible outside class--Clear grading criteria--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: Class is pretty much just lecture, with some coding that she assigns, and then goes over. Coding is manageable, you just need to pay attention. HW wasn't really a thing, just some prep for quizzes, which you should do. Quizzes emphasized small points from class, so know specifics. Exams were fine if you study. Group project is also pretty simple.
ratingTags_Rating: Graded by few things--Clear grading criteria--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: Prof. Smith is a wholesome down-to-earth man. He is talented in relaying his lessons and willing to do review sessions and meet during office hours before exams. He is also a good advisor for your first year.
Smith is a great portico prof. He really knows his stuff and is great with explaining things. Beware of tedious group projects that take up a lot of your grade. Tests are harder than they may seem.

Genuinely one of the kindest, most caring professors I have ever met, he was always accommodating and extremely willing to help you for even the slightest bit of confusion. His assignments, including exams, are very fair and not particularly difficult. The group projects/presentations can be a bit difficult. He fosters great class discussions.
Professor Smith is passionate about portico and loved facilitating discussions and keeping the class engaged! You are so lucky if you get him as a portico teacher!

Professor Smith is one of the most insightful and caring professors at Boston College. This guy will really challenge you and make you think hard about not only business ethics but your own ethics as well. This guy is what makes portico so special, amazing professor.
Best portico professor and an amazing guy. Definitely take him.

Best portico professor!!!! Super caring and reachable to students outside class. You can tell he genuinely enjoys his job. In-class discussions were always interesting even if the readings were not. Gave great feedback on presentations.

Awesome guy. So nice. Classes are engaging and participation does matter so speak when you can. Try and form good relationships with your classmates and TAs. Will help you down the road and with the group projects (presentations) throughout.

Professor Smith was my favorite professor during the first semester of freshman year. He's extremely lenient with deadlines and will almost always give you extensions on assignments. Exams are a little tricky, so make sure you really understand the readings and concepts. Definitely the best portico teacher.
Really interesting. Makes class enjoyable and engaging. Really tough A but almost guaranteed B

Professor Smith was a great Portico professor! His dog Attie was the main attraction for many of the classes this semester. He always demonstrated an open mind in terms of providing extensions to students in terms of finishing writing assignments and other tasks. Highly recommend taking him as a professor at BC.

Professor Smith would be the professor I would choose if I had to choose a professor to have all 4 years of undergrad. He is caring, accessible, and passionate about what he teaches. There is a lot of readings to do for his class but he covers everything so thoroughly and he loves answering any questions or any comments.

Professor Smith is an amazing professor, one that I wish I could have all four years of my education at BC. He is an amazing teacher because he covers everything in detail and answers ANY question. He loves participation and hearing diff. perspectives. He is very caring and passionate about what he teaches.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Caring--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: Great guy and lecturer, cares about us as people, pretty easy grader. Would 100% recommend.
professor smith is amazing! had him for portico and 10/10. he genuinely cares about his students and that is one of the best things about him.
Absolutely loved his class. Highly suggest if you have the opportunity to take him!
Take this man for portico, you will not regret it. Put simply he cares so much about the students and the material. Take him!
Professor Smith is a great professor, and has the ability to easily explain difficult concepts. He is kind, accessible outside of class, and genuinely cares about his students.
One of the kindest professors Ive ever had, if you have the opportunity to take Prof Smith, definitely do it
Very philosophy-based lecture, but is good with grading (seems like he hates grading at times and gives students the upper hand).
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--GROUP PROJECTS

comment_Rating: I had him for perspectives my freshman year, and he was incredible. Could not recommend the guy more.

Lots of group discussions in class, is clear about what will be on exams and homeworks, overall a great professor. Beyond just academics, the conversations you'll have in this class are excellent. Highly reccomend.

Had him for Perspectives my freshmen year. Overall really caring, passionate, and engaging  Professor. He made the material interesting and really seemed to care about his students and what we had to say. I wouldnt say hes an easy grader, but as long as you participate in class discussions and engage with the material youll do well.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Gives good feedback

comment_Rating: Prof Storey puts a lot of effort and care into the class, very nice guy, just be prepared to spend a LOT of time reading some very dense material. One of the only philosophy professors (to my knowledge) that uses powerpoints during the lecture which I found very helpful since complicated ideas are always being discussed!
ratingTags_Rating: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--Participation matters

comment_Rating: What can I say? Just an amazing professor. Cares about her students and is very passionate. You can always feel free to reach out to her. She's not an easy A professor, but once you put in a decent effort, promise me that you will be fine for sure.

Professor Bernhard cares more about what you can take away from the course than how much of the content you actually memorize. The multiple choice parts of tests were open note. She makes lectures very engaging and applicable to students' lives. Loved this course.
She is harder than other professors. Good teacher but the rest are an easier A.
Nice teacher, basically reads from a script for her portion of MMW. Class is really hard but interesting.

She is super laid back and easy to work with. She clearly cares and will definitely help you out if you ask. Her lectures definitely covered a lot but overall the class wasn't too bad and she always kept it casual. I would definitely recommend her.
Amazing teacher.
Father Rivera Castro is really nice and wants to see you do well. If you show effort in the class it can definitely help with your final grade.

Professor Rivera truly cares about his students and wants to see them do well. His lectures helped to understand difficult texts and his weekly assignments helped us understand if we understood the reading or not. While there was a lot of readings, I still liked his class and would take him again.
Amazing in almost every way. Can't be bullied, threatened, intimidated or blackmailed. Strong, honest and sure.

Despite being a well known liberal figure, Pakman respects everyone and keeps his own progressive views to a minimum. He is very willing to help out those in need, and he is accessible outside of class. Overall a great guy and I highly recommend you take this course.
Absolutely fantastic class and professor.
ratingTags_Rating: Participation matters--Skip class? You won't pass.--Inspirational

comment_Rating: Very good at breaking down the subject and making it understandable even if you've never taken a Comp Sci class. Problem sets are really tough but exams aren't bad.
Amazing at explaining things and takes the time to break down concepts. Would definitely take her again.
Easy to follow and understand. Very generous with her time during office hours. ����������

It's unfortunate because Evrenk is a really nice professor in class and in office hours, but the way he runs his class is awful. I was constantly stressed about pop quizzes. Exams are nothing like we have seen before. He overcomplicated easy concepts. I wish he would understand students don't learn well under those conditions. Don't recommend.

Great person. Not so much of a great professor. While the concepts taught in class make sense in theory, the application of them on quizzes, tests, and problem sets have no connection with each other. Grades on a scale with tests being nearly impossible. The material you are tested on will not be familiar to you. Many better options for Econ 2201.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Beware of pop quizzes--Test heavy

comment_Rating: Prof. Evrenk is very nice and caring, but this does not mean he is a good professor. Three stressful random pop quizzes, challenging midterm, final, and participation grade make the class overwhelming. Avoid unless you want constant stress. Class average is a B-.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Participation matters--Beware of pop quizzes

comment_Rating: Evrenk is caring about his students and often asks if the class has question. He tries to explain concepts in multiple ways, but this class is very hard. His quizzes include info we don't talk about in class to see if we can apply what we learned elsewhere. He grades very strictly, taking off points for minor mistakes. Hard class decent teacher.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Beware of pop quizzes--Lecture heavy

comment_Rating: Conflicting character for me. On one hand, he is a very good lecturer with some of the best blackboard writing and drawing I have had. On the other hand, there was very little structure to go back and review content that was covered prior and you never knew what was going to come up in the next lecture. Would take again but not for everyone.

his tests and pop quizzes are VERY hard, going beyond the scope of what's taught. class consists of him asking us if we have questions, which i appreciate, but then he rambles and scribbles on the blackboard. comment_Rating: Simply busy work. No actual information being taught in any of her labs. This is the main reason the BC Chemistry department is hated by freshman.

comment_Rating: You'll have to have her for GenChem lab, which she supervises but is taught by graduate TAs. Nothing good about it, but prepare for the suffering and you might survive.

Lynne's instructions on the lab are incredibly unclear and the post labs are so difficult and pointless as they have nothing to do with what is learned in class. She is in charge of every chem lab so unfortunately as a pre-med you have to deal with her. Prepare yourself if you are entering Gen Chem because lab is harder than the course itself.

Prof O'Connell runs the most vague and frustrating lab. The instructions in the post-lab are often incredibly confusing, and leave students wondering if they've completed the assignment correctly. Pre and post-labs feel like busy work rather than learning. As a freshman, it's disappointing that this is my 1st lab experience.

BUSY WORK! There is far too much useless, nonsensical fluff that students are forced to do that are extremely time consuming and worthless (especially given that Labs are 1 credit co-requisite courses). She is the facilitator of all Chemistry labs so there isn't even a way to avoid her if you are a STEM student.
ratingTags_Rating: Lots of homework--Skip class? You won't pass.--Beware of pop quizzes

comment_Rating: Prof. O'Connell is probably one of the worst people in the entirety of Boston College. Every single lab is passionless, and written with incredibly frustrating, and vague instructions. This class is purely to meet requirements, and not much learning gets done. The post-lab and pre-lab assignments are pure busy work, and can take up to 3-4 hours.
ratingTags_Rating: Skip class? You won't pass.--Group projects--Beware of pop quizzes

comment_Rating: Had Prof. Allgood for financial accounting; it was a very good experience overall. He managed to make what can be a very dry subject engaging and easy to understand. There was quite a bit of homework but only graded for completion. Expectations for exams were clear and he held extra office hours to review for them.
ratingTags_Rating: Clear grading criteria--Lots of homework--Accessible outside class

comment_Rating: engaging lectures, interesting readings, accessible teacher. solid class.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Clear grading criteria--Gives good feedback

comment_Rating: Although the class is interesting, I don't think I would recommend him as a professor. His grading criteria is so arbitrary. I got As on every assignment but somehow ended up with an A- in the course. He also doesn't give any feedback so you don't even know where you went wrong. But as long as you pay a little bit of attention you should be good.
ratingTags_Rating: Participation matters--Lecture heavy--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: He comes off as intimidating, but is really a great professor who goes out of his way to make sure that the lesson is fully understood by all students. He truly cares about the subject matter and it is clear to see during class. There is weekly readings but considering the class meets once a week they're very manageable. Would definitely recommend!

Although there are a lot of readings for the class, you don't need to do them on time to participate in the lectures. He can be a bit corny at times, but he's very passionate. Exams and papers are also easy if you pay attention and read.

I loved Professor Concepcion and his RLR class. While it was very reading heavy, they aren't necessarily mandatory to participate and do well in class. The topic and content of the class are absolutely amazing and in-depth. My one warning is that sometimes it seems like the class doesn't have a planned direction and can go off on tangents.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: Do not take this class
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Graded by few things

comment_Rating: Knowledgeable, loves the material, and cares a lot. Problem is that he loves it too much - strict, uptight, and expects you to be in love with theology like he is. Lots of readings, exams are oral, quizzes weekly, book list $300+. Very nice person, though you should take another professor and get the same grade doing half the work.
ratingTags_Rating: Tough grader--Get ready to read--Participation matters

comment_Rating: He makes Philosophy fun and his class consists of conversation that can often show his very witty sense of humor.  Be prepared to read and participation is necessary. Two oral exams and two papers take up most of your grade. Lenient grader willing to help and answer any questions in office hours to help you succeed!
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Clear grading criteria

comment_Rating: Professor Berger's classes are very challenging yet very rewarding. Prepare to read a lot. Participation is a big deal. He is a fair grader, but do expect to have to put forth a lot of effort in order to receive a good grade. He does seem to genuinely care about his students, and his knowledge and passion for philosophy is evident in his lectures.

Professor Berger really grows on you. He seems intense at first, but really has a sense of humor and actually cares about his students. He is very smart, but does expect you to have a ton of background knowledge. Assigns a lot of homework. He is clear about expectations for assignments and is tough, but not impossible.
This is the worst class I have ever taken in my whole life. Never take this class. So much stupid work for no reason. The final paper makes literally no sense. Dacia doesn't help.

Dacia is a fine professor. Applications of Learning Theory is not a class you need to attend ever. The content is completely useless. Additionally, you need to submit samples of annotated notes, readings, and all these different charts EVERY SINGLE WEEK for every class. The work is so pointless and there is so much of it. AVOID THIS CLASS.
ratingTags_Rating: Get ready to read--Lots of homework

comment_Rating: One of the most caring professors I have ever met. Her classes are very interesting. The course is worth taking.

Dacia is a must have professor. Shes super chill but youll still learn a lot in an engaging way. She loves getting to know her students and shes open to feedback about any and everything. If you ever need help with anything, Dacia is your girl!!!

I took freshman writing seminar with her and it was great. grading policy is vague, basically you just have to show improvement from your first paper to get an A. no busy work, everything that we did had a purpose. teacher is very accessible. loved getting to know her through mandatory writing conferences once a week. great teacher not too serious
Dacia is a great professor. She really takes the time to get to know her students, and she is very helpful in class. Also, she never gives busy work or anything that will not actually help us.
Really chill and personable. Kind of a hard grader for papers, which you would never expect from how easy she makes the class.

She is the nicest professor and so caring toward her students! Had her for Lit Core and she made class fun and engaging. There is a lot of reading and essays, but she is flexible with deadlines. Participation and discussions matter for your grade! But they are always a good time :)
Highly recommend! Not only because the lectures are great, but because he's the Channing Tatum of Boston College... No exaggeration.

This professor was awesome! Looked forward to his class all week! He brought in awesome guest lectures and was very knowledgeable himself. Best professor I've had so far. It doesn't hurt that he's a flaming hot pepper :).

The class she teaches is the most uninteresting class you will ever take. The assignments she gives are pointless because she makes you do a peer review several times throughout the class but you cannot revise your paper after the peer review so its kind of pointless. Her grading is hard to follow because she doesn't use a rubric.
HE IS AMAZING. The best professor I've had at BC. So kind and always brings flowers and snacks to class for us :) I would take this class every semester. Highly, highly, recommend him and this class!

Took this class because there were no options for macro, my biggest mistake. He cold calls, does not teach (told us to learn how to read the textbook because he simply didn't want to teach), and assigns at least two textbook homework per week. He doesn't make his slides and gets it from the 300$ required textbook. he told us today to suck it up.
